<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusAccidents     05-19 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Accidents,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Hurt when School Buses Overturn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus overturned on a curve and plunged down an
embankment Thursday, injuring 60 people returning from a church
outing in Pennsylvania, and more than 20 fifth-graders were injured
in a school bus crash in Albion, Iowa, authorities said.
   No one was killed in either accident, and authorities said most
injuries apparently were bruises, cuts and broken bones.
   Police said the bus carrying a group from the Walnut Street
Christian School in Jersey Shore, Penn., was returning from an
outing in Harrisburg when it overturned on a sharp curve known in
Jersey Shore as ``Devil's Elbow.''
   At least two adults and one child were admitted to a hospital
after the 4:45 p.m. accident.
   Children on the bus appeared to be between the ages of 6 and 12,
observers at the scene of the accident said. Twelve ambulances took
them, their chaperones and the bus driver to three hospitals.
   In Iowa, 58 fifth-graders from Lowell Elementary school in
Waterloo and several chaperones were returning from a field trip
near Des Moines, when their bus slipped onto a soft shoulder and
overturned south of Albion.
   ``The injuries don't appear to be that serious,'' said Omar
Voran, administrator of the Marshalltown Medical and Surgical
Center, where at least 20 students were treated in the emergency
room.
</TEXT>
