<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PoliceFire 1stLd-Writethru a0832 05-19 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0832,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Erupts In 8-Story Police Headquarters Downtown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with fire out, casualties, police phone
service still available; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out Thursday night at the
eight-story downtown headquarters of the Kansas City Police
Department, knocking out 911 emergency service and forcing
evacuation of the building, officials said.
   At least seven people were taken to hospitals and several others
were treated for smoke inhalation at the scene, officials said.
Firefighters brought the blaze under control about 9:55 p.m., two
hours after it was reported.
   About 60 people were working in the building, police spokeswoman
Sgt. Laura Mulloy said. About 40 prisoners were evacuated from the
city jail on the eighth floor of the building and taken to the
basement of Municipal Court, she said.
   The city's 911 emergency service was out of order because of the
blaze, officials said, but four phone lines were open to the public
to reach police in case of emergency.
   The four-alarm blaze was reported about 7:45 p.m. on the
building's fifth floor, said fire department spokesman Capt. Joe
Galetti. The office of Police Chief Larry Joyner is located on the
fifth floor.
   ``There was some redecorating going on in the chief's office,
I'm told,'' Galetti said, adding that the blaze was reported by
construction workers. floor.
   Smoke poured from windows of the fifth, sixth and seventh
floors, witnesses said, and several firefighters trapped by fire on
the fifth floor were rescued by ladder, officials said.
</TEXT>
