<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeedOff     05-19 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teed Off,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Dealership Sues Golf Course After Errant Swings Damage Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a car dealership that
sells expensive sports cars are teed off about their neighbors, a
miniature golf course where they say some players take too-hefty
swings.
   Golf balls have been clearing a 30-foot-high net between
Golfland USA and Porsche Motorsport for years, said Ken Boswell,
the car dealership's general manager.
   But the last straw, he said, was when a brass putter also flew
over the fence and smashed the windshield of a Porsche 911
convertible. The putter, which also scratched a Porsche 928 on the
rebound, caused $3,000 in damage, Boswell said.
   As a result, the dealership filed a lawsuit Tuesday against
Golfland in Santa Clara County Superior Court. It asks for
unspecified damages, contending Porsche Motorsport has suffered
thousands of dollars in losses because of the errant golfers.
   The manager on duty at Golfland on Wednesday referred phone
calls to owner Robert Kenney, who could not be reached for comment.
Kenney's wife, Geri, said Wednesday the couple had not seen the
lawsuit, but added that they had done everything possible to
prevent balls from going onto adjacent property.
   Boswell believes most of the wayward balls come from a hole
where golfers must hit up a ramp to reach the cup.
   ``They must treat the hole like they're on a driving range,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
