<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Pravda     05-19 0125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Pravda,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German-Language Edition Of Pravda Goes On Sale In Vienna</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A German-language edition of the Soviet
Communist Party newspaper Pravda has gone on sale in Vienna.
   The paper, which appeared on newstands on Wednesday, will have
an initial daily circulation of 15,000, Christoph Raabe, who heads
the company issuing the newspaper in German-speaking countries, was
quoted as saying.
   According to the Austria Press Agency, Raabe expects a deficit
of $590,000 by the end of the year but hopes to break even by the
end of 1989.
   Pravda is to appear daily, but Sunday and Monday editions will
be combined. Prospective readers include companies doing business
with Eastern Europe as well as institutions and associations
interested in Soviet bloc events.
</TEXT>
