<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FarewellParty     05-19 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farewell Party,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Getting Wish Posthumously: A Piano Dropped From The Sky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his lifetime, John Cameron Young
had a secret wish, an unusual fantasy: He wondered what an airborne
piano would sound like crashing to earth. Now, a bit late, his
friends will find out.
   The Marin County man was 44 when he died three years ago,
leaving an $800,000 estate. In his will, Young, whose life was full
of adventure and fun-loving behavior, left $15,000 to three buddies
who were instructed to toss one last party for their departed
friend.
   The professional guitar player told his friends to ``give a
party for themselves and as many of my friends as they can find
that desire to attend.''
   As told by Young's friends, the Mississippi native moved to the
San Francisco Bay area in 1972. He sang Delta blues and found time
to be a parachutist, pilot, storyteller and business success with
six furniture stores.
   It took three years to straighten out Young's will, and on May
28, hundreds of folks are expected to gather for the memorial
celebration.
   They will indulge Young's strange fantasy _ listening to a
300-pound piano crash to the ground from a hovering helicopter.
   ``He talked about that all the time,'' said Harry Murphy, 53, a
Fairfax graphic designer who met Young in a San Anselmo saloon 10
years ago. ``He'd sit here and say, `Harry, we've got to have a
piano drop. Can you hear it? ... You take an old upright piano
about 1,000 feet in the sky ...'''
   Murphy mused over that, and added fondly, ``... I think he'll be
able to hear it.''
   Murphy said a helicopter will drop an inlaid walnut upright from
50 to 100 feet near Sonoma County Airport.
   ``It's an arrogant, outrageous, playful, childish thing to do,''
said Murphy. ``That embodies J.C.''
   About four hours after the smash, the celebration will turn to a
more sedate mood with food, drink and music in Marin.
   Friends said the sendoff fits in with Young's life. He once
drove a motorcycle into a bar and ordered a beer with an olive.
   However, Young was far from a clown. He had a master's degree in
mathematics, and often dragged bar patrons into conversations about
negative numbers and mind-twisting theorems.
   His death was as unusual as his life. His body was discovered in
his black Cadillac in a ravine below a steep highway near Stinson
Beach. Authorities said he may have been beaten to death.
   ``He was full of life and I miss him,'' said real estate broker
Richard Catlett, who met young in a bar in Spain in 1972.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
