<DOCNO> AP880519-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Autos-Future     05-19 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Autos-Future,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Automakers' Crash Diets Leading To Lasting Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers are replacing their
crash diets of the early '80s with more lasting changes to prepare
for challenge of the next decade: overproduction.
   By 1990 there could be 5.6 million more new cars and trucks than
buyers worldwide, according to industry estimates.
   ``First, obviously, cost-cutting was the major concern ... But
in the long term it's the products they're coming out with'' that
will determine who survives, said Kathleen Heaney, an analyst with
Nikko Securities in New York.
   Having modernized their factories and corporate structures, the
Big Three are marshaling their resources with the aim of making
American cars that are better engineered and sell like Japanese
cars.
   The dollar's slide against the Japanese yen and European
currencies two years ago has made some imports more expensive and
temporarily helped level the playing field for General Motors
Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
   So has a new United Auto Workers pattern contract that stresses
job security over wage increases and gives the companies needed
flexibility.
   The auto industry tumult of the past 15 years _ fuel crises, a
recession and the shock of Japanese entry _ has given way to a more
stable market where winners and losers no longer are determined by
national origin.
   Ford, losing $1 million a day at the beginning of the decade,
has made big adjustments already, closing excess plants and running
the rest on overtime while grabbing styling leadership from GM with
a sleek, aerodynamic new lineup.
   ``People who go into a Ford dealership have a car in mind. They
say `I want that Thunderbird, Taurus, Continental','' Heaney said.
``People are not doing that for GM. ... They're going to a GM
dealer and saying: `I've got $13,000. What can I get?'''
   Ford led U.S. automakers in earnings in 1986 and went on to set
the world auto industry record with $4.6 billion in 1987 profits
and again with $1.6 billion in earnings in the first quarter of
1988. It also has a comfortable $10 billion cash cushion it is
saving for a major electronics acquisition.
   At its annual meeting last week, Ford Chairman Donald Petersen
said the second largest U.S. automaker has no intention of giving
up its edge and will substantially increase spending on new product
development over the next few years.
   Chrysler, under Chairman Lee Iacocca, also has switched its
focus from trimming costs to investing in new products.
   Chrysler had been shedding weight gained in its August
acquisition of ailing American Motors Corp. After squeezing more
Jeeps out of a former AMC assembly plant in Toledo, Ohio, Chrysler
decided to close AMC's other U.S. assembly plant, in Kenosha, Wis.,
by year's end.
   It also settled its UAW contract five months early, eliminating
the chance of a costly strike in September when its factories will
be pushing out 1989 models.
   Chrysler's strategy of aggressive pricing to gain market share
at the expense of immediate profits has boosted sales during 1988,
including a 72 percent jump for Jeeps and a 55 percent increase for
minivans.
   Iacocca, who faces his shareholders Thursday in New York,
already has injected extra money into research and development for
new models and advanced engineering this year and plans more.
   GM, which spent $50 billion since the early 1980s to modernize
or replace its factories, is also channeling resources into new
product development, but analysts say it has more problems to solve.
   The world's largest automaker is barely breaking even on its
U.S. car and truck business despite cost-cutting, which may make
additional plant closings necessary.
   Analysts also question Chairman Roger Smith's pledge to regain
lost market share. To move eight points to 45 percent of the
market, GM would have to increase sales by at least 1.2 million
cars and trucks a year. GM lost market share in 1986 to Ford and
Chrysler as well as to foreign makers.
   And the field of competitors only grows thicker.
   Mazda, which joined the ranks of Japanese makers with U.S.
plants, has sold out its Michigan plant's production through
October. Toyota's huge Kentucky plant will begin making Camry
sedans this summer and a Chrysler-Mitsubishi plant in Illinois soon
will be churning out sporty 1989 models.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EconomicAnxiety     05-19 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economic Anxiety,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Why The Seers Say `Bah, Humbug' To Strong Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the U.S. trade deficit for March improved
beyond all expectations, many economists and big investors
responded with a chorus of ``Bah, humbug.''
   Funny they should pan what would seem like fabulous news. But
they've done it before and most likely they'll do it again.
   They responded that way to news of a lower jobless rate, to
increases in factory use, even to the dollar's new stability.
   It is a strange, discomfiting world in which good is bad, happy
is sad, up is down, square is round, best is worst, last is first,
strong is weak, bottom is peak, rich is poor and less is more.
   And if the sages are being spooked by the ``good'' news _ news
for which they've waited months and which they deemed necessary for
economic survival _ it's no wonder they're exaggerating ``bad''
news, of which they've found plenty.
   Late last year, for instance, the pessimists said consumers
would reduce spending, forcing the economy into recession. It
didn't happen. Then they said an inventory glut might produce
recession in 1988. But the glut disappeared.
   ``It is ironic that the pessimistic crowd see a boom just as
bloated inventories are starting to cool things off,'' said
economist Edward Yardeni of the Prudential-Bache investment firm,
who fears neither a boom nor a bust.
   Throughout, there has been wide disagreements among economists,
some of whom believed the biggest threat was from recession, others
that inflation would turn out to be the big problem.
   Whatever the interpretation, however, the conclusion has been
the same, i.e., bad news. If the economy expanded it would strain
production facilities and produce inflation. Should expansion
cease, recession would follow.
   The dramatic improvement in the nation's trade deficit _ a $4
billion reduction to $9.7 billion in March _ provides the most
vivid example of the syndrome.
   Nothing economic has been more eagerly awaited in recent months,
since a shrinkage of the deficit means U.S. goods, especially
manufactured items, are becoming more competitive abroad.
   In fact, many economists and investors made the latest trade
figures the fulcrum of their analyses. When the deficit grew in
February, the stock market plunged. Would a gain in March make the
market rise?
   It didn't happen. Once again the news, though opposite to that
of February, produced a negative reaction. Both the bond and stock
markets interpreted the news as indicative of an economy about to
overheat and produce inflation.
   ``It seems the better things get, the worse they're going to
be,'' quipped Malcolm Forbes, the publisher, who was addressing a
business luncheon group shortly after hearing the news.
   Why the mood?
   Economists themselves have been asking that question, and most
have defended their positions with data and theories that to the
layman seem thorough, reasonable and even sagacious.
   While recognizing that pessimism may be justified _ and that
inflation, high interest rates and perhaps recession lie ahead _
some economists believe there is a large psychological element
involved.
   In fact, with so many disproportions and dislocations in the
economy _ big budget and trade deficits, uncollectable Third World
loans, and the crash of the securities markets in October _ no
matter how poor or inaccurate an analysis might be, a negative
forecast stands a chance of being correct.
   There are also the awful memories of the 1970s to contend with.
Economists back then couldn't believe what was happening _ that
inflation and interest rates were not just high but in the double
digits. They cannot forget.
   And, finally, anxiety is produced by the very expansion itself.
Now in its 66th month, it has lived far beyond the usual lifespan
of expansions, and inevitably will turn down. But when? And will
inflation or recession end it?
   H. Erich Heinemann, chief economist for Ladenburg, Thalmann &
Co., a securities broker-dealer, remains optimistic, at least about
inflation. He notes that major inflation indicators rose less in
the first quarter of 1988 than in the final quarter of 1987.
   His forecast contrasts with that of most economists.
   ``We're convinced that with just a little bit of luck, the
expansion could continue into 1991 or 1992,'' he says, adding the
caveat:
   ``However, this will be a respite, not a reprieve. If Washington
cannot deal with its problems (mainly the budget deficit), we will
all have to live with the consequences.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: John Cunniff has covered business and economic
issues for The Associated Press since 1964.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
