<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HastingsProfile     05-19 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings Profile,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hastings Takes Fighting Image To Impeachment Hearings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hastings-Impeach, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Alcee Hastings and his
supporters see him as a courageous, outspoken fighter now taking
unfair shots from those who cannot accept him as the first black
federal judge in Florida.
   Hastings, whose impeachment hearing began Wednesday in Congress,
has been battling bribery and conspiracy charges for the last seven
years.
   But he has remained a popular figure in South Florida's black
community, which has held impassioned demonstrations in his support
and contributed $65,000 to his legal defense.
   ``He's never been the kind to back down from a fight; he's had
to pull himself up from his bootstraps from day one,'' said Dr.
Gordon Merritt, a Fort Lauderdale dentist and longtime friend who
helped raise funds for Hastings. ``Most federal judges are the
placating type, but Alcee speaks out _ he's a maverick.''
   The flamboyant Hastings has proclaimed his innocence ever since
he was indicted on bribery charges in 1981 and then acquitted two
years later.
   The case didn't end there. Fellow judges accused Hastings of
obstructing justice and lying under oath, and issued a report
recommending his impeachment.
   ``I'm not going to be impeached and I'm not going to be
removed,'' Hastings said in a recent interview. ``It's pure
unadulterated politics.''
   Hastings, in sermon-like speeches around the country, has
blasted the secret judicial investigation after his acquittal as a
``witchhunt'' and an unconstitutional ``throwback to Star
Chamberism.''
   He has suggested his race has had something to do with the
effort against him, and said he really angered Justice Department
officials with his 1981 rulings blocking deportation of Haitian
immigrants.
   Complaints were filed against him in 1984 for his alleged
improper political statements, including harsh criticism of the
Reagan administration. Hastings said his position on the federal
bench does not mean he can't speak his mind.
   ``I don't have any organized effort,'' said Hastings, who added
he has also spent much of his own money. ``It's draining me
financially. It's impacting me from an emotional standpoint _ I'm
tired from all this mess.''
   His 70-year-old mother Mildred, with whom Hastings, 51, has
shared a Lauderhill apartment since his second divorce, said her
son would come out of the hearings fine and ``he doesn't need me to
talk for him.''
   The only child of a maid and butler in Altamonte Springs, a
small town north of Orlando, Hastngs earned his law degree at
predominantly black Florida A&M University, became a civil rights
leader, and ran unsuccessfully for office several times.
   In 1970, he was the first black man to run for the U.S. Senate
from Florida, but failed to win nomination.
   He returned to his private law practice, where he did much free
work in civil rights cases, until 1979, when President Jimmy Carter
appointed him to the federal bench.
</TEXT>
