<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--North Korea,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Students Favor Talks Between North and South</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 North Korean students attended a
rally in that country to support proposed talks between student
leaders from north and south Korea, an official news report said.
   Students from more than 150 colleges and universities in the
Pyongyang area attended the rally in a stadium in that capital on
Tuesday, according to a report by the north's Korean Central News
Agency, which was monitored in Tokyo.
   The report said the students formed a preparatory committee for
north-south student talks comprised of 30 representatives of
different schools.
   At a rally in Seoul, South Korea, on Saturday, 10,000 students
proposed that student leaders from the south and north meet June 10
to discuss national unification and co-hosting of the Olympic Games
in South Korea in September.
   South Korean officials have said they would not allow such a
meeting.
</TEXT>
