<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul music legend James Brown spent the night
in jail on charges of drug possession and fleeing from police after
his wife again complained he was abusing her.
   The 55-year-old singer, known to fans as the ``Godfather of
Soul,'' was charged Wednesday with failure to stop for police,
resisting arrest, assault against an officer and illegal possession
of a revolver, police said.
   Later in the day, Brown was charged with possession of the drug
PCP after tests on a substance found in his car.
   Deputies were dispatched to Brown's Beech Island home Wednesday
after his wife, Adrienne, went to a neighbor's house and said he
was abusing her, said Aiken County Sheriff Carrol Heath.
   When officers arrived, Brown sped away in his car but was
overtaken 1{ miles away, Heath said.
   Brown told officers he was late for an appointment, the sheriff
said. A scuffle ensued, but no injuries were reported. Brown
remained jailed Wednesday night.
   On April 4, Brown was charged with assault with the intent to
murder, aggravated assault and battery after allegedly beating his
wife with a pipe. He also was charged with firing a gun into a car
while she was inside.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisa Bonet, who plays Cosby kid college
student in NBC-TV's ``A Different World'' but has raised eyebrows
by posing nude, is pregnant, a network spokesman said.
   Six months ago, Miss Bonet married musician Romeo Blue, also
known as Lenny Kravitz.
   There was no immediate word on how the pregnancy of the
20-year-old actress would affect her role in the series, according
to a statement Wednesday from NBC spokesman Bob Meyers. The show, a
spinoff of ``The Cosby Show,'' was rated No. 2 for the season,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co.
   During her career on ``The Cosby Show'' and ``A Different
World,'' Miss Bonet has raised eyebrows by twice posing nude in
magazines and starring in the movie ``Angel Heart,'' which barely
escaped an ``X'' rating for its torrid love scenes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conductor Gunther Herbig, saying money problems
have cramped his style as music director of the Detroit Symphony
Orchestra, is heading north to take over the same job with the
Toronto Symphony.
   Wednesday's announcement was seen as a serious blow to Detroit's
cultural community and a coup for Toronto's.
   Herbig, 56, has been music director in Detroit since 1984.
During that time, he appeared as guest conductor with major
orchestras in Europe and the United States.
   He said lack of money for expansion, recordings and tours led
him to leave Detroit, where the orchestra went on strike last year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino
became a father for the second time when his wife gave birth to a
son at Hialeah Hospital.
   The healthy boy, born Wednesday, weighed in at 9 pounds, 3
ounces, and measured 21{ inches, said Eddie White, spokesman for
the Dolphins.
   Marino, 26, and his wife, Claire, have not yet picked out a
name, White said.
   The baby's big brother, Daniel Charles, is 20 months old.
   Marino has been an All-Pro at quarterback each of his five years
in the National Football League.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankees second baseman Willie Randolph
says he has regular conferences with his kids, while actor-singer
Kris Kristofferson modestly claims he only had the good taste to
pick the right mothers.
   Whatever their secrets, the two were among eight men honored
Wdnesday as 1988's outstanding fathers by the National Father's Day
Committee.
   Randolph, who spends half the baseball season on the road, says
he has to work at keeping communication lines open with his four
children.
   ``We have conferences,'' Randolph said. ``We dim the lights and
just talk. You'd be amazed at the off-the-wall stuff. They can say
whatever they want.''
   Kristofferson, who has six children by three wives and three
adopted Salvadoran orphans, said, ``I had the good taste to select
mothers who would raise them. All I've done is love them.''
   Apparently love was enough, because all nine children now live
with him and his current wife, Lisa, at their Malibu, Calif., home.
   Other fathers honored were NBC White House correspondent Chris
Wallace, FBI Director William Sessions, Fox Television sportscaster
Bill Mazer, Tennis Hall of Famer Arthur Ashe, New York City police
officer Steven McDonald, who was left paralyzed in a shooting, and
broadcast personality Larry King.
   Father's Day is June 19th.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND FORKS, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To journalist Rick Reilly, North Dakota
conjurs up images of ``desolation, tundra, one two-lane highway.''
But movie reviewer Judith Crist says she thinks of a state full of
``bright, no-nonsense people.''
   Reilly, a writer for Sports Illustrated, and Crist, a reviewer
for TV Guide, were among notables who responded recently to a
questionnaire about North Dakota sent by the tiny senior class of
Willow City High School.
   The eight seniors were miffed when Kellye Cash said her Miss
America 1987 title gave her the chance to visit places ``you never
thought people actually lived _ like North and South Dakota.''
   So they decided to find out what other celebrities thought of
North Dakota.
   ``It's fun to see what other people's impressions are, but I
don't think it changed (the class members') minds,'' said their
teacher, Peggy Gregg. ``They're all proud to live in North Dakota.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressman Nick Joe Rahall has
pleaded guilty to reduced charges stemming from a drunken driving
arrest, the city district attorney's office said.
   Rahall, a West Virginia Democrat, was arrested Jan. 14 after
giving a speech to the Tobacco Institute near this resort
community. He opted for the reduced charges at a pretrial
conference Wednesday.
