<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Threat 6thLd-Writethru a0994 05-19 1019</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Threat, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0994,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Search Background of Missouri Couple Charged in
Jackson Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 12th graf pvs, bgng: Jail officials, with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with more Williams comment in newspaper interview</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal law officers searched Wednesday for any
``shred of evidence'' that might link a Missouri couple charged
with plotting to kill presidential candidate Jesse Jackson to
violent white supremacist groups.
   Londell Williams, 30, and his wife, Tammy Williams, 26, of
Washington, Mo., were in custody on charges of conspiring to kill
Jackson, threatening an informer and possessing an automatic rifle.
   A Secret Service agent testified at a hearing Tuesday that
agents had taped a conversation in which Williams said the
Covenant, the Sword and the Arm of the Lord was planning the
assassination of Jackson.
   ``We are out seeking every shred of evidence and talking to
every person we can who might know something,'' Rich Adams, a
spokesman for the Secret Service in Washington, said Wednesday. The
Secret Service is responsible for protecting Jackson.
   Meanwhile, the Secret Service on Wednesday found a bullet under
a seat in the Jackson campaign plane. But Adams later said it was
determined the 9mm bullet belonged to the Secret Service. ``It's
one of ours,'' he said.
   Jackson, campaigning in California, suggested that comments by
some public officials had helped set the stage for the alleged plot
against him. He was apparently referring to strong criticism of him
during the New York primary campaign by New York City Mayor Ed
Koch, who at one point said Jews would have to be ``crazy'' to vote
for Jackson.
   ``The climate for this kind of antagonism and violence, of
course, has been set by many irresponsible public leaders (whose)
attacks based on race have set a divisive and dangerous climate,
such as the one...in New York in April, for example,'' Jackson told
reporters in Fresno, Calif.
   Tom Den Ouden, the agent in charge of the Springfield, Mo., FBI
office, located in an area that has become known for attracting
members of extremist groups, said he had done some checking into
the Williamses background and found no evidence the pair belonged
to The Order or CSA.
   Papers filed in federal court indicated Londell Williams told an
informer that he was a member of The Order and other white
supremacist groups and that Jackson was to be killed.
   A St. Louis television station, KSDK, reported that Williams had
telephoned from jail on Wednesday to say he had not been involved
in any plot against the Democratic presidential contender.
   ``I did not conspire to kill the man,'' the station quoted
Williams as saying. ``If Jesse Jackson makes it to the presidency,
well, fine.''
   And in an interview with the Belleville (Ill.) News-Democrat,
published in Thursday's editions, Williams admitted he is a racist
but said he is not affiliated with any group.
   ``If there was a crime done, I've done it all on my own,'' he
told the newspaper in a telephone interview from jail on Wednesday.
``I deny that there is a crime done. I did not conspire with anyone
to kill any presidential candidate, especially Jesse Jackson.
   ``I do have prejudices ... against anything that isn't white,''
he added.
   Lawyers for the couple said each denied belonging to a white
supremacist group. And after the hearing Tuesday, Mrs. Williams
said as she was escorted out of the courtroom: ``We're not part of
the CSA.''
   According to the criminal complaint filed in U.S. District
Court, an unidentified person contacted the Franklin County
sheriff's office earlier this month, claiming that the Williamses
were conspiring to assassinate Jackson.
   The information was relayed to the Secret Service and agents met
with the informant, who agreed to wear a hidden microphone and meet
again May 10 with Londell Williams, this time with law enforcement
officials listening in, the complaint said.
   The complaint said the informant later received a death threat
from the Williamses for informing on them.
   At the hearing, Secret Service agent J. Christopher Murphy
testified that the informant led sheriff's deputies to a wooded
area in Franklin County where they found an AR-15 Colt
semi-automatic rifle and a bag the informant said belonged to the
Williamses.
   The complaint said the bag contained a postcard addressed to
Londell Williams and maps, one of which had his fingerprints. The
rifle had been reported stolen from Springfield, according to the
agent.
   Murphy said that during the recorded conversation with the
informant, Williams said he wanted to get the rifle back because it
had been issued to him by the CSA. Williams also said the
organization wanted it returned because it had been used to kill a
law enforcement officer, Murphy said.
   Murphy said that the informant brought up the assassination plot
during the conversation and Williams said ``the CSA was planning to
assassinate candidate Jackson on the Fourth of July.''
   Murphy said that after the Williamses were arrested, Williams
told authorities about the individual who provided him with the
rifle and also made statements about a plan to kill Jackson.
   Secret Service agent David Northcutt testified that he had
interviewed Ms. Williams after her arrest. At that time, she said
she was present when her husband discussed the CSA and other groups.
   Jackson, who is seeking the Democratic presidential nomination
and has been the target of hundreds of death threats in his 1984
and 1988 campaigns, said Wednesday he would not be deterred.
   ``We will not surrender to the dream-busters,'' Jackson said in
Los Angeles. ``The Secret Service will handle the dream-busters,
and I will keep (articulating) the dream and keep hope alive.''
   The Williamses were being held without bond in the federal
detention facility in Belleville, Ill., across the Mississippi
River from St. Louis.
   Records in Christian County Circuit Court show Londell and Tammy
Williams were both arrested in Ozark Dec. 7, 1986. He was charged
with unlawful use of a weapon and she was charged with possession
of marijuana. Both ended up serving short sentences in the
Christian County jail and are on probation, according to records.
</TEXT>
