<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF-Ethiopia-War     05-19 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Ethiopia-War,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopians To Pay Month's Salary To Finance Attack On Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All adult Ethiopians, including
pensioners and nationals living abroad, have been ordered to pay
the government one month's salary to help finance an offensive
against two rebel groups.
   A special decree, signed by President Mengistu Haile Mariam on
Tuesday, said the government also will levy a war tax on private
enterprises.
   The decree, described by a Council of State statement on
Wednesday, did not say how much money would be raised or when the
offensive would be launched.
   According to the World Bank, Ethiopia's 42.2 million people are
among the world's poorest with a per capita annual income of $120.
   During the 1984-85 famine, which killed an estimated 1 million
Ethiopians, Mengistu imposed a similar tax for drought relief.
   The offensive will be launched against the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front and the Tigrean People's Liberation Front, two
northern rebel groups that have been fighting for a separate
homeland for more than 14 years.
</TEXT>
