<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-UniversityPresident     05-19 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-University President,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Back In After Plagiarism Apology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An educator who acknowledged using plagiarism
in his bid to become president of North Dakota State University
said Wednesday he has accepted a request to renew his candidacy.
   University of Minnesota interim President Richard Sauer withdrew
as a candidate earlier this month after he admitted lifting part of
a presentation for the NDSU job from a magazine article without
crediting it.
   He said Wednesday night that John Richardson, North Dakota's
commissioner of higher education, asked him Wednesday afternoon to
again become a candidate for the position.
   ``I think I have something to offer, I think I can do that job
and I'm interested in it,'' Sauer, 48, said when asked why he
accepted the offer.
   Richardson said he first asked Sauer Tuesday to resubmit his
name at the behest of the higher education board. He would not
comment on why the board members wanted to consider Sauer.
   Board President Jack Pfister of Wahpeton could not be reached
for comment Wednesday night.
   Richardson said the action merely follows the original
recommendation of the president's search committee, which put forth
Sauer's name as a possible candidate even though it knew of the
plagiarism allegations against him.
   Sauer will be interviewed by the board Sunday night at NDSU, the
higher education commissioner said.
   Sauer last week apologized to the Univesity of Minnesota
Regents, and they gave him a unanimous vote of confidence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
