<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalCost     05-19 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Cost,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admission Review Can Cut Hospital Costs 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance companies can cut medical expenses 8
percent if they require people to get approval from a review board
before being treated in the hospital, says a study published today.
   Such ``utilization review'' progams are intended to hold down
medical expenses by checking to make sure hospitalization is
necessary.
   The study found that the controls save money, although it did
not determine whether they have any effect on health.
   Utilization review programs generally require that hospital
admissions be approved by a review panel before or at the time of
admission.
   The study, directed by Dr. Paul J. Feldstein of the University
of California at Irvine, was published in the New England Journal
of Medicine and was based on a review of 222 groups of employees
and dependents who were covered by a large private insurance
company that required utilization review.
   The study concluded that utilization review reduced hospital
admissions by 12 percent and total medical expenditures by 8
percent.
   For a typical company with 1,000 employees, this could mean
saving $636,000 over five years, the study said. For a similar
company with a high rate of hospital use, the savings could total
$2.2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
