<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LandTrade     05-19 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Land Trade,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Swap Of Downtown Real Estate For
Swampland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the House Interior Committee are
split over whether a proposed swap of 92.5 U.S.-owned acres in
downtown Phoenix for 118,000 acres of swampland in Florida is fair
to taxpayers, but the committee approved the arrangement.
   ``This is a good deal ... everybody wins,'' says longtime
Interior Chairman Morris Udall, D-Ariz., who helped put the
proposal together.
   Strongly disagreeing is Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., an
Interior subcommittee chairman who is first in line to eventually
succeed Udall as chairman and who normally is aligned with Udall on
issues before the panel.
   Miller says the deal could find taxpayers trading the Phoenix
acreage for ``a bargain basement price'' because nobody knows just
how much the property will be worth when it is rezoned for
commercial development.
   Udall on Wednesday had the clout that normally flows to a
chairman, easily winning voice-vote approval for legislation
authorizing completion of what Miller says would be the biggest
interstate land trade in U.S. history.
   The proposed deal involves the 104-acre site that now houses the
Phoenix Indian School, a federal facility that is slated to close
next month. Miller says the property is one of the most valuable
undeveloped urban tracts in the West. An Interior Department
appraisal values the parcel at $122 million.
   On the Florida end are 118,000 acres owned by the Collier
family, although Miller says that 4,236 of them are under tidal
water and possibly owned by the state of Florida. This land would
be used to enlarge the Big Cypress National Preserve and the
Florida panther refuge in the southwest part of the state, but the
government would not own the subsurface mineral rights.
   The deal worked out by the Interior Department and the Arizona
congressional delegation values the Florida land at $45.1 million.
The proposal also calls for the Collier family to pay the
government $34.9 million.
   Under the plan, the Colliers would get 68 of the 104 acres in
Phoenix. The city of Phoenix would be given 20 acres for a park and
the Veterans Administration 11.5 to expand a hospital, with the
state of Arizona possibly getting the other 4.5 acres.
   Miller challenged the appraisal on the Phoenix property, citing
a report by the congressional General Accounting Office that says
the real value of the land won't be known until the 68 acres are
rezoned for commercial use.
   By a 36-3 vote, he lost an attempt to amend the bill to delay
completion of the deal until after Phoenix substantially completed
the rezoning process, new appraisals were submitted to Congress and
GAO ruled that what the government was getting was equal to what it
was trading away.
   ``My intention is to make this exchange look a little more like
a business transaction,'' Miller said. ``We owe this to the
taxpayers. ... There is no private individual who would get rid of
these lands under these circumstances.''
   Udall and other supporters argued that the legislation could
bring a higher price for the 68 acres because it requires the tract
to be offered to the highest bidder once rezoning is completed.
Under the plan, the Colliers could get the land by matching the
high bid.
   Miller said, however, that there is little likelihood another
buyer could quickly put together the financial package to satisfy
the bill's requirement that the buyer pay cash for the property
within 30 days of the bidding.
   Defending the legislation, Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, said that
``it's a good package for what we're all trying to do. Forget the
value of the Phoenix land. ... We're not in the moneymaking
business.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
