<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Hostages-Petition     05-19 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Petition,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Petition Seeks Release of Western Hostages in Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A petition organized by a Christian human
rights group asks a Shiite Moslem religious leader in Beirut to
intercede on behalf of Westerners being held hostage in Lebanon, a
former captive said Wednesday.
   The prayerful plea, with 40,000 signatures, was carried out of
the United States this week and is expected to be delivered this
weekend to Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah in Beirut, said David
Jacobsen, who spent 17 months in captivity.
   The wording of the petition was carefully worked out in
consultation with Shiite religious leaders, Jacobsen said in a
telephone interview at his home in Huntington Beach, 32 miles south
of Los Angeles.
   Reading from a copy of the petition, Jacobsen said it reads:
``In the name of one merciful God, we the undersigned wish to
express to you our concern and prayers for the hostages held
captive in Lebanon.
   ``We also pray for the countless Lebanese held captive in
Lebanon and elsewhere in the Middle East.
   ``As believers in almighty God we have faith that prayer is more
powerful than armies or contingents of diplomats. Because of this
we respectfully ask you to pray with us and to do whatever you can
to intercede on behalf of all these hostages and captives.'''
   Fadlallah is a Shiite Moslem religious leader associated with
the Hezbollah, or the Party of God,
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah is the group believed responsible
for the kidnapping of Americans, British and other Westerners in
Lebanon.
   ``What makes this so very important is that a story came out
Tuesday in which Sheik Fadlallah said the only way the hostages can
be released is through direct talks with the abductors,'' Jacobsen
said.
   It is hoped that Fadlallah can facilitate those talks, Jacobsen
said.
   A total of 18 Westerners are being held in Lebanon, including
nine Americans. Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press, has been held captive longest. He was
kidnapped on March 16, 1985.
   Jacobsen, 57, was released by his captors in Beirut on Nov. 2,
1986, after being held for 17 months. He was working as the
hospital administrator at the American University Hospital in
Beirut when he was seized on May 28, 1985.
   Jacobsen said the petition specifically asks Fadlallah to ``join
us in prayer'' for the safe return home of Anglican church envoy
Terry Waite, who was taken hostage last year while trying to
negotiate the release of other Western captives.
   The petition concludes, ``We share with you the desire to see
all people safe and at peace, and we agree with your statement,
`Neither Islam nor Christianity justify kidnapping.'''
   The petition was organized by Friends in the West, a small
Protestant group based in Seattle, Wash., that has worked quietly,
but tirelessly for the release of the hostages since 1986, Jacobsen
said.
   Jacobsen asked that the leader of Friends in the West not be
named, saying it may endanger his life, or his freedom, in further
efforts to free the hostages.
</TEXT>
