<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TV-Prime-TimeNews     05-19 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Prime-Time News,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC To Experiment with Prime-Time News This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A summer experiment with prime-time news on NBC
could turn into a fall series if the strike by the Writers Guild of
America doesn't end by mid-summer, says NBC Entertainment President
Brandon Tartikoff.
   Tartikoff told reporters in a satellite news conference
Wednesday that NBC plans to put a series of news specials,
prominently featuring Connie Chung, into the Tuesday 10 p.m. EDT
time period by the end of June.
   NBC has scored in the ratings this season with lifestyle
documentaries like Chung's ``Life in the Fat Lane'' and Maria
Shriver's ``Women in Prison,'' but NBC has not had a regular
prime-time news show since ``1986'' was canceled 1{ years ago. CBS
has three prime-time news hours: ``60 Minutes,'' ``48 Hours'' and
``West 57th.'' ABC has ``20-20.''
   NBC starts the season with prime-time coverage of the Summer
Olympics, but Tartikoff said if the writers' strike continues
through the summer, it could delay the start of NBC's entertainment
series, and a news show could fill in. NBC News writers are covered
by the National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians,
not the Writers Guild.
</TEXT>
