<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WhiteHouseBooks     05-19 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-White House Books,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Baker Won't Write Book, but Others Have</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard H. Baker Jr. says top White House aides
have ``at least an implied commitment'' not to write about their
intimacy with power. If so, its a commitment as often honored in
the breach as in the observance.
   A quick survey shows that half a dozen people who have held
Baker's post of White House chief of staff, or its equivalent, have
written books about their experience. About the same number have
passed up the temptation.
   At least three of the chiefs of staff who have written books
have described tempestuous circumstances surrounding their
departures from the White House.
   Donald T. Regan, however, was apparently the first to rush into
print while the president he had served was still in office, which
partly accounts for the unprecedented furor his book has aroused.
   ``I don't think you ought to write those books,'' Baker told
reporters Wednesday. ``I think when you take a job like this that
there's at least an implied commitment that you're not going to
write books like that. If you're in daily, intimate contact with
the president in a decision-making process, I think there's an
obligation to treat that discreetly and confidentially.
   ``I do not intend to write a book,'' Baker said. ``I think the
bloom is off the rose now with the kiss-and-tell books and I very
much hope that that's a phenomemon that's going to subside and go
away.''
   Maybe so, but it's been around for a while. The very first
person to hold the title of White House chief of staff, Sherman T.
Adams, brought out a book about his experiences in 1961, one year
after the president he served, Dwight D. Eisenhower, left office.
   Like more recent ones, the book contained direct quotations from
the president's conversations, such as one in which Eisenhower told
Adams that the maneuverings of one GOP party leader ``looked like
pretty slippery business'' to him. Adams did not identify the party
leader.
   Regan also sprinkled his book with what appear to be direct
quotes from President Reagan, although he omitted the quotation
marks ``out of deference to the office and the man'' except when he
was quoting what had appeared elsewhere.
   Adams' book, ``Firsthand Report,'' contrasts sharply with
Regan's in one respect. In the index, it has nine entries for first
lady Mamie Eisenhower. The index to Regan's ``For the Record'' has
half a column of entries for Nancy Reagan and nine separate
headings covering his controversial disclosures of her interest in
astrology.
   Adams is one of the two previous chiefs of staff who, like
Regan, left office under fire _ Regan over his handling of the
Iran-Contra affair and Adams over his acceptance of gifts from
Boston industrialist Bernard Goldfine.
   Regan, describing his abrupt replacement by Baker, recounts an
angry telephone conversation in which he told Reagan he had
``deserved better treatment'' and the president replied only that
he was sorry.
   Adams, who had a reputation for reticence, wrote that when he
handed the president his proposed statement of resignation,
Eisenhower ``said that he wanted nobody but me to make this
decision and that under the circumstances he thought I had acted
wisely.''
   In contrast to this low-key account, H.R. Haldeman wrote a
dramatic recital of his dismissal by Richard Nixon at Camp David,
with Nixon telling him that the night before he had ``prayed that I
wouldn't wake up in the morning.''
   Haldeman said he was touched by the president's words, but was
hurt to discover after a Nixon television interview in 1977 that
the president had spoken the same words to John Ehrlichman in
firing him the same day. In fact, he said it was this interview
that prompted him, almost four years after leaving the White House,
to write his book, ``The Ends of Power.''
   He said the effect of the Nixon interview was to ``distort and
confuse'' Watergate issues.
   The most recent chief of staff to break into print was Hamilton
Jordan, whose 1982 book, ``Crisis,'' dealt with the last year of
the Carter presidency. Other books by top White House aides include
``A Political Education,'' published in 1972, by Harry C.
McPherson, who was special counsel to President Johnson, and two
books about the Kennedy administration by Theodore Sorensen. Both
Andrew Goodpaster, who took over many of Adams' duties, and
Alexander Haig, who succeeded Haldeman, have written books but they
did not deal with their White House days.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   W. Dale Nelson covers the White House for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
