<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     05-19 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters President Has Surgery To Remove Tumor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters union President Jackie Presser
was recovering well following successful surgery to remove a
malignant tumor from inside his skull, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Presser underwent the operation Tuesday at Barrow Neurological
Center at St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center, Deborah Gelbart
said Wednesday.
   The 61-year-old Cleveland man was recovering well and without
complications, but no further information was being released at the
request of his family, Ms. Gelbart said.
   She said that decisions on further treatment would be delayed
until next week, ``pending review of all post-operative studies.''
   An Ohio newspaper reported that Presser was diagnosed as having
brain cancer two weeks ago. He was transferred from the Cleveland
Clinic to Barrows on May 11.
   Presser, who has been the president of the nation's largest
union since 1983, relinquished his duties for four months effective
May 4 because of health problems.
   He underwent surgery for a malignant lung tumor in January 1987
in Cleveland.
   The hospital said the malignancy removed Tuesday apparently had
spread from the cancer that led to the earlier operation.
   Presser, elected to a five-year term in 1986 as head of the 1.6
million-member union, is scheduled to stand trial July 12 in U.S.
District Court in Cleveland.
   He is charged with embezzlement and racketeering on allegations
that he took $700,000 from his hometown union local in Cleveland,
and paid it to ``ghost'' employees who performed no work.
   Presser pleaded innocent to the charges.
</TEXT>
