<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites SUB a0422 05-19 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, SUB, a0422,0259</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf of final item to fix `that' to `than'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>COOKEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recipe for a potentially record-winning
burrito: mix 70 pounds of beans with 70 pounds of meat, spread it
in 750 tortilla shells and sprinkle with 15 pounds of cheese.
   And hope the locals like Mexican food.
   The 444-foot-long burrito, constructed Wednesday by students at
Tennessee Technological University, was divided into 600 six-inch
pieces that went for $1 each.
   But the sponsor's goal was bigger than the public's appetite:
about half the big burrito was left over and had to be thrown away.
   Still, the project raised $300 for the Cookeville Rescue Mission
for the homeless, said Bob Hagemann, a spokesman for Tennessee Tech.
   The goal was to build a 500-foot burrito, but the weather
interfered as workers tried to cover 65 tables with the flour
tortilla shells in preparation for stuffing.
   ``It was too windy a day. All of our burrito flours (tortilla
shells) were flying away,'' said Jeff Dishman, shift manager for
the Cookeville Taco Bell, which helped build the burrito.
   Denver burrito builders hold the Guinness Book of World Records
award for the largest burrito _ a 400-footer _ said Joseph Null,
assistant manager of Taco Bell.
   Guinness officials were invited Wednesday, but none showed up,
Dishman said. But he said the organizers plan to send Guinness some
photos of the burrito and a sworn statement from the Cookville
mayor in the hope they will be declared the new champion.
</TEXT>
