<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSCommission     05-19 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Commission,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Masters And Johnson Defend Research Before AIDS Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex therapists William H. Masters and Virginia
E. Johnson say they published their controversial book on AIDS
because too little attention was being paid to the potential spread
of the disease among heterosexuals.
   Ms. Johnson told the White House AIDS commission on Wednesday
that the authors did not mean to create ``panic in the streets,''
but wanted to ``counteract an earlier absence of openness, of
honesty in collaboration'' on the part of government officials.
   Federal health officials have criticized the book for suggesting
AIDS is spreading more rapidly among sexually active heterosexuals
than projected by official government estimates.
   Another criticism is that the Masters-Johnson findings did not
go through the ``peer review'' process required for publication in
a major medical journal.
   ``There would have been no way to publish in journals,'' said
Masters, citing both the length of the material and what he said is
traditional difficulty in getting sex research accepted in such
forums.
   ``Books are the characteristic mode of publishing in the field
of sex research, which is our field,'' added Dr. Robert C. Kolodny,
a long-term associate of the Masters-Johnson team and a co-author
of the book ``Crisis: Heterosexual Behavior in the Age of AIDS.''
   To commission chairman James Watkins' admonition that there
should be ``an element of solidarity, you might say, among the
scientific and medical community'' on AIDS, Kolodny replied:
   ``With all due respect ... the process of science is not and has
never been served by looking for unanimity of opinion. The process
of science has always been served by allowing people to speak on
varying interpretations.''
   Kolodny acknowledged the book's estimate that as many as 3
million Americans may have the virus without knowing it is about
twice as high as the official government estimate. But he
emphasized that the difference stems from different interpretations
of the same raw data available to both government and private
analysts.
   As to controversy over what is often called casual spread of the
disease, Kolodny said the book carefully distinguishes between
theory and saying ``as a practical matter, this is not something
you ought to worry about.''
   For example, on the question of risk of catching the virus in a
restaurant where a waiter or chief has AIDS ``we said in our book,
specifically, not unless you have sex or share needles with that
person.''
   On catching it from a toilet seat?
   ``We traveled here by public transportation and we all used the
toilets in those areas and that should address the practical
aspects of the risk,'' said Kolodny.
   ``We do not suggest for a minute that people not use public rest
rooms, but we do suggest that if the public place looks to be
contaminated with suspicious substances, blood or other materials,
we wouldn't have used that 15 years ago in the time before AIDS and
we don't suspect that anyone would really use that now.
   ``This is common sense. No one is claiming that the virus jumps
off a surface and bites you,'' Kolodny said.
</TEXT>
