<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PhoneFlap     05-19 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phone Flap,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DJ, D'Amato Staff Claim White House Refused Anti-Noriega Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York disc jockey claims the White House
``acted very bizarrely'' when his listeners took the advice of Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato and called to complain about President Reagan's
handling of the situation in Panama.
   The White House switchboard refused to take the complaints
Wednesday or to transfer callers to a special presidential
inquiries extension, said Jim Kerr, a disc jockey with WWPR-FM, an
ABC affiliate in New York City.
   ``I spent two hours of my day today before I escaped from the
station taking all these phone calls from people saying, `I tried
to call the White House and they told us to call another number,'''
Kerr said.
   He said he believed the White House did not want to keep what
could be an embarrassing tally of the calls.
   ``The White House is now acting very bizarrely,'' he said.
   D'Amato spokesman Ed Martin said ABC ``thinks they're getting
jerked around because the president's giving a big drug speech and
they don't want to have anything critical like this.'' The
president stressed his administration's antidrug efforts in a
commencement speech at the U.S. Coast Guard Academy on Wednesday.
   White House spokesman Ben Jarrett refused a reporter's request
to find out whether operators were refusing to transfer the calls.
   ``I don't know anything about the operators,'' he said. ``I'm
not going to track that down, I'm sorry.''
   He also declined to explain how the inquiries office functioned,
and refused a request to determine how the office decides when to
begin keeping a tally of calls on an issue.
   Jarrett said that office had received calls Wednesday about the
situation in Panama, but ``They didn't have a count of them and no
characterization of the answers.''
   But Martin said he got a call from a volunteer at the complaint
number ``who left a message with our reception area saying the
senator made some comments in New York today and we're getting a
flood of calls and we'd like to know what he said.''
   D'Amato, R-N.Y., went on the radio Wednesday morning expressly
to ask constituents to call the White House and complain about
reports that the United States is considering dropping drug charges
against Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</TEXT>
