<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-19 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Kicks Off Campaign Swing In Two Remaining Big Primary
States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Prenoon lead likely.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENGLISHTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, riding an impressive
string of primary victories, is taking aim at the blocs of
delegates he needs to clinch the Democratic presidential nomination.
   Still several hundred delegates shy of a convention majority,
the Massachusetts governor was campaigning in New Jersey and
California. The states are the two big prizes on June 7, the day
that closes out the Democratic primary season.
   There are 314 Democratic delegates at stake in the California
primary and 109 in New Jersey. The other two June 7 states are New
Mexico with 24 delegates and Montana with 19.
   At a news conference on Wednesday, Dukakis brushed aside
Jackson's complaint that he was not getting his fair share of
support from the party and elected officials designated ``super
delegates'' to the nominating convention.
   ``I think Jesse has a perfect right to voice criticism of
whatever he chooses to criticize,'' Dukakis told reporters at the
Massachusetts Statehouse. ``I don't think we are going to have a
fight with Mr. Jackson.''
   After he arrived in New Jersey, Dukakis said of the Jackson
complaint, ``We all knew what the rules were going in.''
   Dukakis continued to insist that he won't start the process of
choosing a running mate until after he has clinched the nomination.
   Asked about reports he has designated his close friend and law
school classmate Paul Brountas to head the search for a vice
presidential candidate, Dukakis said: ``Nobody is heading my search
for a running mate. The search for a running mate will not begin
until the eighth of June.''
   But Dukakis also said he hoped to have chosen a running mate
before the Democratic convention convenes in July.
   ``I would hope that decision would be made before the
convention,'' he said.
   Dukakis has been getting plenty of advice about where to turn
for the second spot on the Democratic ticket, most of it centering
on members of the Senate.
   Among the names mentioned most often were Sens. Sam Nunn of
Georgia, Bob Graham of Florida, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, John Glenn
of Ohio and Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
   Asked about the home-state favorite when he arrived in New
Jersey, Dukakis said of Bradley, ``I like him.''
   But Bradley said Wednesday he doesn't want to be vice president.
``No, no, no. It's as firm and strong as I can make it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
