<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0812 05-19 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0812,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Attacks Second Neutral Tanker in Retaliation for Iraqi Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with second ship attack, TRIMS. No
pickup.
^With AM-Iran-Elections, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian speedboats attacked a Norwegian
tanker twice in the Strait of Hormuz on Thursday, shipping
executives said. It was Iran's second foray against neutral vessels
in two days in the Persian Gulf.
   The executives identified the tanker as the 55,173-ton Berge
Strand, an empty liquefied petroleum gas carrier. Its destination
in the gulf was not immediately determined.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they did
not know what weapons were used against the vessel in the first
attack, at 6:30 a.m. (10:30 p.m. EDT Wednesday).
   The Berge Strand began sailing to the southern gulf port of
Dubai for repairs on minor damage. There were no injuries reported.
   An hour later the speedboats returned and fired four rockets at
the ship, injuring one person, the sources said. They said that the
Berge Strand developed engine problems after the second raid, but
had no further details.
   Iran attacked the Japanese-owned chemical tanker Ace Chemi on
Wednesday.
   A fire started on the 6,730-ton Ace Chemi that forced its
Japanese captain and 16 South Korean crewmen to abandon ship in
Hormuz, the gulf's only outlet. All were rescued by salvage tugs,
said shipping executives who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In the ground war, Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency
said Iranian forces killed or wounded 2,000 Iraqi troops and
captured more than 10 square miles of northeast Iraq in an
operation that began Tuesday night. It said many Iraqi troops were
taken prisoner. There was no comment from Iraq.
   The U.S. Central Command said the Navy's 32nd convoy of the year
was sailing south through the gulf. It included one U.S.-flagged
Kuwaiti tanker, the 46,723-ton Gas Prince, escorted by the missile
frigate Copeland.
   The Ace Chemi attack was the first by Iranian gunboats on a
neutral vessel since April 24. It came one month after a major
clash with U.S. naval forces in which six Iranian craft were sunk
or disabled.
   It also was the first since the Reagan administration began a
new policy May 3 that permits Navy ships to intervene in attacks on
commercial vessels on request regardless of what flag they are
flying.
   Iranian officials recently declared their policy of
blow-for-blow retaliatory attacks on neutral shipping would
continue.
   The Ace Chemi raid happened 11 miles south of Iran's Larak
island oil terminal as the Panamanian-flagged ship was heading into
the gulf, bound for the Saudi Arabian oil port of Jubail for a
cargo of petrochemicals, the sources said.
   U.S. warships were on patrol as usual in the area at the time of
the 8 a.m. attack and monitored the tanker's distress call on
radio. But the nearest U.S. vessel was 60 miles away, a two-hour
sail at top speed, said Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke.
   Iraq has claimed a dozen raids, six of them independently
verified, on Iranian tankers and terminals since April 29. The
raids seek to strangle oil exports that support Iran in the
7{-year-old gulf war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
