<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MXDevelopment     05-19 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MX Development,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci OKs Development of Missile Rail System; Contracts Let</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has awarded two contracts
totaling almost $329 million to develop a rail-car launching system
for the MX nuclear missile, the Pentagon says.
   The contracts were let after Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
authorized full-scale development of such a `rail garrison' system.
   ``As currently configured, the `rail garrison' system will
consist of 50 missiles, based aboard 25 trains with each carrying
two missiles,'' a Pentagon statement said.
   The MX, a 10-warhead, 195,000-pound missile, is now entering the
Air Force's inventory as a silo-based weapon. President Reagan has
asked Congress to allow deployment of 100 of the missiles, but so
far only 50 have been authorized.
   Reagan, in a bid to obtain approval for the second 50, proposed
in December 1986 that a rail version of the missile be produced to
improve its survivability in the event of a Soviet attack.
   His proposal is known as rail garrison because it envisions
placing MX missiles on rail cars that would remain inside military
bases, or garrisons, until there was a threat of attack. Only then
would they scatter across the country on the commercial rail
network.
   Unlike the Soviet Union, the United States currently does not
have any mobile intercontinental missiles.
   The Air Force contracts are for the construction and testing of
the missile-carrying, launch control and security rail cars that
will be needed to make the 71-foot missile mobile.
   A $167 million contract was awarded to Westinghouse Electric
Corp.'s Marine Division in Sunnyvale, Calif., to design, develop
and test the missile launch car.
   The second contract, worth $161.7 million, was awarded to
Rockwell International Corp.'s Autonetics Electronics Systems
Division in Anaheim, Calif., for the design, development and
testing of the launch control system, launch control car and
security car.
   Both contractors will be expected to complete their work by July
1992, the Pentagon said.
   The Air Force has said it expects each train to include two
locomotives and six cars _ two missile launch cars with missiles
inside; one launch control car; two security cars, and one
maintenance car.
   Congress has generally endorsed the idea of developing a mobile
missile, but is now locked in a debate over whether to produce a
rail version of the MX or a much smaller, single-warhead missile
known as the Midgetman that could be fired from a truck launcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0046 </DOCNO>
