<HEAD>Dissident Reports That Thousands Rally in Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sakharov</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people rallied in Armenia to tell
authorities the sentencing of an Azerbaijani man does not address
their demands that a neighboring region be annexed, a dissident
source said.
   ``They think the problem goes deeper than sentencing guilty
people,'' Vladimir Ryabokon, an editor of the dissident journal
Express-Khronika, said Wednesday.
   Ryabokon said about 15,000 Armenians rallied in the streets of
Yerevan, the Armenian capital, on Tuesday, a day after Talekh
Salekh Ogli Ismailov was found guilty of premeditated murder and
given the maximum sentence of 15 years.
   It was the first conviction in connection with three days of
rioting that broke out in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait on Feb.
28.
   Ryabokon said there were no arrests by police during Tuesday's
protest.
   He said a few thousand people also gathered in Stepanakert, the
major city of Nagorno-Karabakh, after Ismailov was sentenced to
stress that they consider the annexation issue still not settled.
   Ryabokon said his information came from the weekly journal's
correspondent in Yerevan.
   Express-Khronika has been distributing information on dissident
activities and actions by various ethnic groups in the Soviet Union
since the fall.
   Armenians began agitating in mid-February for permission to
annex the predominantly Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh region from
neighboring Azerbaijan. Their campaign apparently led to the riots.
   Thirty-two people _ 26 ethnic Armenians and six ethnic
Azerbaijanis _ were killed in the rioting.
   The Soviet government has refused to permit the annexation.
Instead, it has come up with a costly development program for
Nagorno-Karabakh to improve economic and social conditions.
