<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChowderChef Bjt   05-19 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chowder Chef, Bjt,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Spoonful Of Chowder Helps The Medicine Go Down At Beth Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief chef at a popular seafood restaurant
chain returned to the hospital where he had been a patient recently
to perform some corrective surgery of his own. In the kitchen.
   As the specialist he is, Jean-Jacques Paimblanc supervised a
well-scrubbed staff of more than 100 at Beth Israel Hospital.
   A few watched as he made an incision into a cooked fish.
   ``Perfect,'' said Paimblanc, of Legal Sea Food's restaurants.
``It should taste moist, but not too soft. This is good.''
   For Wednesday's lunch and dinner, Paimblanc and two Legal Sea
Food employees oversaw preparation of 1,400 meals for patients and
staff at the 460-bed hospital.
   ``It just takes a little attention to make good, fresh meals,''
said Paimblanc. ``Hospitals serve fish sticks when they could get
in fresh fish. They serve frozen vegetables when they could buy
presliced fresh vegetables. It doesn't take much to make a much
better meal.''
   The items on the menu were identical to those served at Legal
Sea Food's six Massachusetts restaurants, including the fish
chowder included at President Reagan's inaugural dinner in January
1981.
   Paimblanc added a newly created low-calorie clam chowder with
clams and vegetables.
   ``With all the studies talking about the benefits of fish and
fish oils on health, it seems like hospitals should be talking a
closer look at their meals,'' Paimblanc said.
   ``We'll put the hospitals out of business if people keep eating
like this.''
   Gail DeLuca, Beth Israel's director of nutritional services,
said research is still ongoing on direct correlations between fish
oils and lower incidence of cardiac problems. The hospital omitted
a reference to fish oil's health benefits from the back of the
Legal Sea Food menu used at the hospital.
   Paimblanc, 54, was recovering from a mild infection 18 months
ago when he wandered into the Beth Israel kitchen bored by his
meals. He suggested trying his hand at preparing the hospital's
food for a day.
   On Wednesday, 250 pounds each of cod and tuna were baked or
broiled under the supervision of Paimblanc, who wove his large
frame through the crowded kitchen to inspect the meals.
   During a break in preparing the fish and stirring the chowder,
Paimblanc took time out for his own lunch.
   A corned beef sandwich.
</TEXT>
