<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Tidy Britain,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discard Manners To Combat Littering, Conference Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British may have to discard their cherished
good manners to combat littering, the chairman of the Tidy Britain
Group said.
   ``I'm beginning to think we've been nice about it for a little
bit too long,'' Lord Parry told a conference Wednesday sponsored by
the anti-litter organization.
   Parry called for tougher enforcement of anti-littering laws. The
law permits fines of more than $700 for littering, but in 1986, the
average fine imposed was less than $60.
   Parry also suggested hiring wardens to ticket litterers, much
like meter maids ticket parking violators, and producing a ``black
book'' illustrating a community's litterers or even awarding a
``booby prize'' to the worst.
   A major soccer match can pile up 5 tons of garbage in and around
a stadium and on an average week, commuters leave 25 tons of
rubbish behind in the London Underground subway system, said Graham
Ashworth director-general of the group.
</TEXT>
