<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Criticizes Gorbachev's Handling of Ethnic Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights group said Andrei
Sakharov, the Nobel Peace laureate, wrote Mikhail S. Gorbachev
critizing the Soviet leader for his handling of recent ethnic
unrest in the Soviet Union.
   ``Glasnost appears to be crushed when it is most needed,'' wrote
the nuclear physicist who won the Nobel prize in 1975.
   The Bukovsky Foundation, a lobby group for Soviet dissidents,
released excerpts of Sakharov's letter translated into English at
its annual Sakharov Conference on Wednesday, saying it was written
in April but never publicized.
   Sakharov was invited but did not attend the conference on
``Blank Spots in Soviet History,'' the Amsterdam-based organization
said.
   Now living in Moscow, Sakharov was exiled to the city of Gorky
from 1980 to 1986 for criticizing his nation's intervention in
Afghanistan.
   Expelled Soviet dissident Vladimir Bukovsky, for whom the
foundation is named, on Wednesday predicted that Gorbachev will
have to increase consumer prices, and that could lead to unrest in
Soviet society.
   Gorbachev told Sakharov soon after receiving the letter that it
would be published in the popular English-language weekly Moscow
News if the dissident was willing to ``soften some of his
language,'' the foundation said in a preface to the letter.
   Sakharov refused, the foundation said. It added that the letter
was signed ``with deep and sincere respect.''
   The letter referred to clashes in February between ethnic
Armenians and Azerbaijanis in Azerbaijan's Nagorno-Karabakh region,
where dozens of people died.
   ``In the context of perestroika, the Armenian population of
Karabakh raised its hopes that there may be a constitutional
solution to the problem,'' said Sakharov's letter.
   ``Glasnost,'' openness on selected social topics, and
``perestroika,'' restructuring, are key elements of Gorbachev's
program to reform the Soviet society and economy.
</TEXT>
