<HEAD>Jackson, Campaigning In California, Vows To `Keep Dreaming'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson was campaigning in
California's agricultural heartland today, sounding environmental
and farming themes as he searched for votes in the June 7 primary.
   At a stop in Fresno Wednesday night, Jackson suggested that past
comments by ``irresponsible public leaders'' could have helped set
the stage for an alleged assassination plot against him.
   A St. Louis couple, Londell and Tammy Williams, were charged
this week with conspiring to kill Jackson. According to court
papers, Londell Williams told an informant he was a white
supremacist, but investigators said they had not found evidence
linking him to any organized white supremacist group.
   Jackson suggested that racial hatred could have been fueled by
statements made during last month's raucous primary campaign in New
York. New York City Mayor Ed Koch criticized Jackson harshly and at
one point said Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for him.
   ``The climate for this kind of antagonism and violence, of
course, has been set by many irresponsible public leaders (whose)
attacks based on race have set a divisive and dangerous climate,
such as the one...in New York in April, for example,'' Jackson told
reporters.
   However, Jackson vowed not to ``lower the tone of my campaign,
adding: ``I will keep dreaming.''
   Londell Williams, in an interview published today in the
Belleville, Ill., News-Democrat, said, ``I did not conspire with
anyone to kill any presidential candidate, especially Jesse
Jackson.''
   ``I'm sorry that this mess has been brought up,'' he said.
``This is a very bad mistake. I'm really sorry the man (Jackson)
has to hear anything like this. The man should not be afraid of
anything from me ... I could care less if he's elected president or
not.''
   Jackson, whose relations with the Jewish community have been
strained in the past, met Wednesday with some three dozen rabbis
and Jewish leaders.
   Jackson was beginning the day today in Bakersfield, with stops
set later in San Francisco.
   Jackson received a warm welcome at Fresno's Saroyan Theater from
a crowd of about 3,000, including toddler Jonathon Clark. Last
year, Jackson taped a public service announcement to appeal for a
new liver for the boy, then 10 months old, who needed the
transplant to survive. The child received the donor liver last May
and will celebrate his second birthday next month.
   Jackson hoisted the boy in his arms during the speech and told
the crowd of the ``challenge to save our children'' by putting a
higher priority on education and social programs.
   After the rally, Jackson reiterated his support for the United
Farm Workers' boycott on table grapes. And, questioned about
cleanup of pesticide contamination in San Joaquin Valley wells,
Jackson replied, ``It does not require additional laws, it just
requires commitments and enforcement.''
   Jackson criticized the Reagan administration record on
environmental and worker safety laws as ``scandalous.''
</TEXT>
