<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-Defense     05-19 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Defense,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Chief Says Taiwan Could Beat China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top general said in a rare interview
that Taiwan's military could repel an invasion from Communist China.
   Hau Pei-tsun, chief of the general staff, said in the interview
with the Global Views Monthly magazine that Taiwan was building up
its defenses to deter an invasion from Communist China, which
maintains this island off its coast is a renegade province.
   Hau was quoted as saying that ``there has always been the threat
of a Communist Chinese armed invasion against Taiwan,'' although
Beijing might hesitate to launch such an attack because of negative
international reaction.
   ``But from the military standpoint alone, we still have chances
of winning,'' Hau was quoted as saying in the edition of the
magazine published Sunday. It said the interview was the general's
first with the media.
   Despite China's large amount of military equipment, Taiwan ``can
win by the quality of not only our defense equipment but our
troops,'' he was quoted as saying. The United States has been
Taiwan's main weapons supplier.
   Although Communist China has roughly 3 million troops while
Taiwan has fewer than a half million, Hau told the magazine that
China could not bring into play all its forces against the island.
``The room for battling is very small in Taiwan,'' he was quoted as
saying. ``They cannot fly thousands of aircraft, nor can they send
millions of troops here at the same time.''
   The Nationalist government based in Taiwan claims to be the
rightful ruler of all China, although it lost a civil war to the
Communists in 1949. Beijing has refused to rule out using force to
reunify with Taiwan, but tension has eased as unofficial contacts
have increased in recent years.
</TEXT>
