<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-19 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Tells Congress That Unneeded Bases Should Be Closed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, pointing
to the need to reduce the federal deficit, says he supports
congressional attempts to close unneeded military bases.
   ``It makes sense to look seriously now at closing bases, because
our military force structure is being reduced and growth in the
defense budget is being slowed,'' Carlucci told a House
subcommittee on Wednesday.
   ``We must stop spending money to operate bases we do not need,''
he said. ``Our increasingly scarce resources simply must be applied
to higher defense priorities, so that we do not jeopardize
America's national security interests.''
   Carlucci was testifying in support of a plan designed to
surmount the strong reluctance of Congress to allow military bases
to be closed.
   It calls for creation of a Pentagon commission to review bases
by Dec. 31 and recommend a list of which can be closed. Carlucci
would then have 15 days to accept or reject the entire list. His
decision would be made less than a week before the end of President
Reagan's term in office.
   The Pentagon estimates $2 billion to $5 billion could be saved
by closing the unneeded bases.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>IRS Refunds Total $56 Billion So Far</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has refunded
$55.9 billion to taxpayers this year, slightly less than it sent
out last year, although the money went to more people.
   The IRS said Wednesday that 65.1 million couples and
individuals, or 80.4 percent of the returns that have been
processed so far this year, qualified for refunds. The refunds
averaged $860.
   The total number of refunds is up slightly, from 64.8 million
last year. The amount refunded declined, from $56.1 billion, as did
the average, from $866.
   Through May 13, the IRS had received almost 101 million returns,
an increase of 3.3 percent from the 97.7 million tallied during the
same period a year ago. The agency has processed 80.9 billion, up 1
percent from the 80 billion last year.
   The number of taxpayers who filed the simplest return, the Form
1040EZ, rose by 8.7 percent over last year, from 16.7 million to
18.2 million. Filers of Form 1040A, were off slightly, from 17.6
million to 17.4 million. The number filing the long form, 1040,
increased 3.3 percent, from 63.4 million to 65.4 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three Dismissed Workers Get Awards For Whistleblowing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people who lost their jobs after
allegedly blowing the whistle on wrongdoing by their employers have
been rewarded with $10,000 each by a private foundation.
   The Cavallo Foundation, set up by Massachusetts money manager
Michael Cavallo, gave its first annual awards on Wednesday to a
fired shipyard inspector, a former Census Bureau worker and an
ex-Veterans Administration employee.
   The awards came as a Senate committee prepared to vote today on
a bill that would protect government employees who disclose abuses.
The bill would restrict the Office of the Special Counsel from
acting against whistleblowers who complain that the agency often
ends up investigating them when they file complaints.
   Receiving the awards Wednesday were: Leon Bard, 34, fired in
1986 as a quality inspector at Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine; John
Barter, 39, fired as security chief at the Cincinnati Veterans
Administration Medical Center; and Billie Pirner Garde, 35, fired
for speaking out eight years ago against corruption and sexual
harassment in the Muskogee, Okla., district office of the Census
Bureau.
