<HEAD>Bradley Says No To Vice-Presidential Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey says he does
not want to be the Democrats' candidate for vice president this
year.
   ``No, no, no. It's as firm and as strong as I can make it,''
Bradley said Wednesday.
   The senator has been mentioned occasionally as a possible
running mate for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, and The
Washington Post reported Wednesday that senior Dukakis aides are
talking favorably of Bradley as well as Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, as
potential vice presidential candidates.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen also denied any interest Wednesday in joining
Dukakis on the ticket.
   ``I have absolutely no interest,'' says the senior senator from
Texas.
   Dukakis himself said he has not begun to look for a running mate
but hopes to choose one before the Democratic National Convention
in July.
   Bradley said that while he and Dukakis have met twice during the
past month, they have not discussed the vice presidency. ``The
subject has never come up in a private conversation,'' he said.
