<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NeighborhoodPosse     05-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Neighborhood Posse,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mob Apprehends Man Suspected Or Raping Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mob of neighbors chased down and apprehended a
man accused of breaking into a home and raping a 7-year-old girl in
front of her 5-year-old sister, authorities say.
   One of the neighbors said later that if they had known why they
were chasing the man, they might have killed him.
   The man, a parolee who was once accused of making a telephone
threat against the life of President Reagan, was chased for about
four blocks by about eight people, surrounded and held until police
arrived, officers said.
   ``I think we basically got there before anybody had a chance to
lay into him,'' said Sgt. Bill Staney of the Juvenile Division.
   Charles Franklin Ireland, 42, was being held in the Harris
County Jail today in lieu of $20,000 bond on charges of burglary
and aggravated sexual assault of a child.
   Ireland is accused of climbing through a window of a house late
Tuesday and sexually assaulting the girl in her bedroom, Staney
said. Her 5-year-old sister was in the room and saw the attack, he
added.
   The victim was released Wednesday from Ben Taub Hospital.
   The girls were alone in the house while their mother worked at
her evening-shift job, Staney said. She normally had a babysitter
stay with the girls, but she told police she had no money to pay
the sitter this week and left them at home with a padlock on the
front door, he said.
   The girls' father does not live with the family, Staney said.
   Neighbors saw Ireland climbing back out the window and heard the
girls frantically screaming, Staney said.
   ``It's a mostly Hispanic neighborhood, so when the neighbors saw
this big white guy coming out the window, they knew he didn't
belong there,'' he said.
   Ireland did not resist and was not harmed by the neighbors,
Staney said.
   Guadalupe Ramirez, one of the people who chased the man, said
they heard someone yelling and ran toward the house.
   ``We were behind him. There were about eight of us,'' Ramirez
said.
   ``We were trying to catch him, but we really didn't know exactly
why,'' Ramirez, 43, said. ``If we had known what had happened he
might have died.''
   Ramirez said Ireland started crying after he was caught.
   ``He just started crying, crying like a baby,'' Ramirez said.
   Ireland, a welder, told police he didn't remember assaulting the
girl, Staney said.
   Ireland was charged in August 1984 after calling the local U.S.
Secret Service and FBI offices from a Houston telephone booth and
making a threat against Reagan, police said.
   Agents said his threat stemmed from a belief that Reagan was
sending money to Africa instead of helping people in this country.
   Staney said Ireland also was paroled from the Texas Department
of Corrections in October 1982 after serving about five months of a
two-year sentence for auto theft.
</TEXT>
