<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Banned     05-19 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Banned,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Barred From Speaking At Utah School</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Gov. Evan Mecham, whose criminal
trial was scheduled to begin today, has been barred from speaking
at Brigham Young University because of questions about his honesty.
   ``We haven't decided that Evan Mecham is guilty, but now is not
the appropriate time for him to appear on campus,'' said Brent
Harker, a spokesman for the university that's operated by the
Mormon Church.
   Mecham, who is a Mormon, had been scheduled to speak at the
Provo, Utah, campus on May 26 or 27, in an appearance sponsored by
Campus Republicans, a student group.
   ``We do not allow to speak on campus people who are not worthy
examples,'' said Brad Hanesworth, a communications professor and
the group's faculty adviser. ``I thought it was clear that he did
not meet the criteria'' on which speakers may appear at BYU.
   ``It wasn't an effort to say `Here's Governor Mecham. He's a
great guy and the people of Arizona (treated him unfairly.)' It was
an effort to say, `Governor Mecham, here's a chance to explain
yourself and give one side of the issue,''' said Joe Woodwell,
president of the Campus Republicans.
   School policy says that in order to appear at BYU, a speaker
``must not, in his or her personal life (as reflected in the news
media and common understanding of the public), have committed acts
of immorality, dishonesty or other conduct that would make it
inappropriate for the Church Education System to feature him or her
as a speaker.
   ``His or her life and advice should make an appropriate model
for students in an educational system with our ideals.''
   Mecham, a Republican, said Wednesday he is not upset by the
decision barring him from speaking on the campus.
   ``I don't get too upset about anything,'' Mecham said. ``It was
just a group of young Republicans who wanted me to speak. If they
have a policy, they have a policy, and I won't speak.''
   Harker said one reason for not permitting Mecham to appear is
that he is under indictment and his trial on charges that he
concealed a $350,000 campaign contribution was about to begin.
   ``When a person is involved in (a court case), if he comes to
speak, that would imply an endorsement by the university,'' Harker
said. ``People would say, `Oh, he's speaking at BYU. They must
think he's OK.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
