<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WellsFargo     05-19 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wells Fargo,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sets $1 Million Bond For Defendant in Wells Fargo Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge set bond at $1 million
for a Puerto Rican nationalist who is accused of helping mastermind
a $7 million Wells Fargo robbery and has been held without trial
for a record 32 months.
   U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie, acting under a federal
appeals court order, set the bond Wednesday for Filberto Ojeda Rios.
   Under last week's order by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, Ojeda must be released by 5 p.m. Friday.
   Clarie had denied bond for Ojeda five times before at the
request of authorities, who sayd Ojeda is a Cuban agent and would
flee the country before trial.
   ``It (32 months detention) is not a record I am proud of,''
Ojeda said in a telephone interview Wednesday night from a federal
detention center. ``To tell you the truth, I'd rather have the
record for the shortest.''
   He said he considers his imminent freedom only a ``partial
liberation. ... It could only be total liberation if I was in my
home and my country was free.''
   Ojeda is accused of helping plan the September 1983 robbery of a
Wells Fargo depot in West Hartford to finance Los Macheteros _
Spanish for ``the machete wielders'' _ a violent group seeking
Puerto Rican independence.
   Clarie rejected a prosecution request that he set bond at $2.5
million, but imposed sharp restrictions on Ojeda's movements once
he is released.
   Ojeda must wear an electronic bracelet that will tell
authorities where he is, must live in Hartford and will be able to
move around the city only between 7 a.m. and 8 p.m.
   Clarie rejected the government's request that Ojeda be confined
to a defense attorney's home and a defense request that he be
allowed to return to Puerto Rico to convalesce from triple-bypass
heart surgery April 11.
   Defense attorney Richard J. Harvey called Clarie's ruling ``a
clear defeat for the government.''
   ``As long as justice is done, the government never loses,'' said
U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr.
   Twardy said that despite the $1 million bond he still does not
believe Ojeda will appear in court.
   ``If I thought this was enough I would have done this three
years ago,'' the prosecutor said.
   Ojeda, who is in his mid-50s, has been in pretrial detention
since his August 1985 arrest in Luquillo, Puerto Rico.
   He had been held under the Bail Reform Act of 1984, which allows
federal judges to deny bond to dangerous suspects. However, the
appeals court ruled that further detention would violate Ojeda's
constitutional rights.
   The 15 other Wells Fargo defendants are free on bonds of up to
$1.5 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
