<DOCNO> AP880519-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs     05-19 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Siege Over; Reopening Temple Discussed; Sikh Gunmen Kill 13 In
Punjab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sikh elders who manage the Golden
Temple were called into session today to discuss reopening the
golden-domed shrine where a 10-day police siege ended with the
surrender of militant Sikh separatists.
   The 400-year-old temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine, had become a
base for extremists waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for an
independent Sikh homeland in Punjab state.
   Forty-five men and one woman walked out of the temple on
Wednesday, their hands in the air or clasped on their heads, and
surrendered to the 2,800 policemen, commandos and paramilitary
troops surrounding it.
   At least 42 people, mostly militant Sikhs, were killed during
the siege. Four other militants committed suicide rather than
surrender.
   Bhan Singh, secretary of the Sikh elders' committee that runs
the temple, told reporters late Wednesday night that it would today
discuss how to restore daily religious rites at the shrine.
   A curfew remained in effect today within 300 yards of the
complex's walls and municipal workers began cleaning its dining
hall, hostels and offices.
   Despite the government's success in ending the siege, its
authority is still challenged by continuing Sikh attacks elsewhere
in Punjab state.
   The United News of India said today that 13 more people were
killed during the night around the northern state in attacks by
Sikh extremists, who killed at least 99 people in Punjab while the
siege was under way.
   At least 40 people were killed Tuesday and Wednesday, including
more than 30 migrant Hindu laborers shot to death as they slept at
a camp near the state capital of Chandigarh. A note found near the
laborers' bodies said the killings were to avenge the Golden Temple
siege.
   So far this year, at least 1,076 killings in the state have been
blamed on Sikh gunmen. In all of 1987, the militants killed about
1,030 people in Punjab.
   Sikh militants say they need a separate homeland to preserve
their faith and combat what they call discrimination by India's
Hindu majority.
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, comprise less than 2 percent of
India's 800 million people but are a majority in Punjab.
   The temple siege began May 9 after Sikh gunmen fired from inside
the complex at a party of police commanders who were on an
inspection tour outside its walls. Five of the officers were
wounded.
   Eight hundred pilgrims and temple workers were evacuated the
following day and security forces proceeded to fire hundreds of
rounds at the temple complex's office and residential buildings.
   They were, however, under orders not to hit the temple itself.
   On Sunday, 146 people including a number of wanted Sikh
extremists surrendered during a cease-fire. The last of the
hard-core militants gave up on Wednesday.
   Sidharth Shankar Ray, the governor of Punjab, called it ``a day
of great relief'' but added: ``It is neither victory nor defeat.''
   He urged Sikh gunmen throughout Punjab to turn themselves in and
pledged to restore religious rites at the temple as soon as
possible.
   The siege was the largest show of force at the temple since June
1984, when Prime Minister Indira Gandhi had the army storm the
complex to oust armed Sikhs. More than 1,200 people, mostly Sikhs,
died in the onslaught.
   Many Sikhs considered the raid the worst sort of desecration,
and it was avenged less than five months later when Mrs. Gandhi was
assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
   Mrs. Gandhi's son and successor as prime minister, Rajiv Gandhi,
said on Wednesday that the carrying of arms in the temple should be
banned.
   He also told reporters in New Delhi that he thought most of
India's Sikh community had supported the siege.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-ShipFire     05-19 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Ship Fire,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Allow Some Japanese Investigators Aboard Burned Ship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials today reluctantly allowed
Japanese investigators to search a portion of a Soviet passenger
ship to determine what caused a fire that killed at least 11 people
and injured 35.
   After 70 minutes of heated negotiations with Soviet consular
officials, police agreed to pare down to 15 a team originally
consisting of more than 60 investigators.
   Police also gave in to Soviet demands that the probe be limited
to the passenger cabins of the 4,870-ton Priamurye, gutted by a
fire on Wednesday.
   All of the 129 crew members and 295 passengers listed in the
ship's registers were Soviet nationals, and all of the dead were
passengers.
   ``I have no idea why they (the Soviets) demanded this and I
don't really understand what the problem is with them,'' said
Yoshihide Yasuda, a police official in charge of the investigation.
   ``But the fact remains that our investigations are limited ...
and may not be carried out as expected,'' Yasuda said at a news
briefing.
   Earlier, Yasuda said police and firefighters had been through
the gutted ship in a preliminary probe, but the Soviets asked them
not to enter the engine room. Police had said the fire was
discovered in an area above the engine room.
   It took 18 hours for firefighters to put out the blaze aboard
the Priamurye, which was blackened and listing at dock in this port
city of western Japan. The investigative team, clad in boots and
overalls and equipped with cameras and flashlights, entered the
ship at 10:43 a.m.
   Yasuda said the 10 police, three fire department and two
Maritime Agency specialists will concentrate on a cluster of cabins
on the second deck, one level below the main deck, where nine of
the 11 bodies were found.
   Maritime official Norimasa Watanabe, in charge of emergency
measures, said earlier that a cigarette or faulty lighting could
have started the fire, which gutted most of the 85-cabin ship
registered in Vladivostok, U.S.S.R.
   Osaka Fire Department officials contacted by telephone said 15
of the original 35 injured in the fire remained hospitalized this
afternoon.
   Yasuda described as ``uncooperative'' the attitude of both
Soviet consulate officials and ship captain Aleksandr Yerastov. He
said there was little likelihood that investigations could be
completed prior to the arrival of a Soviet vessel to take back
survivors.
   Soviet crew members, including about 50 who had remained on
board the ship overnight despite police objections, began loading
food and beverage supplies to prepare to pull out as early as
Friday, officials at the site said.
   The Piramurye pulled into Osaka port Tuesday after calling on
Otaru, Hokkaido May 8 and Tokyo May 12. The vessel was to leave for
Hiroshima tonight.
   Maritime officials said the passengers, many of them in their
20s and early 30s, were visiting Japan for sightseeing purposes as
part of the Sputnik youth group tour, organized by the Soviet
Communist Youth League.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
