<DOCNO> AP880519-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugBusts     05-19 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Busts,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Drug Seizures Made in New York, Florida And Georgia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Undercover agents broke up an alleged conspiracy to funnel 1,000
pounds of cocaine every 48 hours for a month into a swanky New York
summer retreat, in one of three separate U.S. drug busts that
netted 17 arrests.
   In other actions Wednesday,Customs agents said a patrol vessel
chased down a high-speed boat running without lights in the Florida
Keys just before dawn and found more than 2 tons of cocaine aboard.
   Three Florida men and a Colombian national were arrested and
their 38-foot boat confiscated, said Customs spokesman Michael
Sheehan.
   In Mobile, Ala., federal authorities charged four people,
including a West German couple, with possession of 1{ tons of
marijuana and 236 pounds of a substance believed to be hashish oil,
with a combined street value of more than $20 million.
   Customs agent Gary Wright said the drugs were smuggled into the
Gulf Coast from a foreign distribution point apparently aboard a
35-foot sailboat.
   The plot to sell 8 tons of cocaine in the Hamptons, a chic beach
retreat on New York's Long Island, came to light when undercover
agents learned of an attempt to get a plane for flights between
Colombia and Long Island, officials said.
   ``This seizure is unbelievable, out of sight,'' said state
police Capt. Gary Heesch. ``It has not only put a major dent into
the importation of cocaine to Long Island but it has more
significantly removed the major players.''
   The first shipment, which contained 1,200 pounds of cocaine, was
seized Tuesday in Miami when the plane transporting it lost an
engine and had to land, officials said. The plane, which was headed
for Suffolk County Airport in Westhampton Beach, N.Y., had been
under surveillance since leaving Colombia.
   The pilot, Dennis Pekarchik, 40, of Boston, was arrested in
Miami and eight others, including two Colombians, were arrested
Wednesday on Long Island. All were charged with conspiracy to
import and distribute cocaine.
   Heesch, head of the special investigations bureau, estimated
that the 1,200 pounds of cocaine could have been sold for $80
million.
   Undercover agents infiltrated the plot by arranging for a jet
between Colombia and Long Island and helping handle the logistics
of the smuggling operation, using electronic surveillance
throughout the negotiations.
   Special Customs Agent Arthur Stiffel said the smuggling ring had
planned to bring in 1,000 pounds of cocaine every 48 hours for 30
days, stockpile it at various sites on Long Island and sell it in
the Hamptons.
   ``We got them on their first run,'' said Stiffel. ``They were
just gearing up so they had enough supplies during the peak sale
period of the summer.''
   In Los Angeles, meanwhile, youthful-looking undercover officers
posing as high school students made more than 230 drug buys and
arrested 171 drug dealers recently, Police Chief Daryl Gates said
Wednesday.
   Of those arrested in undercover operations at 10 high schools,
Gates said 46 were gang members. Of the total arrested, 104 were
younger than 18 years old, and of those, 101 were students.
   Drugs seized by police, mostly high potency marijuana, were
valued at about $114,330, the chief said.
</TEXT>
