<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LehderTrial     05-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberations Enter Seventh Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led after jury resumes at 9:15 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the cocaine-smuggling trial
of Carlos Lehder Rivas watched a videotape in which the reputed
Colombian cocaine lord called drugs a ``revolutionary'' weapon
against North American imperialism.
   The jury were scheduled to return today for their seventh day of
deliberations in the 7-month-old trial.
   On Wednesday, the jury reviewed a tape made by Lehder in 1985
when he was a fugitive in the jungles of Colombia, as well as a
June 29, 1983, television tape that a clean-cut Lehder made when he
was running for the Colombian Senate. In the jungle tape, Lehder
said, ``This is about political action and cocaine has become, and
marijuana has become, a revolutionary weapon in the struggle
against North American imperialism. Stimulants from Colombia are
the Achilles' heel of imperialism.''
   However, added Lehder, who prosecutors say has neo-Nazi views,
``I have never admitted that I have dealt or done any business with
drugs.''
   On the jungle tape, Lehder is dressed in a sleeveless T-shirt
and sleeveless denim jacket and has long, stringy hair, in sharp
contrast to his short hair and business suit image in court.
   The last time the jury communicated with the court before
Wednesday was Saturday, when U.S. District Judge Melton denied
requests for the testimony of three prosecution witnesses.
   Lehder appeared weary in court Wednesday. His brother, Bill
Lehder, an economist in Colombia, said he had been able to visit
the defendant during deliberations.
   ``He's very positive, energetic. He's feeling well. He's in a
good mood,'' the brother said.
   Lehder, 38, and co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, are charged
with conspiring to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United
States from Colombia, using Norman's Cay in the Bahamas, from 1978
to 1980.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, two counts of importation of
cocaine, seven counts of possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute and one charge of engaging in a continuing criminal
enteprise.
   If convicted, he could receive life plus 150 years in prison and
up to $350,000 in fines and forfeiture of his assets in the Bahamas.
   Reed, of San Pedro, Calif., is charged with a single conspiracy
count and faces up to 15 years in prison and $25,000 in fines if
convicted.
</TEXT>
