<DOCNO> AP880519-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     05-19 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Drop Sharply In Japan; Dollar Also Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped nearly 400 points
today for its biggest single-day decline this year, while the
dollar declined in narrow trading against the yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues closed at 27,373.24, falling 394.34 points, or 1.42
percent. On Wednesday the index shed 52.40 points.
   ``Apprehensions about possible inflation and rising interest
rates in the United States outweighed the expectations produced by
the dramatically reduced U.S. trade deficit,'' said Keiji Arai of
Sanyo Securities.
   On Tuesday, the U.S. Commerce Department reported the nation's
trade deficit fell more than $4 billion in March to $9.7 billion,
the lowest monthly finish since March 1985.
   Compared with Wall Street, what the Tokyo market lost was
smaller, but if Wall Street continue to sag, pulling the Dow Jones
industrial average below the 1,700-point level, investors will be
forced to ``give a second thought about the Tokyo market as well,''
he said.
   Steels and shipbuildings were under strong selling pressure.
Electricals, chemicals, non-ferrous metals also lost ground.
Certain precision metals and drugs were higher.
   Volume on the first section trading was esimated at 1 billion
shares, down from the 1.2 billion shares that changed hands on
Wednesday.
   After opening the day at 125.00 yen, down 0.53 yen from
Wednesday's finish, the dollar dipped further and closed at 124.80
yen, down 0.73 yen.
   ``The dollar's lower opening followed its decline against the
yen in New York trading,'' said an exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank.
   The dollar buying by trading houses in the morning was outpaced
by selling in the afternoon by export-related industries, said the
dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Trading was relatively quiet, however, and the dollar traded in
a narrow range between 125.00 yen to 124.75 yen without incentives
to prompt major movements among participants, he added.
</TEXT>
