<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     05-19 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Wedtech President: $1 Million to Meese Associates Were
`Payoffs'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wedtech Corp.'s former president characterized a
$1 million fee for two financial associates of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III as a payoff.
   Fred Neuberger made the statement Wednesday in testimony for the
prosecution in the trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi, Biaggi's former law
partner and five others accused of turning the now bankrupt
military contractor into a racketeering enterprise.
   Neuberger said W. Franklyn Chinn, Meese's former financial
adviser, told him the money was needed ``for friends in Washington
that he has to take care of.''
   Biaggi's lawyer, James M. LaRossa, asked Neuberger about a $1
million payment Wedtech made to Chinn and a colleague, Rusty
London, to manipulate the company's stock.
   Neuberger testified: ``Mr. Chinn also came to whisper in my ear
that he needs it for baksheesh, which means payoffs ... payola ...
grease. ''
   Chinn and Meese's former lawyer, E. Robert Wallach, have been
indicted on charges of taking bribes for trying to influence Meese.
Meese has not been indicted in the Wedtech case.
   The defense has been trying to show that Biaggi's role in
helping Wedtech win no-bid government contracts was insignificant
compared to Wedtech's ties to the Reagan administration.
   Neuberger, the third Wedtech executive to testify, backed up
earlier testimony that Wedtech paid $300,000 to help defray
Wallach's costs in defending Meese during his 1985 confirmation
hearings.
   LaRossa asked Neuberger if Wallach asked for the $300,000 ``to
assist in the defense of his friend Ed Meese'' during the
confirmation hearings.
   ``Oh yes,'' Neuberger said. ``At that time, yes. He said to me,
it's clear that he hasn't got any income now because he is involved
in the defense of Mr. Meese and he needs help for that reason. So
if we'd pay his expenses, which are very high in Washington.''
   LaRossa asked Neuberger whether it was ``your belief that you
were paying $300,000 to Mr. Wallach and, in effect, Wedtech was
paying for Meese's legal representation?''
   Replied Neuberger: ``That was my thought.' '
</TEXT>
