<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0545EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Sheldon     05-19 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Sheldon,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author Sidney Sheldon Sues Over `Hart To Hart' Compensation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Sidney Sheldon sued Columbia Pictures
and Spelling-Goldberg Productions, claiming they owe him $1.4
million in compensation for creating the television series ``Hart
To Hart.''
   Sheldon said in his Superior Court lawsuit Wednesday that he
gave Spelling-Goldberg the right in 1973 to use certain material,
which resulted in the creation of the program about a globetrotting
husband-and-wife detective team.
   The rights later were transferred to Columbia.
   The suit says Sheldon was to get 15 percent of the producer's
net profit, but several improper charges such as excessive studio
overhead, were billed to the production. Sheldon was told the
series had not produced a net profit until this year.
   Sheldon said a 1988 accounting showed the series grossed $178.9
million.
   ``Hart To Hart,'' which starred Robert Wagner and Stefanie
Powers, ran from 1979-1984 on ABC-TV.
   The lawsuit seeks $1.4 million in compensatory damages and
unspecified punitive damages.
   An after-hours call seeking comment from Columbia Pictures was
answered by a recording saying the switchboard had been shut down.
There was no Los Angeles area listing for Spelling-Goldberg
Productions.
   Sheldon is the best-selling author of such books as ``Windmills
of the Gods'' ``A Rage of Angels,'' and ``The Other Side of
Midnight.''
</TEXT>
