<DOCNO> AP880519-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0546EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Baker-USElection     05-19 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baker-US Election,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says Economy Will Help Determine Presidential Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-World Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of renewed vigor in the U.S. economy are
likely to play a role in determining the outcome of the November
presidential election, Treasury Secretary James A. Baker said today.
   ``My rosy predictions won't decide the election. If they come
true they might have some impact,'' Baker told a breakfast meeting
with reporters.
   He said the Reagan administration was sticking to a forecast
that the economy would expand by 2.4 percent this year and that
inflation would hold near the current level of 4 percent.
   ``In our view at least, there is not going to be a resurgence of
inflation,'' Baker said. ``The economy is a major factor in any
election, particularly in a presidential election. People tend to
vote their pocketbooks.
   ``We have no reason to suspect or expect that the economy is not
going to perform reasonably well.''
   Baker was in Paris for two days of talks with trade and finance
ministers from leading industrial countries.
   Some European officials expressed concern on Wednesday that U.S.
consumer demand was growing too fast, raising the risk of a revival
of worldwide inflation. Baker said he rejected this view.
   Baker also said he had no immediate plans to leave his post to
manage the fall election campaign of Vice President George Bush,
who has virtually locked up the Republican nomination.
   ``For now I'm staying at the Treasury Department,'' he said.
``What I do in the future, of course, is a matter for the vice
president and the president.''
</TEXT>
