<HEAD>Judge Rules Police Testing Plan Illegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ruled that random drug tests proposed
for Boston police officers are unconstitutional.
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert E. Keeton ruled Wednesday that
unannounced, random urine tests violate an officer's Fourth
Amendment right against unreasonable search and seizure.
   The Boston Police Patrolman's Association, which filed suit in
protest against Police Commissioner Francis Roache's proposed drug
policy in April 1986, called the ruling a ``major victory.''
   Roache's attorney, Kevin McDermott, said he will urge a federal
appeals court to reverse Keeton's ruling.
   Roache proposed testing the 2,300-member police department after
three officers were charged with drug violations in 1985.
