<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SwanDefense     05-19 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swan Defense,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Swan, Claims it Was Self-Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENFIELD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boater charged with shooting a swan with
a pistol told police he was acting in self-defense.
   John Milazzo, 39, told investigators he was canoeing in
Irondequoit Creek near Rochester on Wednesday when the swan started
paddling toward him in the water and flapping its wings, said
Robert Doe, a New York state environmental conservation officer.
   Milazzo said he tried to shoo the bird away with his paddle, but
it kept coming back until Milazzo capsized and fell in knee-deep
water, said Monroe County sheriff's Capt. John Perrone. Milazzo
shot at the bird twice, hitting it once, Perrone said.
   ``He claims the swan attacked him,'' Doe said. ``He said he had
no other choice but to draw his .38-caliber pistol and shoot.''
   The bird, a white adult muted swan, survived the wound from a
bullet that apparently passed through its body, said Dan
Michalowski, director of the Seneca Park Zoo. The bird is being
kept at the zoo's hospital, he said.
   Michalowski said swans can get belligerent with intruders and
will flap their wings and raise a fuss if they feel threatened.
   ``They're real bullies when it comes to protecting the nest. If
he invaded their territory, that can happen,'' Michalowski said.
   Milazzo was charged with a violation of state conservation law
for shooting a protected bird. The violation carries a potential
fine of $250 and 15-day jail sentence, Doe said.
</TEXT>
