<HEAD>Judge Won't Seek Re-Election; Wife Gets Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politics may make for strange bedfellows,
but in the race for the Newton County judge's office, two bed
partners are making for some strange politics.
   Alton Campbell, a convicted felon, decided not to run for
re-election, even though he won the Republican nomination March 8.
That decision prompted the county's GOP township committee to
certify the second-place finisher: Campbell's wife, Verdell.
   Both Campbells declined comment when asked if their husband-wife
politics was meant to hang on to political clout. But the incumbent
characterized the race as friendly: ``We're probably the only two
candidates who sleep together,'' he said.
   Mrs. Campbell filed for the spot after her husband's conviction
last April on federal vote-buying charges. He received a three-year
prison sentence and a $5,000 fine. A three-member panel of the 8th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals recently upheld that decision and
Campbell filed a petition asking the full court to review his
appeal.
   Campbell said he plans to finish his fifth term and has no
intention of resigning. Mrs. Campbell faces Democrat Clinton
Daniels in the November general election.
