<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in thin European trading this morning, and traders
suggested it will remain in a narrow trading range for the rest of
the week. Gold prices rose.
   Earlier, the dollar fell 0.73 yen to a closing of 124.80 yen in
Tokyo, in what traders said was a correction following sharp gains
on the back of Tuesday's narrower-than-expected $9.75 billion U.S.
trade deficit for March.
   ``The dollar overshot a reasonable range after the trade
figures,'' said a currency dealer in Milan, Italy. ``But in ...
Europe, it seems to have found a more sustainable level.''
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   --1.6988 West German marks, down from 1.7055
   --1.4150 Swiss francs, down from 1.4215
   --5.7517 French francs, down from 5.7700
   --1.9022 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9090
   --1,261.30 Italian lire, down from 1,265.50
   --1.2434 Canadian dollars, up from 1.24125
   In London, the dollar was also quoted at 124.75 yen, and one
British pound cost $1.8660, more expensive for buyers than late
Wednesday's $1.8605.
   Gold prices firmed in moderate European trading, boosted by
Wednesday's gains in New York, bullion dealers said.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$456.65 a troy ounce at midmorning, up from the opening bid of
$455.50 and late Wednesday's $453.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $456.60, up from $454 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.02 to close at a bid $457.56.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid $6.70 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $6.58.
