<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Thunderstorms Over Much Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dropped heavy rain on parts of Pennsylvania today,
sending streams over their banks, while rain and drizzle fell over
much of the northern Atlantic Coast and the upper Ohio Valley.
   Showers and thunderstorms were common from western Minnesota and
the eastern Dakotas to the central and southern High Plains.
   A few showers dampened Florida. Widely scattered showers fell
over the central Rockies and the Pacific Northwest. Fair skies
prevailed elsewhere in the nation.
   A thunderstorm in Nebraska spawned a tornado Wednesday evening
south of Hershey, but no damage was reported. Thunderstorms
produced dime-size hail north of Pecos, Texas, and at Statesville
and Mooresville, N.C., and small hail in Colorado.
   Several high-temperature records were set Wednesday, including
92 degrees in Fargo, N.D., topping the 90-degree record set in
1941; 94 in Lake Charles, La., beating the 92-degree mark of 1961;
and 93 in Port Arthur, Texas, besting by one degree the 1933 record.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
eastern lower Michigan, eastern Indiana and Kentucky to the
Atlantic Coast, from central Maine to Maryland and Delaware, and
from northwest Wisconsin to the upper Mississippi Valley, South
Dakota, Nebraska, Wyoming, eastern Colorado, western Kansas and
northern New Mexico. Sunny skies were predicted for much of the
rest of the nation.
   Highs were expected to be in the upper 50s and 60s in New
England, the northern half of the Appalachians, the lower Great
Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley; 50s from northern Colorado to
central Wyoming; 60s from North Dakota to western South Dakota, the
upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies and the northern Pacific Coast;
upper 80s and 90s from northern Florida to the central Gulf Coast,
the lower Mississippi Valley, Oklahoma and the eastern two-thirds
of Texas; and in the 90s in the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs
will generally reach the 70s and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at McCall, Idaho, to 79 at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 58 fair; Boston 50 drizzle; Buffalo 51 foggy;
Charleston, S.C., 64 fair; Cincinnati 56 partly cloudy; Cleveland
52 foggy; Detroit 58 cloudy; Miami 74 fair; New York 56 cloudy;
Philadelphia 57 drizzle; Pittsburgh 55 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 54
foggy; Washington 63 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 cloudy; Chicago 52 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
69 fair; Denver 51 rain; Des Moines 62 fair; Indianapolis 53 fair;
Kansas City 65 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 63 cloudy;
Nashville 56 fair; New Orleans 67 fair; St. Louis 59 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 56 partly cloudy; Anchorage 50 cloudy; Las
Vegas 72 fair; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 77 fair; Salt Lake City
52 partly cloudy; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle
50 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 cloudy; Toronto 55 drizzle.
</TEXT>
