<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Dissident     05-19 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Dissident,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor Of Dissident Journal Says Police Shut It Down Through
Seizure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of a well-known Soviet dissident
journal said police held him for a week and seized the computer and
printer he uses to produce the magazine as well as its archives.
   KGB security police ``even took all the pictures off the
walls,'' Sergei I. Grigoryants told reporters in his Moscow
apartment on Wednesday.
   The editor said that his arrest and detention show that Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's promised reforms have not ended civil rights
violations by the state security apparatus.
   The former political prisoner was arrested May 9 with four other
people at a small country house he uses to produce his 11-month-old
unofficial magazine, named Glasnost after Gorbachev's policies of
more openness in society.
   Grigoryants, a literary expert, said the officers had no arrest
or search warrants, and a judge convicted him of ``malicous
disobedience'' of a police officer and sentenced him to seven days
in jail without a proper trial.
   ``It is a result of the demonstrably sharp deterioration in the
situation in the country of people's rights,'' he said.
   The actions show that Gorbachev's drive for democratization of
Soviet society and openness has not meant more tolerance of
dissent, Grigoryants said.
   Grigoryants was released from jail on Monday and the following
day tried to visit the house in the village of Kratkovo, 25 miles
southeast of Moscow.
   Police sealed off the house and prevented him from entering,
saying he must prove to a prosecutor he has the right to live there
and that his property won't be returned until he shows evidence it
belongs to him.
   Grigoryants said, however, that a prosecutor told him the matter
should be taken up with the militia. ``It's not even clear to whom
to turn,'' he said.
   The editors of Glasnost hope to continue publishing, but they
are having trouble getting needed equipment and offices.
   Glasnost was the first privately controlled periodical to be
published openly in the Soviet Union. Past dissident magazines had
been published clandestinely and many of their publishers were
arrested.
   Grigoryants was sentenced in 1983 to 10 years in prison for
writing for an underground bulletin on human rights. He was
pardoned in February 1987.
   His arrest May 9 came hours before a group seeking to found a
political party called the Democratic Union planned to meet in his
offices.
   The group met instead at a nearby club to form the party, which
seeks to challenge the Communist Party's political monopoly.
   The weekly newspaper Moscow News has accused the Democratic
Union of seeking to replace socialism with capitalism and called
its members ``convinced enemies of our system, the political and
economic system of the Soviet Union.''
   The Democratic Union calls for multiparty parliamentary
democracy, independent trade unions, a new constitution and the
withdrawal of Soviet troops from Eastern Europe and areas of the
Soviet Union seized in World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r n PM-McKinleyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0406 05-19 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-McKinley Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0406,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Describe Death on North America's Highest Peak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of death, climb, other
injuries. ADDS byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENALI MEDICAL CAMP, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new expedition led by the
first man to conquer Mount McKinley alone in winter ended less than
1,000 feet from the top when one climber apparently froze to death
and three others suffered hypothermia.
   Lynn Salerno, 31, died early Wednesday at the 19,500-foot level
of North America's highest peak, the National Park Service said.
Two other members of the nine-person expedition were evacuated by
helicopter.
   ``We had a beautiful experience turn into a nightmare,'' one
exhausted climber, Leonard Kelly, said as he clutched a hot cup of
tea at Denali Medical Camp at the 14,000-foot level of Mount
McKinley.
   ``It's unbelievable that one minute you can be on top of the
world, and in the next minute under it,'' Kelly said.
   The expedition, which began about May 1, was led by veteran
guide Vern Tejas, who last March became the first mountaineer to
survive a winter climb to McKinley's 20,320-foot summit.
   According to accounts from expedition members, Tejas called a
conference at about 8 p.m. Tuesday, after nearly 10 hours on the
trail. They were still more than 1,000 feet below the summit.
   Tejas warned that the approaching night would be bitterly cold.
He told them to make individual decisions on whether to continue.
   Kelly, at 57 the oldest member of the party, said he had
intestinal cramps and decided to turn back with another man, Dave
Burns. Tejas sent assistant guide John Swider to accompany them to
the 17,200-foot camp. The others, led by Tejas, went on.
   Before the trio reached the haven, Swider fell on the steep,
rocky terrain. He was saved from certain death only when Kelly
secured them using an ice ax.
   ``We all ended up in kind of a blob, hanging on, looking at each
other, because the next step was really kind of a big one _ like a
couple of thousand feet right off the ridge, going straight down,''
Kelly said.
   Other climbers saw the fall and went to the rescue.
   Swider, who had head lacerations and a back injury, and Kelly
were helped back to camp, where they spent a long night worrying
about their companions.
   The others had it even worse.
   Some 500 feet below the summit, Lynn Salerno began acting
irrationally.
   It remains unclear whether she was ailing from hypothermia or
some sort of altitude sickness, but she grew increasingly cold and
unresponsive, the climbers said.
   While others worked desperately to warm her, Tejas tried to dig
a snow shelter in the icy, rocky terrain, but in a matter of
minutes she was dead.
   ``She was such a strong supporter of Vern's,'' Kelly said. ``She
was practically on the trip because of him'' after hearing him
describe his mountain experiences at a talk in Anchorage.
   Kelly was assisted down the mountain Wednesday evening by other
climbers. He was treated for three frostbitten toes.
   Swider and Mike Moss, 50, of Minnesota, who had severely
frostbitten feet, were flown off the mountain to a hospital in
Anchorage.
   Tejas remained with the rest of the expedition at 17,200 feet.
Two reportedly were recovering well from hypothermia.
   ``I felt like we had the best guide in the world,'' Kelly said.
``He did everything in the world a human being could be expected to
do in a dangerous occupation like this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
