<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FraternitySuspended     05-19 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fraternity Suspended,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frat Suspended for Hanging Battered Female Mannequin From Balcony</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fraternity Rape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLEBURY, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Middlebury College
suspended a fraternity for hanging a battered female mannequin
splattered with red paint from a balcony during a toga party
earlier this month.
   College President Olin Robison on Wednesday accepted the
recommendation of the school's community council to ban the Delta
Upsilon fraternity from living in its house next year or
functioning as a social organization.
   Members of Delta Upsilon also must participate in a sexism
awareness course, said college spokesman Ron Nief.
   The fraternity was deluged with criticism last week after
several students complained about the mannequin used as a
decoration at the party.
   The mannequin's breasts were mutilated and splattered with red
paint, and its head and face were bashed in, according to a letter
of complaint seven students wrote to Robison.
   The action was characterized as being sexist and insensitive to
violent crimes against women.
   In a statement, Robison said, ``It is at just such times as this
that we recognize how very much our community depends upon a shared
acknowledgement of the limits of permissable behavior.
   ``Our very survival as a community of learning requires both a
generous amount of tolerance and a concomitant willingness to
insist that there is ... a point beyond which our tolerance cannot
and must not be stretched,'' Robison said. ``This recent episode
has defined, and defined appropriately, such a limit.''
   The fraternity called the council's decision too severe.
   Jennifer Weiss, one of the students who complained, said she was
pleased that a sexism awareness program would result from the
complaint.
   After the end of the school year, the council will decide
whether the fraternity should be placed on probation, suspended for
another year or closed. The council is made up of students, faculty
and staff members.
</TEXT>
