<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FraternityRape 1stLd-Writethru a0526 05-19 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fraternity Rape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Fraternity Members Indicted in Rape Case, Chapter Suspended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 1 graf to ADD suspension of Delta Upsilon fraternity in
Vermont.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three fraternity members were indicted
in the rape of an 18-year-old Florida State University student who
was near death from drinking.
   A grand jury on Wednesday indicted an FSU student, a Tallahassee
Community College student and an Auburn University student on
charges stemming from the March 5 incident at the Pi Kappa Alpha
house.
   The students were arrested last month, and are free on bond.
   Daniel G. Oltarsh, 23, of Fort Lauderdale and Byron L. Stewart,
21, of Orlando were charged with sexual battery. Oltarsh and Jason
J. McPharlin, 19, of Plantation were charged with kidnapping to
facilitate the commission of a felony.
   Oltarsh, the FSU student, was charged with battery in the
scrawling of a fraternity symbol and other writing on the woman's
leg and with aiding in the possession of alcohol by a person under
21.
   The indictment alleged that McPharlin, the Auburn student, and
Oltarsh carried the victim, who had passed out and was near death
from alcohol intoxication, from the Pi Kappa Alpha house to a
neighboring frat house, where they abandoned her.
   The victim was hospitalized for treatment of scratches, bruises
and abrasions.
   Following the indictment, Raymond Orians, the fraternity's
national executive vice president in Memphis, Tenn., said the FSU
chapter had been suspended and that an undetermined number of its
members would be expelled.
   The grand jury, which had complained in an interim report that
fraternity members had been uncooperative, reiterated the complaint
in a final report Wednesday.
   After the interim report and a university order disbanding the
fraternity for five years, a fraternity member stepped forward, the
grand jury said.
   Information from the fraternity member led to two of the
arrests, and another frat member who admitted involvement in the
incident was granted immunity in exchange for information leading
to the third arrest.
   According to the grand jury, the informant described sexual
activities all four had with the woman, and said they dressed her
as she sat slumped on the floor. He said they verbally abused her
and repeatdly told her they were members of another fraternity and
that they were in that fraternity's house, the panel said.
   The victim admitted she violated the state's drinking age law
against consumption by those under 21, but the grand jury urged she
not be prosecuted because of the circumstances.
   The panel recommended that university police monitor areas where
there is drinking, and urged FSU administrators to establish a
mandatory first-semester orientation course on date rape, drug and
alcohol abuse, personal safety and the availability of counseling
services.
   University President Bernie Sliger thanked the grand jury for
its recommendations, and said he had already directed FSU officials
to take actions requested by the Board of Regents.
   ``This university has made it clear it will not tolerate conduct
which demeans the human spirit,'' Sliger said.
   In Middlebury, Vt., on Wednesday, Middlebury College President
Olin Robison suspended the Delta Upsilon fraternity for using a
female mannequin that had been battered, mutilated and spattered
with red paint as a decoration at a toga party. The fraternity was
heavily criticized after students complained about the mannequin.
</TEXT>
