<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Army-Drugs     05-19 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Army-Drugs,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head of Joint Chiefs Says Drug-Trade Assault Would Mean Tradeoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff said
the armed forces will carry out any anti-drug assignments that
Congress decides upon, but he warned the practice could compromise
civil rights.
   ``Putting an end to the drug problem would be much broader than
our mission,'' Adm. William J. Crowe Jr. said at a news conference
Wednesday before a luncheon speech to the Economic Club of Detroit.
   ``I think there are things we can do, primarily identification,
surveillance and tracking of people bringing in drugs in illicit
fashion,'' Crowe said.
   But, he warned, ``to solve the drug problem and still guarantee
all Americans the rights and privileges they enjoy today is a
difficult thing. ... To truly stop the flow of drugs you would have
to increase police powers and do some searches and seizures that
are not contemplated today.''
   The Senate last week approved a provision giving the military an
expanded role in stopping drug smuggling, including new arrest
powers for Navy officers aboard warships that stop suspected drug
boats on the high seas.
   The House has passed a more far-reaching provision, ordering the
president to have the military essentially seal off U.S. borders
against illegal drug trafficking.
   The provisions were attached to the Defense Department's budget,
which is being debated on Capitol Hill.
   Crowe also said he did not expect increased U.S. military
activity in Panama would force the exit of its leader, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   The admiral said he did not know when U.S. involvement might end
in the Persian Gulf.
   ``I do not see any short-term or long-term end to the Iran-Iraq
war,'' he said, adding that the United States is committed to
protecting shipping in the gulf.
   ``As long as those interests are in jeopardy, we will be
there,'' Crowe said. ``Of course, the government never said it
would be a short-term operation.''
</TEXT>
