<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     05-19 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino To Convene Crisis Committee After Court Issues Summons to
Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said she
will convene her Cabinet's crisis committee to discuss the
implications of a summons a Philippine court issued to her ousted
predecessor, Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino told reporters on Wednesday that she would convene
the committee soon to discuss the summons issued on Tuesday by the
anti-graft court, the Sandiganbayan.
   The summons stems from a $2.5 billion lawsuit filed by the
Presidential Commission on Good Government to recover some of the
$10 billion it alleges Marcos stole during his 20 years in office.
   Mrs. Aquino has barred Marcos from returning from Hawaiian exile
to the Philippines, from which he was forced in a February 1986
popular uprising.
   Government sources said the committee must study the legal
implications of the lawsuit, including whether the summons can be
served on Marcos in Hawaii and if so, whether he has a legal right
to return to answer the charges.
   A source at the anti-graft court said on condition of anonymity
that the summons was forwarded to the Department of Foreign Affairs
but had not yet been sent on to Honolulu.
   The source said Marcos and his wife Imelda could respond in
writing within 60 days of receiving the order. Legal sources said
it was not clear whether Marcos could demand to answer the charges
personally in Manila.
   On Wednesday, police fired tear gas and smoke bombs to halt a
rally and march to the U.S. Embassy by protesters demanding that
Marcos be allowed to return for his mother's funeral.
   Organizers said at least four women and two children were hurt.
Police said there were minor injuries to several demonstrators but
did not give a figure.
   About 5,000 demonstrators rallied to urge the government to
allow Marcos to return to attend the funeral of his mother, Josefa
Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4. A breakaway group of 2,000
demonstrators, chanting ``If you want trouble, we will give you
trouble!'' later marched toward the embassy and were blocked near
City Hall by 50 policemen.
   A police spokesman said the demonstrators were dispersed when
they started throwing stones at the officers, who fought back with
truncheons and later used tear gas and smoke bombs to disperse the
marchers. The marchers later regrouped in the central Bonifacio
Square to protest the dispersal.
</TEXT>
