<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka-India     05-19 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka-India,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Says Indian Troops Will Withdraw</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior government minister told
Parliament today that Indian troops battling Tamil rebels in the
north and east will withdraw from the island nation.
   ``The government is very keen to see the Indian peacekeeping
troops leave. They are definitely going,'' said Gamini Dissanayake,
land and river development minister.
   Dissanayake said the withdrawal would be in stages but that the
date of the pullout has not been discussed yet. He did not
elaborate.
   Indian Defense Minister K.C. Pant is scheduled to arrive in
Colombo this week to discuss peace proposals with Tamil militants,
who have been fighting for a separate homeland since 1983.
   India and Sri Lanka signed a peace accord in July 29, 1987 to
end the Tamil separatist war in Sri Lanka's northern and eastern
provinces. The accord, which grants some autonomy to the minority
Tamils in exchange for a surrender of weapons, has been rejected by
the militants.
   Indian troops landed on July 30, 1987 to disarm the militants
and enforce the peace pact, and an estimated 50,000 Indian soldiers
are now in Sri Lanka.
   India, a regional power, became involved because of its own 60
million ethnic Tamils, who are politically powerful and have close
ties with the Sri Lankan Tamils.
   A senior police official, meanwhile, reported that Sinhalese
extremists killed a candidate of the governing United National
Party in the central Kandy district on Wednesday night.
   The officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified the
victim as Jayaratna Heenbanda, who was going to run for the
provincial council elections.
   A 19-year-old student, Aruna Saman Dissanayake, also was killed
Wednesday when gunmen shot at another government party candidate,
Sella Jayakody, at Horona town, just south of Colombo.
   Sinhalese extremists also oppose the accord on grounds that it
gives too many concessions to the Tamils. They have vowed to kill
government officials, politicians and others who support the peace
pact.
   Tamils are 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people, most of
whom are Sinhalese. Tamils say they are discriminated against by
the Sinhalese, who control the government and the military.
</TEXT>
