<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Hear Arguments For Retrying Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CLARIFY that no decision made to reopen
trial. Pick up 6th graf pvs: `President P.W...' TRIMS thereafter.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge will hear defense
arguments next month that the ``Sharpeville Six'' defendants should
be spared death for complicity in the mob killing of a black
official, court officers said.
   The black defendants _ five men and a woman _ were scheduled to
hang March 18 for their role in the 1984 mob slaying of a black
town councilor in Sharpeville, south of Johannesburg.
   However, a stay of execution was granted March 17 in the case,
which has attracted international attention and widespread appeals
for clemency.
   Pretoria Supreme Court Justice W.J. Human this week gave
permission to defense lawyers to present arguments June 6 on why
the trial should be reopened. The lawyers say they have evidence
that a key state witness was coerced into giving false testimony.
   The Justice Department said Wednesday that no decision had been
made on whether to reopen the trial. It noted that government
prosecutors would be arguing against the application to try the
defendants again.
   President P.W. Botha has said he will not intervene in the case.
   The trial caused debate in part because the six were not
convicted of contributing physically to the death of councilor
Jacob Dlamini. Instead, they were convicted under the doctrine of
common purpose, which held them responsible because they actively
joined the mob.
   The killing occurred during riots provoked by a rent increase in
Sharpeville and neighboring townships.
   Also Wednesday, police said a former mental patient on Tuesday
night killed two officers, including one accused by black squatters
of organizing vigilante gangs against them.
   The 30-year-old white man who killed the officers in a shootout
was identified as Christopher Du Plooy. He later was killed by
police who stormed his house in Fish Hoek, a coastal town on the
Cape Peninsula.
   One of the slain police officers, Warrant Officer Hendrick
Barnard, was a Cape Town policeman for 20 years. The white officer
usually worked in impoverished black townships and squatter camps
east of Cape Town.
   Last year, he was injured in a hand grenade attack in one
township.
   Many blacks said Barnard was connected with attacks and
factional fighting aimed at intimidating or displacing squatters.
Barnard has been mentioned frequently in an ongoing court action
filed by squatters who were burned out of their shacks in 1986.
   The plaintiffs said that Barnard and other officers either
encouraged or condoned an onslaught on the squatter camp by black
vigilantes. Some witnesses have testified they saw Barnard in a van
leading a force of 1,000 vigilantes, and others say they saw him
distributing incendiary devices.
   Scores of people were killed and more than 70,000 burned out of
their homes during attacks on the squatters in May and June 1986.
   Barnard said police tried to stop the violence but were unable
to move through the densely packed shanties in vehicles and
considered it too dangerous to go on foot.
   Some squatters have banded together to resist attempts to
relocate them, and the government considers other squatter
communities strongholds of anti-apartheid militants.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
