<2ND_LINE>PM-Kuwait-Explosion, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0469,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Killed in Blast Planned To Park Car Near Airline, Official
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with officials saying men tried
to park car near airline office. Pick up 6th graf pvs, `The
previous...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said today that two men killed in a
car bomb explosion were planning to park the automobile near the
headquarters of the Kuwait Airways Corp., but the explosives
apparently went off prematurely.
   An Interior Ministry spokesman identified the men killed in the
explosion Wednesday as Nasser Mohammed Ali Hassan Ahmed, 22, and
Walid Abdel-Nabi Mohammed Mousa Al-Mousa, 23. Both were Kuwaitis.
   ``They were killed as a punishment for their intended crimes,''
said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity under
ministry rules. ``They wanted to plant the explosive somewhere in
the area.''
   He did not say what detonated the bomb on a main downtown
avenue. The explosion, about 25 yards from the airline's office,
destroyed the car and killled both men.
   No other casualties or damage were reported.
   Shops in the area were closed because Wednesday was the third
day of the Moslem feast of Id el Fitr, which marks the end of the
holy month of Ramadan. There would have been few pedestrians in the
area at the time of the blast, residents said.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they believe
that the driver wanted to park the Mazda-929 in front of the
airline's headquarters.
   The explosion was the third in this northern Persian Gulf
country in a month. Kuwait is close to the Iran-Iraq warfront and
has been the target of attacks blamed on pro-Iranian terrorists.
   The previous explosions occurred in the same area of the capital.
   The first, on April 27, injured a guard near the offices of the
Saudi national airline. Then on May 7, an explosion occurred at the
offices of Avis, the American car rental company.
   A Kuwaiti newspaper recently reported three people were arrested
in connection with the earlier blasts. Authorities have not
confirmed the report.
   A Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 was commandeered last month on a
flight from Bangkok by gunmen who have been identified as
pro-Iranian Moslem extremists. Two of its Kuwaiti passengers were
killed during the 16-day ordeal and the other passengers and crew
were released.
   The hijackers sought the release of 17 people convicted of
bombing the U.S. and French embassies, the same demand made by the
captors of pro-Iranian groups holding 18 foreigners hostage in
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
