<2ND_LINE>PM-Sasson-Judge Threatened,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sasson Jeans Head Charged with Threatening Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who built Sasson Jeans Inc. into a
multimillion-dollar business before winding up in bankruptcy court
has been charged with threatening the judge who is hearing the
firm's bankruptcy reorganization case.
   ``I did not threaten anybody. I am astonished to see I have been
accused of this,'' Paul Guez told U.S. Magistrate Barbara A. Lee
during a hearing Wednesday in which prosecutors sought to have him
detained without bail.
   Guez had been arrested and charged with threatening the life of
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland.
   Guez claimed the charges were ``part of a conspiracy'' to block
his attendance at an afternoon hearing on Sasson's Chapter 11
reorganization plan.
   The magistrate ordered Guez, who was dressed in a rumpled gray
suit and white shirt without a tie, held overnight.
   According to federal prosecutors, Guez, 43, threatened to kill
Lifland and the trustee he appointed to oversee Sasson's
reorganization ``if a result contrary to his interest were to be
reached.''
   FBI agents arrested Guez on Wednesday afternoon at the lower
Manhattan building that houses bankruptcy court.
   The allegations of threats on Lifland were based on information
supplied by an informant described as a lawyer with ``a privileged
professional relationship'' with Guez.
   The complaint further stated that ``due to the tone and
demeanor'' of Guez, the informant believed he was ``fully capable
of carrying out his threat.''
   Sasson has been in bankruptcy proceedings since October 1986. On
Wednesday, Lifland approved the sale of the company's name for $8
million to Stanwich Partners of Stamford, Conn.
   The Tunisian-born Guez arrived in the United States in 1976 with
$74 and a new style of French cut jeans. Through clever advertising
he made millions, also licensing the Sasson label for watches,
lingerie and luggage.
   But the company, beset by to internal feuds, was swamped by
lawsuits leading to the Chapter 11 reorganization.
</TEXT>
