<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Angola     05-19 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Angola,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Troops Reported Within 45 Miles Of Namibian Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban troops in Angola have
moved south and are within 45 miles of the border with South-West
Africa, a newspaper reported today.
   Business Day, citing unidentified South African intelligence
sources, said the Cubans were concentrated in five areas in
south-central Angola.
   The newspaper did not say how many Cuban troops were involved.
Defense Minister Magnus Malan said Monday that up to 9,000 of the
more than 40,000 Cuban soldiers in Angola were advancing.
   South African and Angolan officials have met twice this month in
a bid to resolve the 13-year-old civil war in the former Portuguese
colony.
   Angola's Marxist government is supported by the Cuban forces,
while South Africa and the United States support the rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   U.S. officials said South Africa and Angola, joined by the
United States and Cuba, are scheduled to meet next week in
Brazzaville, Congo.
   South Africa and Angola have said initial talks were cordial,
but South African officials continue to make hostile statements.
   Malan had suggested that South Africa may have to respond
militarily to the reported Cuban troop movements.
   Angola says South Africa has 9,000 troops in its territory
backed by heavy artillery. South Africa says it has never had more
than 3,000 troops in Angola since it began deploying combat forces
there a year ago.
   A resolution of the Angolan conflict also could lead to a
political settlement in neighboring South-West Africa, also known
as Namibia.
   South Africa administers the territory in violation of a U.N.
resolution and says it has no plans to grant independence until
Cuban forces leave Angola.
</TEXT>
