<HEAD>Investigators Claim Attacks Masterminded From Austria and Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLZANO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators today blamed recent bombings
in the northern Alto Adige region on neo-Nazi groups based in West
Germany and Austria.
   ``The bombs were probably placed by German-speaking extremists
inspired by neo-Nazi groups based in Bavaria and the north Tyrol,''
said Renato Compagnone, chief of Bolzano's squad that handles
politically linked crimes. He did not say what information led him
to that conclusion.
   Alto Adige, also known as South Tyrol, borders Austria and has
many German-speaking residents. North Tyrol refers to an Austrian
region along the border.
   In the provincial capital of Bolzano on Tuesday, bombs went off
outside two buildings housing Italian-speaking families and outside
the local offices of the Italian state-run television RAI and the
Italian telephone company SIP. There were no injuries.
   Mario Martin, the local state prosecutor, was quoted by Rome's
daily La Repubblica as saying the explosions ``may signal the
beginning of a terrorist escalation in the region.''
   The attacks were claimed, in a leaflet distributed in Vienna, by
a German-speaking extremist organization called ``Ein Tirol'' (One
Tyrol) which seeks self-determination for Alto Adige and opposes a
recent agreement between the Italian government and the local party
Sued Tiroler Volkspartei.
   The party's president, Silvius Magnago, and Eva Klotz, who heads
the South Tyrolean patriotic league Heimatbund, have criticized the
resurgence of extremism in the region.
   The tense relations between Italian-speaking and German-speaking
residents in the popular Alpine resort area was credited for
sizeable gains by Italy's neo-fascist party MSI in the last
provincial elections.
   Italian police tightened security in the area following reports
that a large amount of explosives was stolen this week at Neustift,
an Austrian town just across the border.
</TEXT>
