<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlowingDust     05-19 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blowing Dust,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blowing Dust Called Worst In 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unusually arid spring has kicked up what
meteorologists are calling the worst blowing dust in at least a
decade, damaging crops and creating hazardous driving conditions in
Minnesota, South and North Dakota.
   Light rain that fell in parts of northern Minnesota and North
Dakota today will help somewhat, said Sam Standfield of the
National Weather Service in Minneapolis.
   ``It will help at least keep the dust down for a while, but
we're going to need more rain than this to end the drought
problem,'' Standfield said.
   In northern Minnesota, the dry spring has caused the worst
conditions of blowing dust in a decade, said William Larson, head
of the University of Minnesota's soil science department.
   The dust has been even worse in North Dakota, says state
climatologist John Enz. ``Over most of the state, we've had the
driest September-through-April since the 1930s,'' he said.
   Conditions are poor in the northeast and northcentral sections
of South Dakota, where officials have declared an agricultural
disaster in 13 counties, said state climatologist Bill Lytle.
   ``There have been a lot of calls from farmers reporting crop
damage,'' said Wally Nelson, superintendent of the Southwest
Experiment Station of the University of Minnesota at Lamberton.
   Blowing dust around Aberdeen, S.D., has filled ditches along
roads, and police closed roads in that area around two weeks ago
when a heavy storm made visibility dangerously low and began
causing accidents.
</TEXT>
