   The Supreme Court meanwhile ordered a military tribunal to stop
the arraignment of two other officers, Lt. Col. Eduardo Kapunan and
Lt. Col. Nelson Eslao. They have been charged with the same
offense, but on Wednesday asked the court in a petition halt the
arraignment and release them.
   The five officers were accused of voluntarily joining the mutiny
led by former Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan and denouncing the Aquino
government in a letter read over a radio station in Baguio City,
where the military academy is located. Honasan is still at large.
   In their petition, Kapunan and Eslao accused chief of staff Gen.
Renato de Villa and other officers of ``grave abuse of authority''
in filing the case against them. The court gave military
authorities 10 days to answer the charge.
   A regional Philippine Constabulary commander said today that
vice mayor Aquilino Cantiaga was ambushed Monday in the coastal
town of Albuera, 360 miles southeast of Manila.
   Brig. Gen. Lorenzo Mateo said an undetermined number of
communist New People's Army rebels positioned on both sides of an
isolated road in Albuera fired on the jeep carrying Cantiaga, three
bodyguards and a civilian companion.
   The vice mayor was unhurt, but the civilian was killed and three
bodyguards were wounded in the gunfire, Mateo said.
   On the island of Negros, guerrillas killed two soldiers and two
government militiamen in a clash Wednesday in the town of Isabela,
130 miles southwest of Albuera, a military report said. It said two
rebels died in the fighting.
</TEXT>
