<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-Massacre 1stLd-Writethru a0457 05-19 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Massacre, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0457,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Provincial Council Claims Soldiers Killed 100 Peasants In Peru</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lede to CLARIFY; SUBS 7th pvs: `It said ...' to
INCLUDE bayonets used</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top elective body in Ayacucho Province
said soldiers entered a village and massacred about 100 peasants in
retaliation for a rebel ambush of an army convoy.
   The military, in a communique issued late Wednesday, called the
charges unfounded and said they were aimed at blocking efforts to
capture the Maoist Shining Path rebels. In Lima, lawmakers said the
government would investigate.
   The alleged massacre reportedly occurred just hours before Pope
John Paul II arrived in Peru during a four-nation South American
tour. He did not travel to Ayacucho, which is 230 miles southeast
of Lima.
   The leftist-oriented Ayacucho Provincial Council said troops
swarmed into Cayara, 50 miles south of this provincial capital, on
Saturday and slaughtered the peasants.
   Cayara residents told council members soldiers
``indiscriminately'' killed 30 to 50 defenseless young men who were
harvested corn in fields surrounding the town of 1,000 people, the
council said in a statement Wednesday.
   Residents said troops then herded 50 more peasants into a chapel
and killed them, the statement claimed.
   It said townspeople told the council they were unsure how many
people were killed because the attackers poured gasoline on and
burned some bodies and because many people had gone into hiding. It
said the troops used bayonets to kill many of them.
   The council is headed by Ayacucho Mayor Fermin Azparrent, a
member of the Marxist opposition party the United Left.
   Senate President Jorge Lozada said the government of President
Alan Garcia would investigate.
   Leftist and human rights groups have frequently accused the
military in the past few years of killing civilians in areas where
rebel activity is intense and soldiers suspect villagers of
sympathizing with the insurgents.
   The Ayacucho military command said on Wednesday that 100
guerrillas of the Shining Path movement ambushed two army trucks
around midnight on Friday near Cayara. It said four soldiers and
six guerrillas were killed and 15 troops wounded in the fighting.
   Wednesday's communique, the first official description of the
attack, said troop reinforcements pursued the guerrillas and the
two sides clashed again on Saturday, causing ``unverified
casualties among the subversives.''
   The military communique said Cayara residents had fled and the
town was empty when troops arrived on Saturday. It said four bodies
were found in the chapel.
   Ayacucho's impoverished highlands were the birthplace and remain
the stronghold of the Shining Path. The eight-year insurgency has
cost more than 10,000 lives, mainly those of peasants caught up in
the violence between guerrillas and government forces.
   Police in the provincial capital say the Shining Path has
murdered hundreds of villagers in the province, more than 100 so
far this year, who it accuses of supporting the army.
   The province had been under direct military control since late
1982.
   Residents of the province have linked the military with the
deaths of nearly 150 peasants in three earlier purported massacres
since Garcia took office in July 1985.
   Charges by human rights groups that the military has waged a
``dirty war'' against peasants have eased, however, during Garcia's
term.
</TEXT>
