<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Wright-Ethics 2ndLd-Writethru a0564 05-19 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wright-Ethics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564,530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with Wright statement today.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today that the
government watchdog group Common Cause was wrongly accusing him of
unethical behavior and that his actions were ``clearly legal and
proper.''
   Common Cause president Fred Wertheimer announced on Wednesday
that his group, which monitors and suggests ways of enforcing
ethical practices by public officials, was requesting an
investigation by the House ethics committee into whether Wright
violated conflict-of-interest rules.
   Wright, D-Texas, for months has been the subject of published
reports about his activities on behalf of Texas associates and
campaign contributors.
   According to the reports, Wright receives 55 percent of the
royalties, far above the normal 10 to 15 percent, for his book,
``Reflections of a Public Man.'' The book, published by longtime
campaign supporter William Carlos Moore, has earned Wright more
than $54,000.
   Moore's firms reportedly received more than $250,000 for
campaign services during 1985 and 1986 from Wright's re-election
committee.
   Wertheimer said the ethics committee needs to examine whether
the speaker's campaign committees were at all involved in either
publishing or selling the book, which he said could be a violation
of House or other federal conflict-of-interest rules.
   The committee also needs to determine whether Wright improperly
sought special treatment for constituents and party campaign
contributors in connection with the regulatory activities of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, including blocking legislation,
Wertheimer said.
   ``Common Cause believes that it is in the best interests of the
public, the House of Representatives and of Speaker Wright for the
House ethics committee to examine and resolve these matters,''
Wertheimer wrote in a letter to the ethics panel.
   ``We further believe that in conducting its inquiry, the
committee should retain an outside counsel, as it has done on a
number of occasions in the past,'' to ``ensure that the results of
the inquiry are credible to and accepted by the public.''
   Wright said today his discussions with the banking officials
were part of a congressman's job. ``This action is clearly legal
and proper,'' he said.
   ``Most members of Congress intercede regularly on behalf of
constituents with the various regulatory agencies of government,''
he said.
   Wright said the rules of Congress clearly authorize members to
receive royalty payments for their books, and he said his campaign
committee ``did not pay any amount for publishing the book, nor did
it purchase any copies of the book.''
   The speaker today criticized Wertheimer for not contacting him
directly about the accusations. On Wednesday, the speaker's office
released a statement accusing Common Cause of being ``the
handmaiden of a partisan political initiative.''
   Wertheimer said his request was not associated with the actions
of Wright's opponents. But Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who has led
the criticism, said Common Cause was giving ideological balance to
the criticism.
   Gingrich said in a statement Wednesday he was working with
lawyers ``to develop formal charges along the lines Common Cause
suggests.''
   The ethics committee, officially called the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, has been criticized by Gingrich and
others for apparent reluctance to investigate the speaker's
activities.
   Committee Chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., said he had no
comment on the letter.
</TEXT>
