<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WhaleHome     05-19 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whale Home,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beached Whale Arrives at New Home in Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT FISHER, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An orphaned whale that washed ashore
with its mother arrived today at its new home in Florida, where it
is expected to survive, marine experts say.
   Paul Barrington, curator of the North Carolina Aquarium here,
said the baby pygmy sperm whale showed no signs of disease or
severe injury. Daniel Odell, a marine biologist at Sea World in
Orlando, Fla., said the whale was suffering from low blood sugar
was otherwise fine.
   Sophia and a 10-foot female whale beached Tuesday afternoon at
Long Beach. The larger whale died and its corpse was sent to the
Smithsonian Institution in Washington, where a necropsy will be
performed.
   The surviving whale ate small herring and small portions of
squid at the Fort Fisher aquarium. Aquarium employees were helping
it feed by putting food up to its mouth. Staffers were trying to
keep it relaxed to allow the food to digest properly.
   A veterinarian injected the whale, which was slightly injured in
the beaching, with antibiotics and vitamins.
   Wednesday night, Raleigh television station WRAL hired an
airplane to take the whale _ named Sophia before aquarium workers
found it was male _ to Sea World near Orlando.
   The mammal arrived safely early today, said Kevin Shand, an
assignment editor at WRAL-TV. ``They're still not sure whether the
baby whale will stay at Sea World or be returned to its home in the
ocean,'' Shand said today.
</TEXT>
