<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BasketballRivalry     05-19 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Basketball Rivalry,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Basketball Game Pits Rival Housing Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Youths from rival housing projects
should be able to meet peacefully on the basketball court, say
school officials, but police aren't so sure that street warfare
won't spill over into the contest.
   The Board of Education this week unanimously approved a request
to hold a basketball match June 5 between students from Pitney
Village and the nearby Shore Park complex, both on the city's west
side.
   A school official said he believed there would be no replay of
the violence that marred a tournament last year.
   Wilbert L. Royal, coordinator for the West Side School Complex,
where the game would be held, said the game would be the ``first
attempt to try and ameliorate ... any animosity that still exists
between these two areas.''
   ``It will be a friendly rivalry rather than the combative
rivalry that a turf war brings,'' he said.
   But Atlantic City Police Chief Joseph Pasquale called the idea
``ridiculous'' and said he doubted the event would be permitted.
   ``We discourage any gathering of these two groups because they
hate each other,'' he said. ``Both areas have a lot of weapons.
Both areas dislike each other. Both areas are drug-infested and
we've got two big investigations going on in both areas.''
   Pasquale fears a repeat of the shooting and stabbings at the
Seagull Classic high school basketball tournament in nearby Absecon
in December.
   Royal said he would not dispute Pasquale if he believes the
basketball game would be a risk to safety. But he said he believed
``the sides have cooled.''
   Royal pointed to a recent incident-free rap concert at a city
complex, calling it an example of the ability of students from
different parts of the city to get along.
</TEXT>
