<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Stark 1stLd-Writethru   05-19 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Stark, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0549,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral Says Stark Tragedy Contributed to Saving Others</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 6th graf, `Less said...' to delete extraneous words.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of U.S. Navy forces in the
Persian Gulf said today that the missile attack on the USS Stark a
year ago led to improved safety techniques that helped save a
sister vessel.
   Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less said the survival of the missile
frigate Samuel B. Roberts after it hit an Iranian mine last month
was ``proof positive that others live, due to the sacrifice of the
brave men on Stark.''
   Thirty-seven sailors were killed when two errant Iraqi missiles
hit the Stark on May 17, 1987.
   Less, commander of the U.S. Joint Task Force Middle East, spoke
of the Navy's improved shipboard safety measures at a U.S. Embassy
ceremony honoring the sailors.
   Ten crewmen on the Samuel B. Roberts were injured when it
collided with a newly laid mine in the central gulf April 14. Its
skipper, Cmdr. Paul X. Rinn, has said lessons learned from the
Stark incident enabled his crew to keep their ship from sinking.
   Less said the sacrifice of the Stark's crew ``greatly assisted
the United States Navy in being smarter, more combat-ready,
especially here in this gulf, and elsewhere throughout the world.''
   Among post-Stark safety measures now in effect are procedures
under which Iraqi warplanes raiding Iranian oil tankers are warned
away from U.S. ships.
   Iran and Iraq both have attacked neutral tankers in the gulf as
part of their 7{-year-old war.
   The Iraqi government said the Stark attack was a mistake, and
the United States accepted its apology.
   Other ceremonies marking the first anniversary of the Stark
attack have been held in recent days at Arlington National Cemetery
in Arlington, Va., Mayport Naval Station in Mayport, Fla., the
frigate's home port, and aboard Navy ships in the gulf.
</TEXT>
