<HEAD>Famed Murder Convict Found Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to delete reference to Mrs. in 2nd reference to
Congdon, who never married</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LATROBE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who served time for killing his
heiress mother-in-law and her nurse in 1977 has apparently
committed suicide, authorities said.
   Roger S. Caldwell, 54, slit both wrists and bled to death on his
living room floor late Tuesday or early Wednesday, according to
Westmoreland County Deputy Coroner Joseph Musgrove.
   Caldwell was convicted in the slayings of Elisabeth Congdon of
Duluth and her night nurse, Velma Pietila, 67, in Congdon's Lake
Superior mansion on June 27, 1977.
   Musgrove said Caldwell left three suicide notes. The St. Paul
(Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch reported one note said he was
innocent of the murders.
   The newspaper also cited unidentified sources who said Caldwell
recently complained of being unable to get a job in his hometown of
Latrobe and of being haunted by notoriety from the murders.
   An agreement nearly five years ago allowed Caldwell to plead
guilty to second-degree murder and he was released on time already
served in prison.
   It came after the Minnesota Supreme Court overturned his 1978
murder conviction, released him from prison and granted him a new
trial.
   Prosecutors and police had contended the slayings were part of a
plot by Caldwell and his wife, Marjorie, to kill her adoptive
mother and collect an inheritance of about $8.2 million.
   Marjorie Caldwell was later tried and acquitted on similar
murder charges. The couple were divorced, according to Musgrove.
</TEXT>
