<1ST_LINE>r i BC-CampaignAbroad     05-19 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Newspapers Comment on Bush and Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Editorial writers abroad have begun looking ahead to a race in
November between Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael
Dukakis. Here is some of what they had to say:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Guardian of London (liberal): ``Something that has not
happened since 1964 may suddenly, unpredictably, be happening
again. Almost 24 years ago, Lyndon B. Johnson won California for
the Democrats. No Democratic candidate since has performed that
trick. ... And yet, this morning, we not only find Gov. Michael
Dukakis leading George Bush by 10 clear percentage points on
nationwide polls, the front-runner in every major area of the
United States: we also find him 17 points ahead in California.
   ``May polls, of course, may be broken reeds in November. ...
But, at the very least, Europe ought now to be sitting up and
taking urgent notice. Our leaders, and those they pay to advise
them on diplomatic developments, have until very recently ...
tended to assume that President Bush is a foregone conclusion. That
was always a little wonky. Today it looks stupid. Try President
Dukakis for size.''
  
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of London (independent): ``The American presidency
has more often than not been held by dull men, or by men who would
have been thought dull were it not for the interesting events in
which they were caught up. That is perhaps the explanation of the
`bore factor' which is affecting not just George Bush but his most
likely Democratic opponent, Michael Dukakis. This year's campaign
is taking place in times of peace and prosperity for America
unmatched in most presidential election years this century. It is
difficult for candidates to sound exciting in such times. ...
   ``Whoever wins, an envious world will eventually make sure that
America becomes _ for a while at least _ less peaceful, and perhaps
less prosperous. That is the fate of great countries which are also
democracies in a world in which most countries are neither great
nor democratic. Either candidate will soon become more exciting
than he is at present because _ sadly _ the events will become so.
America should be grateful for these two `bores' while she can.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ZIMBABWE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Herald of Harare (government-controlled): ``In comparing
Democrats and Republicans the former are more accessible and easier
to communicate with. American interests are interwoven with the
interests of others. At worst the Democrats make Third World
countries at least feel they are considered when America makes
decisions. But Republicans act in ways that fly in the face of
accepted diplomatic norms.
   ``Because of that primary consideration for American interests,
it is highly unlikely that anyone with political ideas such as
Jesse Jackson's would ever reach the White House. ...
   ``Mr. Ronald Reagan had no political program when he came in and
may not quite understand the differences between the Contras and
Unita but he went through on the `make America the greatest again'
ticket.
   ``Yet the Democrats are the lesser of the two evils. Developing
countries would certainly be better off with Michael Dukakis. If he
appointed a black to the post of secretary of state this would be
for the purpose of internal public relations and not for any
consideration of black Africa.
   ``Developing countries must accept the fact that developed
countries are only what they are because we are how we are. Any
change in our status will proportinately change theirs. It is this
that is drilled into the resident of the White House to always
remember.
   ``We too in developing countries must always remember that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
