<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0543,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fighting Rages On In Southern Beirut With Negotiations On Truce
Deadlocked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with one man killed today. Pick
up 4th graf pvs: `A police...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Iranian efforts to end a
two-week battle between rival Shiite Moslem militias remained
deadlocked today as fighting raged on in south Beirut, where
foreign hostages are believed held.
   Police said one man was killed and 10 people were wounded as the
pro-Syrian Amal militia, bottled up in Shiyah, its last stronghold
in the southern slums, traded machine gun fire with the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah.
   Today's casualties brought the overall toll to 244 killed and
772 wounded since the fighting began May 6 in the 16-square-mile
district. The man killed was a bystander who was checking on his
damaged apartment, police said.
   A police spokesman said the fighting has ``settled into
exchanges of machine-gun fire,'' as Hezbollah, or Party of God,
tightens its grip on 90 percent of south Beirut.
   The spokesman, who by regulation cannot be identified, said most
of those wounded today were civilians hit by rooftop Hezbollah
snipers.
   Syria on Sunday massed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks and armored
vehicles on the southern, western and northern edges of south
Beirut and its officers said the army was prepared to move in to
quell the fighting.
   However, there was fear that such a move might endanger foreign
hostages believed held in the slums.
   The independent Beirut daily newspaper An-Nahar said, meanwhile,
that Iran was opposed to such a deployment and wants the Syrians to
send in only a limited ``disengagement force'' to separate the
combatants.
   An-Nahar said the Iranians also want guarantees that the Syrian
force would not seek to disarm Hezbollah.
   Iran's third demand, An-Nahar reported, is that ``the issue of
releasing the hostages be separated from the objectives of the
Syrian deployment,'' the paper added without further elaboration.
   Most of the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon are believed held by
Hezbollah-affiliated zealots based in the southern slums.
   Acting Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Mohammed Besharati said on
Wednesday that the hostage issue will be ``solved'' once the
fighting ends. ``The case of kidnapping (foreigners) in Lebanon is
part of the crisis which Lebanon is passing through. I believe that
if we could end the state of war currently prevailing, then
definitely the other case would be solved too,'' he said.
   In Jerusalem today, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
Vernon Walters, said he would talk with Syrian officials in
Damascus to try to help secure the release of the nine American
hostages in Lebanon.
   The nine include the longest-held foreign hostage, Terry
Anderson, Associated Press chief Middle East correspondent. He was
seized March 16, 1985.
   Walters, who leaves Friday for the Syrian capital, would not
detail his plans. He said the trip was prompted by a concern for
the safety of the hostages because of the fighting in south Beirut.
   Meanwhile, Brig. Gen, Ghazi Kenaan, Syria's military
intelligence chief in Lebanon, said Besharati's efforts to arrange
a peaceful settlement were not succeeding.
   The two met for 90 minutes on Wednesday, after which Kenann
said: ``We are giving political efforts a chance to solve the
problem and end the bleeding in south Beirut.''
   The Iranian embassy said Besharati would meet later today with
Lebanese Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini to ``pursue his
efforts.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, is Iran's main Arab
ally in the war with Iraq. However, it recently has been alarmed by
Iran's efforts to dispute its role in Lebanon by trying to dominate
the nation's 1.2 million Shiites through Hezbollah. Lebanon has
been embroiled in civil war since 1975.
</TEXT>
