<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0442 05-19 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Edges Away From Reagan on Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs new with Fitzwater reax to Bush comments on
administration drug policy; editing thruout, no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's spokesman said today there
is ``no conflict'' resulting from Vice President George Bush's
implied criticism of administration policy on Panama.
   ``I'm saying that he has his ideas on how he's going to want to
do things, and that's fine,'' said Marlin Fitzwater. The spokesman
spoke one day after Bush's aides suggested a break with Reagan on
the question of dismissing drug-trafficking indictments against
Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Bush didn't mention Noriega's name as he touted his own drug
enforcement policies on Wednesday in Los Angeles, and he
side-stepped reporters' questions on the subject. But an aide told
a reporter, ``President Bush just wouldn't make a deal with a guy
like Noriega.''
   At his daily news briefing, Fitzwater was questioned about the
White House view of Bush's apparent move to distance himself from
some of Reagan's policies.
   ``We expect the vice president to be speaking out on how he
would do things differently and what his opinions are,'' Fitzwater
said.
   ``As we go through this campaign, I would expect to see the vice
president speaking out on a number of issues in terms of what he
would do,'' he said. ``I expect a number of them will be different
than existing policies and we will not criticize them in any way.
If you want to drive a wedge between the White House and the vice
president, forget it.''
   In his speech at the Los Angeles Police Academy Wednesday, Bush
said, ``Drug dealers are domestic terrorists, killing kids and cops
and they should be treated as such. I won't bargain with terrorists
and I won't bargain with drug dealers either, whether they are on
U.S. or foreign soil.''
   Bush didn't expand on those phrases and repeatedly refused to
comment on the Noriega situation directly.
   But in background discussions, aides said that if Bush were to
become president, he wouldn't do what Reagan is doing _ offering to
drop drug indictments if Noriega will yield his power in Panama.
   The vice president has never directly criticized the
administration's dealings with the Panamanian leader.
   Bush's latest pronouncement wrapped up a weeklong Western
campaign swing that had been dogged by Reagan administration
controversies. Those problems are sticking to Bush, he conceded
Tuesday, helping drive down his ratings versus Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   The Republican standard-bearer used this trip to New Mexico,
Oregon, California and Washington to lay out some differences _ if
not dramatic ones _ with Reagan. For example, he called Monday for
action on acid rain, where the administration has for the last
seven years called only for more study.
   The Noriega situation is a particularly sticky one for Bush, for
it hurts him on an issue _ drugs _ that aides say he wants to use
against Dukakis in the fall. Bush chief of staff Craig Fuller said
the speech is the first of a series by the vice president on drugs.
   Asked why polls show Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis is
perceived as tougher on drugs, Fuller said:
   ``The voters will get a chance to decide who will be tougher on
drugs. ... You can count on the vice president spending more time
on the problem,'' Fuller added.
   In words and actions, Bush worked Wednesday to emphasize his
commitment to fight drug abuse and his different approach from
Reagan's.
   The vice president began the day with a private meeting with Los
Angeles police chief Daryl Gates and then visited a storefront,
raided by police earlier this month, where the potent cocaine
derivative crack was sold and used.
   Asked about the practical value of his visit to the onetime
crack den, Bush bristled a bit.
   ``It's not show business,'' he said. ``Anybody who has practical
experience, you learn more from them. You try to learn and
understand and then take action...It's been extraordinarily
helpful.''
   Bush praised the Reagan efforts to curb drug abuse, but said he
would do things differently. For one, he said he would make his
vice president more than just the head of a task force on drug
interdiction.
   ``If I'm elected, I will put my vice president in charge of
every aspect of federal drug policy,'' Bush announced. ``I will ask
the vice president to head a Cabinet-level council of war to pull
the effort together ... to make sure it's carried out.''
   He repeated his call for the death penalty for drug kingpins.
   ``I'll demand stronger penalities for drug offenders. Mike
Dukakis and Jesse Jackson criticize our anti-drug effort _ I
readily concede there's room for improvement _ but I want them to
join me on these tougher penalities. This isn't Democrat or
Republican,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
