<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HomeEquityLoans     05-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Equity Loans,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Would Require Better Information on Home Equity Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee voted unanimously
today to require banks and credit unions to provide more timely and
complete information on home equity loans, or second mortgages.
   Under the bill, passed by voice vote, lenders would have to
disclose prior to making a loan the annual interest percentage
rate, any fees associated with the loan, a series of warnings about
the risks involved and a description of repayment options.
   Rep. Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., chairman of the committee's
consumer affairs subcommittee, said, ``This legislation will
provide consumers with important information regarding home equity
lines of credit.
   ``It will enable those consumers to understand fully the
conditions of this new form of consumer borrowing,'' said Annunzio.
``It will make clear to them that they risk the loss of their home
in the event of default.''
   The American Bankers Association, in a statement handed out in
the committee room after the bill was approved, said: ``In recent
months we have worked with legislators to ensure that the bill
preserves the product by providing for creditors' remedies in
deteriorating loan situations.
   ``However, the disclosure and advertising provisions are
impractical. They will result in an unnecessary overload of
information for consumers, and they will severely limit the
creditors' ability to design informative advertisements,'' the ABA
said.
   The biggest difference in the measure approved today and the one
which came out of the Annunzio subcommittee in February was a
provision barring lenders from unilaterally changing terms of the
loans, except in some instances.
   ``Traditionally, in open-end accounts, a lender has reserved the
right to change the terms of the loan,'' said Rep. David E. Price,
D-N.C., chief sponsor. ``However, this provision causes special
problems in the home equity area. The high initial fees, the fact
that the home is at risk, and the large lines of credit involved,
make this unilateral right to change the terms of the loan
undesirable in the home equity area.''
   A home equity loan disclosure bill has passed the Senate as part
of a bigger bank restructuring bill now being considered by the
House Banking Committee. A committee staffer said proponents wanted
a separate bill to pass the House and be sent to the Senate in case
the bank restructuring measure is not approved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
