<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru a0475 05-19 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Troubling Signs, Some Big Investors Leaving Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New third graf with prices weak again today; Version moved on
the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's underlying dread of another stock
crash has been aggravated by two significant events, an upward
spike in interest rates and the first notable selling by big
institutional investors in several weeks.
   Unresponsive to good news and obsessed with the bad, the stock
market took another sharp spill Wednesday, depressing the Dow Jones
industrial average to its lowest point in more than three months.
Broader market indexes also fell sharply.
   Prices weakened further this morning. The Dow average was down
24.86 points to 1,926.23 by 11 a.m. EDT on Wall Street, and losing
stocks outnumbered gainers by nearly 5-to-1 on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   The declines themselves were not particularly new or alarming,
because prices have been bouncing up and down for a while in a
post-crash market dominated largely by brokers buying and selling
to each other.
   What concerned investment professionals this time was an influx
of sell orders from large institutional investors such as pension
funds and mutual funds, the flesh and bones of the stockholding
public. The selling suggested that these crucial investors are
growing exasperated.
   ``Today's the first day I've seen some real institutional
liquidations,'' William King, head trader at Nikko Securities Co.
International in New York, said as the selling intensified late
Wednesday. ``You're getting some acknowledgement from institutional
investors that there's a problem.''
   Institutional selling partly was responsible for inflating the
volume on the New York Stock Exchange, where 209.42 million shares
were traded. It was the first time the volume exceeded 200 million
shares in more than a month.
   To the technical strategists who attempt to plot the stock
market's course based on mathematical formulas and past behavior,
the price drop signaled some serious concern as well.
   The Dow industrials fell 35.32 points to 1,951.09 on Wednesday,
the lowest since Feb. 9, when it closed at 1,914.46. At one point,
the average fell through 1,950, which strategists have called an
important ``support level.''
   In addition, a drop in the Dow transportation average, which
often precedes declines in the industrial average, suggested prices
would keep falling.
   More disturbing to some strategists was the lack of support
levels on their technical charts, based on the market's movements
since it plunged 508 points on Black Monday, Oct. 19, to 1,738.74.
Between that level and the Dow average's position now, there have
been only two stable points, 1,930 and 1,860.
   Stock strategists who look at economics to predict the market's
behavior said rising concern about inflation and interest rates was
a key reason for Wednesday's big selloff.
   They were particularly alarmed by the bond market, where prices
tumbled and yields on the 30-year Treasury bond flirted with 9.3
percent, the highest point since the crash. This has made bonds
increasingly attractive as an alternative investment to stocks.
   ``When the bond market started falling apart, we saw quite
substantial blocks of institutional selling in the stock market,''
said Jack Barbanel, a trading strategist at the New York investment
firm Gruntal & Co.
   ``It's certainly bearish for the stock market, because
institutions get out of the stock market when they can get
risk-control yields elsewhere _ the bond market,'' he said.
   ``Why take risks in a stock market that in the past three or
four months has been volatile, with not much volume to support it?
The flight to quality bonds and risk-controlled investments is
going to be the thing to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings-Impeach 1stLd-Writethru a0438 05-19 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings-Impeach, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0438,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 6 grafs new with Doar testimony; picks up pvs 3rd graf
pvs, It was.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal judge Alcee L. Hastings gave false
trial testimony about draft letters and telephone calls in an
attempt to hide his involvement in a bribery scheme, a House
impeachment panel was told today.
   New York lawyer John Doar summarized the evidence used by a
special judicial panel in concluding that Hastings, who was
acquitted of bribery conspiracy charges in 1983, had actually
committed the crime and tried to conceal his part in the scheme.
   Hastings sat silently with his lawyers in the hearing room as
the House Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice heard Doar
outline the judicial panel's case for impeaching the Miami judge.
   Doar said Hastings gave ``knowingly false'' trial testimony
about phone calls and draft letters purportedly made in behalf of
an old friend, Hemphill Pride, who was seeking reinstatement as a
lawyer after serving a prison sentence in connection with
misappropriation of housing funds.
   But Doar said the judicial panel's investigation concluded that
the letters cited by Hastings were intended ``to conceal his
participation in the bribery scheme through false evidence.'' He
said Hastings' testimony about the phone calls also was ``knowingly
false'' and intended to mislead the jury.
   It was the second day of testimony by Doar, a former assistant
U.S. attorney general for civil rights in the mid-1960s and special
counsel to the House Judiciary Committee in its move to impeach
President Nixon in the Watergate scandal a decade later.
   The deliberate, soft-spoken Doar was selected by a special,
five-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta to lead its exhaustive, 3{-year investigation of Hastings'
judicial conduct.
   Hastings was acquitted in 1983 of conspiring to solicit a
$150,000 bribe from two convicted racketeers.
   But the judicial panel said it had found ``clear and convincing
evidence'' that Hastings conspired with Washington lawyer William
A. Borders to solicit the bribe in exchange for a promise of
lenient sentences.
   The panel also accused Hastings of trying to conceal the ``sale
of justice'' by lying under oath and fabricating evidence at his
highly publicized trial in Miami five years ago.
   Hastings, who was nominated to life tenure on the federal bench
by President Carter in 1979, has consistently denied any wrongdoing.
   ``They found me not guilty of crimes I never committed,'' he
said Wednesday at the start of impeachment hearings by the House
Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice.
   ``I am not guilty, but I am not free,'' said Hastings, the first
black federal judge in Florida. His voice rising, he declared:
   ``I ask you in the name of decency, in the name of justice, in
the name of the American jury system ... I ask you in the name of
the American way of life, I beg you, I beseech you, I implore you _
hell no, I tell you and I demand of you that you set me free!''
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., the subcommittee chairman,
expressed concern that the case against Hastings might be racially
and politically motivated _ as Hastings has charged in the past.
But Rep. George Gekas of Pennsylvania, the ranking Republican on
the panel, said Hastings' race played no part whatsoever in the
impeachment inquiry.
   Following Hastings to the witness table, Doar reviewed the
massive evidence used by the appeals court judges in their 381-page
report charging Hastings with impeachable misconduct.
   The report was endorsed unanimously by the Judicial Conference
of the United States, the chief policymaking body of the federal
judiciary, which told House leaders that ``consideration of
impeachment may be warranted.''
   Doar and subcommittee members listened to a series of secretly
taped conversations and telephone calls in late 1981 between Boders
and an FBI undercover agent posing as racketeer Frank Romano.
   Borders was convicted at a separate trial in 1982 on charges of
arranging the alleged bribe payment to Hastings from Romano and his
brother, Thomas.
   If the subcommittee recommends impeachment and the full
Judiciary Committee concurs, the House must vote whether to impeach
Hastings. If impeached, he would face a Senate trial on the
charges. A two-thirds Senate majority would be required to convict
Hastings and remove him from office.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., whose district includes Miami,
entered the hearing room late Wednesday, shook hands with Hastings
and took a front-row seat to listen to Doar's testimony for about a
half-hour.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
