<HEAD>School Bus Used for Armed Robbery Suspect's Getaway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After holding up a place where they
peddle petals, an armed robber put the pedal to the metal in his
getaway vehicle: a 65-passenger school bus.
   An hour after Wednesday's caper, a 32-year-old bus driver was
arrested as he waited to pick up kindergartners at a Minneapolis
school about 11:30 a.m.
   Police said the man robbed a St. Paul flower shop at knifepoint
on his break between school routes and escaped in the bus belonging
to Ryder Student Transportation Services.
   Witnesses outside the flower shop saw a man leave, according to
police.
   An alert Ryder dispatcher identified the suspect from the
descriptions of the man and told officials to hold the children in
school until an arrest was made, said Gary Rogers, transportation
director for the Minneapolis schools.
   The driver was being held in the Ramsey County jail on suspicion
of armed robbery, police said. He will be suspended from his job,
said Bruce Dischinger, Ryder operations manager.
