<HEAD>Pro-Beijing Newspaper Publisher Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fei Yi-ming, the publisher of the influential
pro-Beijing Ta Kung Pao newspaper, died Wednesday of a heart
ailment. He was 80.
   Among the posts he held in the Chinese government was
vice-director of the Basic Law Drafting Committee that is writing a
constitution for Hong Kong that will be used after the colony
reverts to China in 1997. He also was vice-director of the Law
Committee of the National Peoples' Congress, China's parliament.
   Since Fei was hospitalized last year, many Chinese leaders,
including President Yang Shangkun and former National Peoples'
Congress leader Peng Zhen, sent envoys to visit him.
   Fei was born in the Chinese city of Suzhou, Zhejiang province,
and was educated in Beijing. He joined the newspaper in Tianjin
when he was 22 and helped it get started in Hong Kong eight years
later.

