<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Afghanistan,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Sees Indications Sovieties Will Turn Over Equipment to
Afghans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A State Department official said today there
are indications the Soviets will turn over facilities and equipment
worth up to $1 billion to the Afghan government after Red Army
troops depart Afghanistan.
   Michael Armacost, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
told reporters ``there have been indications that we have picked
up'' that the Soviets intend to leave behind equipment and
installations, ``perhaps a half billion or billion dollars worth.''
   ``That doesn't strike me as a demonstration of tremendous
restraint,'' Armacost said, reiterating a U.S. policy that calls
for continued supply of American aid to the Afghan resistance
forces as long as the Soviets continue giving aid to the Afghan
government.
   ``We will have practical ways of accomplishing that purpose,''
Armacost said of U.S. deliveries.
   When the United States and the Soviet Union signed an agreement
setting the stage for the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000
Soviet troops, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
rejected a U.S. proposal that both superpowers stop aiding their
clients in Afghanistan.
   U.S. officials said, however, they still hoped the Soviets would
change their minds as the withdrawal proceeded. It began several
days ago and the first brigade of forces reached Soviet territory
on Wednesday.
   Armacost's comments indicated those hopes may have been dashed,
at least according to the current indications.
   He noted that there have been reports of fighting between Soviet
forces and the U.S.-backed mujahadeen.
   Asked if the United States expected the Soviets to ask U.S.
officials to urge restraint on the part of the resistance, to
facilitate the withdrawal, Armacost said, ``the position we've
taken on that has been generally, a prompt timetable is one that is
more likely to elicit cooperation from the mujahadeen.
   He advised the Soviets to make ``some kind of local
arrangements'' with resistance leaders, through direct talks, to
secure protection for the withdrawing Soviet troops.
   He said he had heard rumors of such arrangements in some areas.
</TEXT>
