<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Pendergrass,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Aids Handicapped Singer-Musician Teddy Pendergrass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-musician Teddy Pendergrass, paralyzed
in an auto crash six years ago, said Thursday he is competitive at
the top level of the music industry thanks to a versatile computer.
   ``I have come to realize that music and technology suddenly got
married,'' Pendergrass told the Senate subcommittee on the
handicapped.
   Pendergrass said his MIDI _ musical instrument digital interface
_ permits him to compose, arrange, create sounds and ``play
literally every instrument that would be included in a 100-piece
orchestra.''
   ``That allows me to compete at the highest level. It erases the
handicap,'' he said.
   The Philadelphia singer-composer, who uses an automatic
wheelchair and has limited use of his hands, was among the
witnesses at a hearing on assistive technology for the disabled.
The panel was urged to make such technology more accessible to
those who need it.
   By bringing his computer software to the studio, Pendergrass
said, he can complete a record in one-third of the studio time it
once took.
   He called the cost of the computer equipment ``fairly
reasonable. We're not re-creating the wheel. The technology was
already on the shelf. All we did was adapt it for my needs.
   ``The technology exists at every level for everything,''
Pendergrass added. ``All we need to do is adapt it ... and
(handicapped) people could continue in any industry at all levels.''
</TEXT>
