<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene     05-19 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene,0829</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Job Outlook Bright for Most Graduates with Agricultural Degrees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of new college graduates with
agricultural degrees is down again this year, but Agriculture
Department officials say their job outlook is the brightest in a
decade.
   One official warned Wednesday that the graduates are declining
in number and that this could spell problems in critical food and
agricultural specialities in the future.
   ``The demand comes in part from recent advances in agricultural
science and technology, and from the need of U.S. agribusiness to
improve its position in international marketing,'' said J. Patrick
Jordan, administrator of the department's Cooperative State
Research Service.
   Despite the good news of greater job demand and record-high
starting salaries, Jordan and college officials said the nation's
supply of graduates in agriculture majors continues to decline.
   This year, for example, Iowa State University graduated about
500 agriculture majors, down 35 to 40 from 1987, and Purdue
University graduated 225, down from 301 a year ago.
   But salaries are looking up. At Iowa State, starting salaries of
graduates with bachelor's degrees in agriculture are averaging just
over $20,000 a year. The University of Georgia estimates starting
salaries near $19,000 for those with bachelor's degrees, $24,000
for those with master's, and $34,000 to start for holders of
doctoral degrees.
   The University of California, Davis, reported situation is
bright for all food science graduates, who will attract starting
offers averaging $22,000 to $36,000.
   At Texas A&M, agriculture graduates will average $17,000 to
$26,000 to start. Cornell University says its graduates with
bachelor of science degrees will see salary offers running 4
percent to 6 percent above last year's average of $20,406.
   Campus recruitment also has perked up, with many businesses
finding a shortage of new graduates to fill current openings.
   The hottest spots in the job picture, according to college
officials, include food science, poultry production, agricultural
education, agricultural chemistry and engineering, dairy science,
agricultural journalism, entomology, landscape architecture and
ornamental horticulture.
   Jordan said a USDA panel forecasts a ``continuing national
shortage'' of 4,000 agriculture and life sciences graduates
annually through 1990. Some experts predict the shortage will
continue beyond that date and that it will become more significant
as good starting salaries and career opportunities draw off
bachelor of science graduates who otherwise might obtain master's
or doctoral degrees.
   ``To a degree, the laws of supply and demand will no doubt enter
into play here, so that more college students, seeing that the
agricultural professions offer good career opportunities, will
choose an agricultural major,'' Jordan said.
   But he added that if college-bound young people fail to see the
opportunities in agriculture, then ``the nation may soon face a
critical shortage of expertise in the food and agricultural
sciences and professions.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers will get a smaller share of what
consumers spend on food this year, according to a new Agriculture
Department report.
   The food marketing bill, or the difference between consumer
expenditures and the farm value of domestically produced food, is
expected to increase 6.6 percent in 1988, compared with a 4.7
percent gain last year.
   Food marketing includes the costs of transporting, processing,
packaging and merchandising food after it leaves the farm.
   ``While food expenditures will rise 4.8 percent _ about the same
as the pace last year _ the farm value of food is expected to
decline 1 percent, because of bigger supplies and lower prices for
livestock and poultry products,'' the department's Economic
Research Service said Wednesday.
   During the first quarter, consumer food costs rose 3.1 percent
above a year earlier, with much of the increase due to higher
prices for fruit, vegetables and fish.
   Prices for food served in restaurants and fast-food outlets
``rose a little faster than prices for food at home,'' the report
said. For all of 1988, food prices are forecast to rise 2 percent
to 4 percent from 1987 when they increased 4.1 percent.
   The report continued to forecast 1988 net cash income of farmers
at $50 billion to $55 billion, down from last year's record of $57
billion. Rising production costs and lower federal payments to
farmers are factors in this year's decline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World sugar production in 1988-89 is expected
to be a record of about 103.9 million metric tons, slightly more
than the 103.8 million tons produced in 1987-88, says the
Agriculture Department.
   The latest figures announced Wednesday included revisions from
the department's first forecast issued on May 4, which indicated
production at 104.1 million metric tons in 1988-89 and last year's
output at 103.6 million tons.
   Production in Brazil _ the largest producer _ was reduced to a
1988-89 forecast of 8.1 million tons from 8.4 million tons
indicated earlier this month, the report said. Revisions also were
reported for several other countries.
</TEXT>
