<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0563 05-19 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0563,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Mourns As Funerals Begin Today For Bus Crash Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with start of funerals,
additional victim being buried today, picking up 4th graf pvs, ``If
it ....' </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state observed an official day of
mourning today as grief-stricken friends and families gathered to
bid farewell to six victims of one of the nation's worst bus
crashes.
   The Rev. Leo Craycroft told mourners at St. Christopher Church
that there were ``no real satisfying answers'' for the deaths of
his three teen-age parishioners and other victims of Saturday
night's accident, which claimed 27 lives.
   ``The saying is trite but painfully true: They had their whole
lives before them,'' the priest said at the funeral Mass for Mary
Cathryn Daniels, 14; Denise Ellen Voglund, 13; and Amy Christine
Wheelock, 14.
   They were to be buried at the same Radcliff cemetery where
12-year-old Julie Ann Earnest was laid to rest today in a brief
graveside ceremony.
   All four girls were students at Radcliff Middle School. A fifth
middle school pupil, 14-year-old Tina Michelle Mustain, was to be
buried later today in Tyler, Texas.
   Joshua Conyers, 14, of nearby Vine Grove, a ninth-grader at
North Hardin High School, was to be buried today at the same
Radcliff cemetery as the others, which abuts his high school.
   Flags across Kentucky flew at half-staff to honor the memory of
the 24 children and three adults killed when their bus was struck
head-on by a pickup truck heading in the wrong direction on
Interstate 71.
   ``If it were possible to turn back the clock, we would,'' Gov.
Wallace Wilkinson said Wednesday in declaring today's official day
of mourning. ``Whatever consolation we can give will never make up
for the loss of friends and loved ones.''
   A memorial service for all 27 victims was planned for tonight at
North Hardin High School in Radcliff. Most of the other funerals
were scheduled for Friday.
   Although fatal bus crashes also occurred this week in Cleveland
and New York state, a deputy administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration said today that school buses are
remarkably safe.
   Jeff Miller, on CBS' ``This Morning,'' said that the Saturday
crash ``was no accident. This was a crash and this was caused by a
drunk driver.''
   ``Out of 46,000 fatalities on our highways every year, less than
100 even involve school buses,'' Miller said. ``It's the safest
form of transportation. We've got 350,000 school buses on our
highways, they transport 21 million kids to school every day and
they've done an extraordinarly good job.''
   The Kentucky crash involved a converted school bus carrying
members of a church group from an amusement park near Cincinnati.
Most of the victims were military dependents or had ties to nearby
Fort Knox. The service at the high school's 2,400-seat football
stadium will include hymns and a performance by the post military
band, said Lelia S. Haddle, secretary to Mayor Joseph Hutcherson.
   ``Right now, Fort Knox is kind of our mainstay,'' she said.
``They are being very involved because there are a lot of military
families in this.''
   The fort has also sent chaplains and counselors to help families.
   On Wednesday, grief counselors from the National Organization
for Victim Assistance conducted a seminar in Radcliff for school
counselors, military personnel and others dealing with victims'
families.
   Also, the National Transportation Safety Board said it located a
witness to the crash, and someone who saw what is believed to be
the pickup truck cross the grassy median and head north in the
southbound lanes.
   The truck driver, Larry Mahoney, still hospitalized in
Louisville about 35 miles southwest of Radcliff, was charged with
27 counts of murder, one for each of those who died in the
accident. Authorities said he was intoxicated at the time of the
crash. Thirteen other people remained hospitalized Wednesday.
   In Cleveland, four people remained hospitalized Wednesday from a
public transit bus accident that killed a teen-age passenger.
Police were checking reports that the bus accelerated after
striking a car.
   Tuesday's accident started when a motorist tried to make a left
turn in front of the bus. The bus struck the car and then lurched
out of control, striking a tree, a pole and a fence before grazing
a building and another pole, said Patrolman Emil Cielec.
   In Clinton Corners, N.Y., an NTSB inspection found no structural
or mechanical problems with a bus that overturned Monday, killing
three people and injuring 20 others, authorities said Wednesday.
   However, mechanical failure has not been ruled out as the cause
of the accident, said state police Sgt. Dennis Cody. The driver of
the bus remained hospitalized and was unable to talk to
investigators Wednesday, Cody said.
</TEXT>
