<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SnowCones-Bacteria     05-19 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Snow Cones-Bacteria,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Get Sick, Officials Suspect Snow Cones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 15 children became sick with an
intestinal bacteria, and health officials suspect tainted snow
cones.
   The children, ages 15 months to 12 years, were infected with the
bacteria shigella and have symptoms of vomiting, diarrhea,
abdominal cramps and fever, said Dr. Mary Duffy, Knox County health
director.
   The illnesses began May 9, she said.
   After talking with the children, health officials figured the
culprit could be snow cones from delivery trucks that circle
Knoxville neighborhoods.
   But Health Department personnel have been unable to find the
trucks. Duffy said no snow cone vendors have obtained the necessary
permit to sell the cones.
   ``These are usually kitchen operations, and they sell the ice
and sell the syrup to other people who in turn peddle it around,''
she said.
</TEXT>
