<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0451 05-19 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,970</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Dukakis, Fitzwater comments; move up
Bush grafs 14-17 pvs bgng ``Bush, who...; pick up 5th graf pvs bgng
``Jackson campaigning...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis today criticized the Reagan
administration for proposing another in-depth look at the nation's
drug problem, saying ``We don't need another study.'' George Bush's
statement that he wouldn't bargain with drug dealers prompted a
White House spokesman to say ``he has his ideas on how he's going
... to do things and that's fine.''
   Dukakis made a final appearance in New Jersey before heading off
to California, both states part of the June 7 primary season
finale. California's will be the biggest primary of the season,
offering 314 Democratic delegates, with 109 at stake in New Jersey.
   In Camden, N.J., Dukakis spoke with community leaders in a
neighborhood marred by drug use and violence. Asked about President
Reagan's announcement Wednesday of a new bipartisan study on drugs,
he said, ``I don't think we need another study.''
   ``There is no Democratic or Republican or independent way to
fight this,'' the Massachusetts governor said.
   Bush wrapped up a seven-day West Coast campaign swing on
Wednesday and made an anti-drug message his central theme.
   Campaigning in Los Angeles, he said that as president, he
wouldn't ``bargain with drug dealers ... whether they are on U.S.
or foreign soil.''
   Although he repeatedly refused to state his views directly on
the administration's attempts to cut a deal with Panamanian leader
Manuel Noriega, who is under indictment on drug charges, his aides
said on background that the message was, ``President Bush just
wouldn't make a deal with a guy like Noriega.''
   At the White House today, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater was drawn
into a debate with reporters over Bush's edging away from Reagan
administration policy.
   ``I'm saying that he has his ideas on how he's going to want to
do things, and that's fine,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``If you want to drive a wedge between the White House and the
vice president, forget it.''
   Dukakis' only remaining rival, Jesse Jackson, suggested that
racist comments by ``irresponsible public leaders'' helped create
the climate for an alleged assassination plot against him.
   Jackson, campaigning in Fresno, Calif., was asked about this
week's arrest of a St. Louis couple accused of plotting to kill
him. Londell Williams and his wife, Tammy, were also charged with
threatening an informant and possessing an automatic rifle.
   Papers filed in federal court indicated Londell Williams told an
informer he was a member of The Order and other white supremacist
groups, and that Jackson should be killed.
   But lawyers for the couple said each denied belonging to a white
supremacist group, and the FBI said no evidence had been found that
the pair belonged to The Order.
   Jackson initially downplayed word of the arrests, saying, ``I
cannot just focus on the two people arrested in St. Louis.''
   But later he told reporters: ``The climate for this kind of
antagonism and violence, of course, has been set by many
irresponsible public leaders (whose) attacks based on race have set
a divisive and dangerous climate, such as the one ... in New York
in April, for example.''
   Jackson was apparently referring to comments by New York City
Mayor Ed Koch during the New York primary campaign last month. Koch
said, among other things, that Jews would be ``crazy'' to vote for
Jackson.
   Jackson met privately Wednesday with nearly three dozen rabbis
and Jewish leaders in Los Angeles, in what he described as a ``step
toward healing the wounds.'' Many Jews were offended by Jackson's
1984 reference to New York as ``Hymietown'' and his association
with Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan.
   A dozen demonstrators outside the Hollywood hotel where the
session was being held chanted ``Lose, Jesse, lose'' and ``Jew
hater.''
   Jackson was campaigning in California again today.
   In Los Angeles, the vice president stopped in at a storefront,
raided by police earlier this month, where the potent cocaine
derivative crack had been sold and used. Later, he visited the Los
Angeles Police Academy and said he would convene a Cabinet-level
``council of war'' against illegal drugs.
   ``Together we can coordinate an attack on the drug trade that
will be nothing less than a modern D-day,'' said Bush.
   The delegate race is over on the Republican side _ Bush
mathematically clinched the nomination last month in the
Pennsylvania primary.
   On the Democratic side, Dukakis has dramatically widened his
delegate lead in recent weeks. By the latest AP count, he has 1,643
to Jackson's 974.
   Jackson's campaign has written to Democratic Party chairman Paul
Kirk, complaining that under the delegate-selection process ``the
vote of the people is distorted.''
   Jackson has long maintained that the support of so-called
``super delegates'' _ party and elective officials who have a vote
at the convention _ should be roughly in line with the popular
vote. But under party rules, the super delegates are not bound to
follow primary results in their states.
   The letter to Kirk, signed by Jackson's campaign chief Willie
Brown and Jackson adviser Walter Fauntroy, the District of
Columbia's delegate to Congress, urged the party chairman to
consider the ``moral and political questions'' raised by the rules.
   A copy of the letter, dated Tuesday, was sent to the Dukakis
camp.
   Dukakis, however, said he did not believe Jackson would mount a
challenge to delegates at the Democratic convention.
   ``I don't think we are going to have a fight with Mr. Jackson,''
he said.
   The Massachusetts governor, who added a primary win in Oregon to
his column this week, was in New Jersey on Wednesday, where he met
with local Democratic leaders, then mingled with patrons and served
up beers at a restaurant in the waterfront city of Hoboken.
</TEXT>
