<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WarPowers Bjt   05-19 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-War Powers, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Proposal Would Modify Vietnam-Era Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The War Powers Act, a Vietnam-era law that has
been the focus of a long-running fight between the White House and
Congress, would be overhauled by a proposal introduced Thursday in
the Senate.
   ``Our goal is to make the statute more workable,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., a sponsor of the reform
measure.
   Commenting about the existing act, Byrd said, ``Frankly, if I
were president, I would thumb my nose at this legislation. The War
Powers Act has never really worked.''
   The law was enacted in 1973, over the veto of President Nixon,
who argued that it was an unconstitutional restriction on his
authority. That is the same position taken by all three subsequent
presidents.
   The law requires a report from the president when U.S. military
personnel are sent to situations of ``imminent hostilities.'' Under
some circumstances, those troops must be withdrawn after 60 days or
90 days, unless Congress specifically votes to authorize them to
remain.
   The new proposal would let the troops remain for an unspecified
length of time unless Congress votes to remove them. It also
creates a group of 18 senior congressional leaders who would
regularly meet with the president to discuss national security
matters.
   ``Presidents have not consulted adequately with Congress prior
to making decisions to involve the nation in a situation where
hostilities are certain, imminent or probable,'' said Byrd, arguing
that the new 18-member group would change that.
   The congressional leadership group could trigger the war powers
law by introducing a resolution to either authorize the troops to
remain or to order them withdrawn.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, said he believes the change is a good idea
because the current law ``has never worked very well.''
   Warner said he doesn't know whether President Reagan will back
the change.
   ``It will be up to the administration to look at this and see if
they can support it,'' said Warner, explaining that administration
approval was not sought by the group of legislators who drafted the
plan.
   Byrd said, ``I would hope the administration won't veto this.''
He said action is likely later this year by Congress.
   Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, said that ``the War Powers Act is
a good example of the limited ability of human beings to predict
future events.''
   ``It was written for the Vietnam war,'' said Mitchell, and has
been difficult to apply to current situation of small, brief
military clashes or terrorist situations.
   The most recent dispute over the War Powers Act involves
Reagan's Persian Gulf policy of reflagging 11 Kuwaiti-owned tankers
and protecting them with Navy warships. Navy vessels have also been
authorized to aid neutral merchant vesels which seek help.
   Reagan has refused to invoke the law, even though there have
been four separate clashes between the Navy and Iran. Congress has
debated trying to invoke the law, but has been unable to agree on
whether that should be done.
   Last year, 115 legislators went to federal court and filed suit,
seeking an order directing Reagan to invoke the law. But the suit
was thrown out of court and the legislators are now appealing that
ruling.
   Mitchell said the law was ``well intentioned, but it has not
worked. We have spent countless hours proposing, filibustering, and
debating measures to invoke a law _ rather than assessing the
wisdom of the policy that prompted the deployment of forces.''
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
said, ``there's an old saying that if something isn't broke, don't
fix it. Well, the War Powers Act is broken and it should be fixed.''
   Nunn said the law ``encourages confrontation rather than
consultation between the presidents and Congress. When forces are
introduced, the debate in the Congress is frequently on procedure
rather than policy.''
   Warner said many of the problems in the current law arise
because ``every president resents a diminuation in his power.''
   The law was approved in November 1973 despite the veto by Nixon.
The House voted 284-135 to override Nixon's veto while the Senate
vote was 75-18.
   Backers of the law argued that it was needed because Nixon's
Vietnam policies were usurping the congressional right to declare
war.
   Since the law was enacted, presidents have formally submitted
reports on a dozen occasions, although they have rarely cited the
section of the law which triggers the 60-day time period for a
congressional vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
