<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhonyDentist     05-19 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phony Dentist,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Officials Strip License from Dentist Who Never Went to
School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Cura was, by many accounts, a
gentle dentist.
   But he gave up his license three weeks ago, when officials
learned he never went to dental school.
   Cura, 46, was trained in the Army as a dental technician and
easily passed Florida's dental exam seven years ago, his lawyer,
Harold M. Braxton, said.
   He treated more than 3,500 patients.
   ``He learned a lot of techniques in the Army,'' Braxton said.
``He just watched, observed and started reading a lot of books.''
   Doctors praised him as highly competent, and patients said he
was generous and had a knack for putting them at ease and getting
rid of pain.
   State licensing officials alleged that Cura forged transcripts
indicating he had attended the University of Havana 1958-63 and had
received a doctor's degree in dental surgery. They said Cura
actually was a high school student in New Jersey from 1958-60.
   ``We were absolutely thunderstruck and flabbergasted,'' said
Robert T. Ferris, an Altamonte Springs dentist who chairs the state
Board of Dentistry.
   Cura told state officials he plans to go dental school, but the
board last month rejected his request for a license suspension
until he graduated. State officials said Wednesday no decision has
been made on criminal charges.
   Bill O'Neil, general counsel for the Department of Professional
Reguation, said he wished Cura would go to dental school because he
did a good job.
   Cura's undoing was person who wrote anonymously to the
department, saying that on a visit to Cura's office, he noticed no
degrees on the walls and began to investigate.
   ``I am asking you for all the innocent people that put their
lives in his hands on a daily basis and trust him wth surgery
without even imagining that he has never had university studies and
does not know what he is doing,'' the letter said.
   Cura couldn't be reached, but Braxton said he was contrite.
   ``I'd say remorseful is a very good word,'' the lawyer said.
``He comitted a wrong, there's no question about it.''
</TEXT>
