<DOCNO> AP880519-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush'sDance Bjt   05-19 0842</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush's Dance, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Must Define Himself Without Undermining Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a painfully slow ballet, George Bush is
delicately stepping away from Ronald Reagan.
   Each step is carefully choreographed as the cautious Republican
vice president tries to define what he would do as president _
without undermining or angering the president.
   The Republican nominee-to-be cannot win without convincing
Americans he is his own man. But he cannot break with Reagan
dramatically, for that would shatter Bush's hold on the
conservative foundation of his bid for the White House.
   And Bush does want to be identified with low unemployment,
continuing prosperity and a declining trade deficit _ all current
conditions the Reagan administration brags about.
   But he is falling in the polls against Democratic front-runner
Michael Dukakis, in part because he has failed thus far to paint
for the voters a vivid picture of what he would do as president.
   As New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean said Thursday, ``Ronald Reagan is a
very popular man, but nobody wants a clone.''
   The White House appeared to ease the way for Bush when spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said, ``He has his ideas on how he's going to want
to do things, and that's fine.''
   A weeklong trip through the West demonstrated graphically the
easy and the hard choices Bush must make in the next six months to
try to put together a winning coalition in the fall.
   In the Pacific Northwest, Bush hit hard on protecting the
environment, proclaiming that the government must do more.
   He didn't directly criticize the environmental record of the
administration, but he did break cleanly with Reagan on one issue
Monday. Bush said he would act to stop the sources of acid rain,
while the administration just wants to study the problem more.
   This was an easy one for Bush, for the environment is close to a
motherhood issue. No one is against clean air and clean water, even
though there are disagreements on how to achieve those goals.
   And acid rain is not a burning issue for Reagan, nor is it one
that is central to the basic GOP constituencies.
   The hard choices for Bush come in packages like the
administration's dealings with Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega.
   The Reagan Justice Department indicted Noriega for involvement
in drug-running, but the White House is thinking of dropping the
indictments if Noriega will give up power.
   Bush's first reaction was to say that talking about sensitive
matters is a mistake. Of course, the White House was talking _
albeit carefully _ about the negotiations.
   Next the vice president said he wanted Noriega out of Panama,
leaving the impression perhaps, that a deal dropping the charges
was all right.
   Then, Bush tried yet another formulation with yet a different
emphasis. He said Friday in San Diego, he wanted Noriega ``brought
to justice.''
   That meant he was against dropping the indictment, right? Bush
wouldn't say and neither would aides. It was a precisely vague
phrase, for bringing someone into court is only one meaning of
``justice.''
   This careful wording didn't draw the attention Bush wanted and
thus didn't deal with the problem.
   At every stop, reporters shouted questions to the GOP
heir-apparent on Noriega. Bush would smile and just say nothing.
   Wednesday brought yet another effort.
   ``Drug dealers are domestic terrorists, killing kids and cops
and they should be treated as such,'' Bush said at the Los Angeles
Police Academy. ``I won't bargain with terrorists and I won't
bargain with drug dealers either, whether they are on U.S. or
foreign soil.''
   He didn't say Noriega. And aides were quick to say he was not
talking about the current situation, only what he would do in the
future.
   Now there was no doubt that Bush wanted to leave the impression
that he simply would not cut a plea-bargaining deal with Noriega.
To say it clearly would have been critical of Reagan and a step
into the middle of a mess Bush would like to avoid as much as
possible.
   So Bush tried to say it without saying it.
   But the problem is a simple one _ it does not answer the basic
question: What does Bush think of the proposed deal?
   So the questions will continue, as long as Noriega is on the
front pages.
   Likewise with the scandals swirling around Attorney General
Edwin Meese _ Bush has refused to comment and so he faces
questioning almost every day on whether or not he thinks Meese
should resign.
   Bush aides will talk privately about the need for the vice
president to step away from Reagan, but Bush himself is the one
arguing the time is not yet ripe for clear and definitive moves.
   The problem for Bush, as an aide once said, is that he is the
Velcro candidate _ everything sticks to him. To win in the fall,
that must change for Bush.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Evans Witt is a Washington-based political writer
who has covered presidential politics since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
