<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     05-19 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Cut Drug-Fighting Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis responded Thursday to President Reagan`s call for a
bipartisan task force on drugs by criticizing administration
cutbacks on money for drug education and enforcement.
   ``I have no problem with another study,'' the Massachusetts
governor told a news conference. But he then added, ``I don't think
we need another study.''
   Dukakis said that in 1985 Reagan signed ``a sweeping drug
education prevention act'' and then four months later cut 50
percent from the funding that had been agreed upon.
   ``There are modest sums that have been appropriated by Congress
for state and local law enforcement agencies to fight this war
against drugs. The president is the one who zeroed them out,'' he
said.
   Apparently unwilling to flatly reject Reagan's call for a
bipartisan effort, Dukakis said, ``This is a bipartisan issue.
There is no question about that. There is no Republican or
Democratic or Independent way to fight it.''
   Dukakis campaigned half a day in New Jersey before flying to
California on Thursday.
   They are the two biggest states holding primaries on June 7, the
day Dukakis hopes to bring his delegate total over the 2,081 needed
to lock up the Democratic presidential nomination.
   He denied he was already looking at potential running mates.
   ``There was not a word of truth in that article,'' he said of a
Washington Post story that said Dukakis aides were looking closely
at Sens. John Glenn of Ohio and Bill Bradley of New Jersesy for the
second spot on the ticket.
   Bradley has said he isn't interested.
   ``I haven't even thought about it,'' said Dukakis.
   After the last Democratic primaries on June 7, he said, ``there
will be plenty of time to be thinking about running mates.''
   He added that no member of his staff was authorized to discuss
the selection process.
   He said he would make his choice ``thoughtfully and with a
certain amount of reflection.''
</TEXT>
