<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     05-19 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Delegates To Debate Kadar Future</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party delegates gather Friday
to consider changes in Hungary's divided leadership, including the
possible replacement of party leader Janos Kadar.
   Kadar, the party's general secretary since the Soviets crushed a
revolt in 1956, has been increasingly blamed for Hungary's
deepening economic crisis and for resisting political reforms.
   ``Kadar has come to personify the mistakes that have been made
in the past,'' said a prominent party official, who spoke on
condition he not be identified further.
   ``No real change can occur as long as he remains on top,'' the
official said, adding that a growing number of party members wants
to see him step down.
   Hungary's Communist leaders are under mounting pressure from
both inside and outside the party to adopt political reforms as a
first step in revitalizing the nation's stagnating economy.
   Last week, the party's Central Committee said personnel changes
would be high on the conference agenda, fueling speculation Kadar
would be asked to step aside.
   However, Western diplomatic sources say there is still no clear
indication that Kadar intends to relinquish control soon.
   ``The situation is very fluid and the outcome (of the
conference) is almost impossible to predict,'' said a Western
diplomat, who requested anonymity.
   Any changes in the party leadership would likely be announced
after a Central Committee meeting scheduled for Sunday.
   While Kadar pioneered reforms that made the country relatively
prosperous in the late 1960s and 1970s, a series of recent economic
setbacks and austerity measures imposed to curb them have angered
many Hungarians.
   Premier Karoly Grosz, a leading contender to succeed Kadar, has
said that the political future of the party leader may be up for
debate during the conference, the first since 1957.
   Kadar has said in recent interviews that he would step down if
asked.
   In addition to personnel issues, some 900 delegates are to
debate a package of economic refoms and proposals for modest
political changes drafted by Kadar.
   Reformists in the party say the political reforms _ which
include provisions for secret ballots, limited terms of office for
party officials and multicandidate elections _ do not go far enough.
   Imre Pozsgay, an outspoken Central Committee member and a
leading proponent of reforms, has called for changes in the
constitution that would provide for referendums and guarantee the
independence of a growing number of political interest groups.
   Pozsgay, leader of the Communist sponsored People's Patriotic
Front, has also urged that the leading role of the Communist Party
be reviewed.
   The Central Committee announced last week that the delegates
would discuss the ``party's tasks and the development of the
political system.''
   A commentary published in the latest edition of Magyar Ifjusag,
the official newspaper of the Hungarian Communist Youth Union, also
called for changes, saying that ``internal instransigence within
the party has come to hamper roads to reform.''
   The economic weekly Figyeloe said in an editorial Thursday that
the conference ``will be a turning point in Hungary's national
destiny.''
   ``Economic reforms cannot be separated from the political
sphere,'' the editorial said.
   A gross foreign debt of more than $17 billion and rising
inflation led Hungary's leaders this year to impose Eastern
Europe's first personal and value added taxes.
   Many Hungarians, whose standard of living has been hit hard by
the measures, are calling for more of a voice in Hungary's economic
and political affairs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
