<DOCNO> AP880519-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpoletoFestival     05-19 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto Festival,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12th Edition Of Spoleto Festival Set To Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Historic Charleston's Southern charm
will take on the air of a European fairy tale Friday when the
Spoleto Festival U.S.A. opens for its 17-day run.
   In its annual rite of spring, the city is transformed into a
carnival of the performing arts, with music, dancing and drama
everywhere. Streets are adorned with colorful banners and street
corners become impromptu stages for mimes and musicians.
   The fairy-tale motif also will make its way to stages around the
city during this year's 12th edition of the festival founded by
composer Gian Carlo Menotti and patterned after its namesake
festival in Spoleto, Italy.
   Spoleto '88 _ the most ambitious American Spoleto to date _ will
open its run with the traditional round of speeches on the steps of
City Hall.
   There'll be a brass fanfare and a samba band from ``The Warrior
Ant'' _ a work by director Lee Bruer and composer Bob Telson
featuring more than 50 dancers, musicians and actors, which will
have its world premiere during Spoleto.
   Later Friday, the festival's major opera, Dvorak's ``Rusalka,''
goes on the boards at the Gaillard Municipal Auditorium.
   The work, based on a Czechoslovakian fairy tale and rarely
produced in this country, is filled with sprites, gnomes and
witches.
   The Spoleto version is replete with special effects and will be
sung in Czech. However, slides with the English translation will be
projected over the stage for festivalgoers.
   Echoing the fairy-tale theme is ``Miracolo d'Amore'' (Miracle of
Love), a dance-theater piece by New York choreographer Martha
Clarke. The work is based on Italian fairy tales and may prove
somewhat controversial in Charleston because it features some
nudity. However, it's not the first time there's been nudity on
stage at the festival.
   And, from 12th century France, comes the musical drama ``Herod
and the Innocents,'' performed by New York's Ensemble For Early
Music.
   Other highlights include Carl Henrich Graun's 1755 opera
``Montezuma'' about the Spanish destruction of the Aztec
civilization in the 1500s and the U.S. debut of the Symphony
Orchestra of Belgian Radio and Television.
   The popular Circus Flora featuring Flora the elephant, which
played to packed houses at Spoleto two years ago, is back for an
encore this season.
   Festival ticket sales have been brisk, said General Manager
Nigel Redden, who added organizers expect to surpass last year's
record box office.
   All in all, there will be 112 performances featuring 550
performers before the festival closes with a concert and fireworks
display at nearby Middleton Place Plantation on June 5.
   There'll also be dozens of additional performances for Piccolo
Spoleto (Little Spoleto), the companion arts festival staged by the
city of Charleston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRoucheTrial     05-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Trial,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Reschedules LaRouche Trial; Questions Oliver North Subpoena</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge who declared a mistrial in a conspiracy
case against political extremist Lyndon LaRouche has scheduled a
new trial for October and challenged a defense request to question
Oliver North, who LaRouche claims tried to ruin him.
   Although U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton has set the trial
for Oct. 3, he will first have to rule on defense contentions that
retrying LaRouche and his followers would violate their
constitutional protection against being tried twice on the same
charges.
   Keeton last week ordered defense lawyers to submit written
arguments on the double jeopardy issue by July 15 and given
Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham until Aug. 1 to respond.
Keeton is expected to rule before a Sept. 8 status hearing.
   Keeton declared the mistrial last month following complaints
from several jurors, who had been told when the trial began in
December that it would last about six months but later were told it
might last up to a year.
   The judge was careful to note he blamed the mistrial both on
lengthy hearings needed because of alleged government withholding
of documents from defense lawyers and on ``agressive behavior'' by
defense lawyers, a comment widely interpreted as an indication
Keeton would reject arguments that LaRouche and the others cannot
be retried because the mistrial was the prosecution's fault.
   LaRouche, six aides and five LaRouche political groups were
charged with conspiring to obstruct a 1986 federal grand jury
investigation of allegations that LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign raised more than $1 million through credit card fraud and
another $1 million or more through loan fraud.
   LaRouche, who is making his fourth run for the presidency,
contends the FBI and CIA infiltrated his organizations because of
Reagan administration anger at his refusal to support efforts to
arm the Contra rebels in Nicaragua. LaRouche contends the
infiltration and fabrication of evidence of fraud was directed by
North, the former Marine lieutenant colonel who ran a Contra
resupply network from the White House at a time when such aid was
prohibited by Congress.
   Defense lawyers have sought to question North from the outset of
the case and stepped up the effort three months ago after obtaining
a declassified memo written to North in which another key player in
the Iran-Contra affair, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord,
mentioned an associate's efforts to gather ``info against
LaRouche.''
   Keeton last week ordered defense lawyer William Moffitt, who is
handling the North request, to refine his lengthy arguments on the
request in a memo outlining what testimony defense lawyers believe
North could give that would be relevant to the case.
   Markham has opposed the request and said that he likely would
have to grant North immunity if Keeton ordered him to testify
because North is under indictment for his role in the Iran-Contra
scandal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
