<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0637 05-19 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0637,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors Sworn As Mecham Trial Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, ``The prospective xxx, with 3 grafs,
questionnaire handed out</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in former Gov.
Evan Mecham's criminal trial on charges of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan.
   About 100 prospective jurors filed into the Maricopa County
Superior Court room and then were sworn in the first step in
choosing a jury for the ousted governor and his brother, Willard.
   The Mechams did not attend today's court session. The former
governor's attorney, Michael Scott, said Mecham probably would
attend next week, after the field is narrowed and questioning of
prospective jurors begins.
   On Wednesday, a state Supreme Court justice refused a defense
request to delay the trial until the high court considers a defense
motion to return the charges to the state grand jury. However, the
justice agreed that the Supreme Court will hear arguments on that
issue June 1.
   The state Court of Appeals rejected a defense claim Monday that
the Mechams were denied ``substantial procedural rights'' in the
grand jury process.
   The former governor said he could not predict whether he will
fare any better in court than he did at his state Senate
impeachment trial. The Senate removed the 64-year-old Republican on
April 4, a year into his first term.
   ``I haven't broken any laws,'' Mecham said Wednesday. ``I looked
at the laws. My attorney looked at the laws. We've had experts look
at the laws. We haven't broken any of them.''
   The prospective jurors were given a questionnaire worked out by
the prosecution, defense and trial Judge Michael Ryan and designed
to ferret out obvious bias for or against the former governor.
   ``Please do not withhold any information in order to be seated
on this jury,'' Ryan told the prospective jurors.
   The 99 questions included whether the prospective jurors know
anyone involved in the Mecham case and whether they signed or
circulated petitions for or against Mecham while he was governor.
Others asked about favorite television shows and whether
prospective jurors have bumper stickers on their cars.
   The field is to be narrowed by the attorneys and judge with the
remaining prospective jurors to be called back for questioning
either Monday or Tuesday.
   Mecham faces six felony counts on three charges _ perjury,
filing false documents and fraud _ accusing him of concealing a
$350,000 campaign loan. Willard Mecham, who was his brother's 1986
campaign treasurer, faces three similar counts.
   Prosecutors said the Mechams failed to report the loan from
Tempe developer Barry Wolfson on personal or campaign financial
statements until after a newspaper reported the contribution.
   The former governor could face up to 22 years in prison if he is
convicted on all six counts.
   If the attorneys are unable to choose an impartial jury from the
initial pool of 100, Scott has said he probably will seek either to
dismiss the charges or to move the trial to another location.
   Scott said other motions may be filed before trial testimony
begins, probably after Memorial Day. Both sides have said they
expect testimony to take two to three weeks.
   In papers filed Wednesday with the state Supreme Court, defense
attorneys said the Mechams were entitled to ``an adequately
informed and properly instructed grand jury.''
   ``Instead the attorney general's office, in its inordinate
thirst for an indictment, and perhaps the celebrity that
prosecuting a controversial governor can bring, repeatedly tested
the very limits of judicial tolerance to which they might go in the
manipulation of this grand jury,'' the defense said.
   Mecham's attorneys contend that prosecutors were not justified
in pursuing a grand jury indictment after an earlier grand jury was
disbanded.
   Also Wednesday, the defense asked Ryan to reconsider a claim
that the Mechams were victims of selective prosecution.
   Ryan has rejected several other defense motions, including a
proposed change of venue and a motion by Willard Mecham for
separate trials.
   Mecham was convicted in the Senate of trying to thwart a death
threat investigation and of misusing $80,000 from the governor's
protocol fund by loaning the money to his auto dealership.
   He also was impeached on charges of concealing the $350,000
loan, but the Senate decided not to consider that charge for fear
of prejudicing Mecham's criminal trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
