<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   05-19 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Told That Reagan Won't Complain If He Cites Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush received an open invitation from the
White House Thursday to express policy differences without fearing
criticism ``in any way'' from President Reagan. Michael Dukakis hit
administration cutbacks in money for drug education.
   Dukakis' Democratic challenger, Jesse Jackson, campaigned on the
West Coast, but spent most of the day in private meetings.
   Bush, who has the Republican presidential nomination locked up,
also spent most of the day working privately. But the political
repercussions continued from his declaration on Wednesday that he
would not negotiate with drug dealers _ an implied disagreement
with administration talks with Manuel Noriega, the Panamanian
general facing drug charges in this country.
   The vice president's comment dominated the daily press briefing
at the White House, where spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said no
offense was taken by the president.
   ``As we go through the campaign, I would expect to see the vice
president speaking out on a number of issues,'' he said. ``I expect
a number of them will be different than existing policies and ...
we will not, we will not criticize them ... in any way.''
   At the same time, Fitzwater defended the administration's
approach to Noriega, which White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker
has likened to ``plea bargaining.''
   But the spokesman also gave these words of advice to White House
reporters: ``If you want to drive a wedge between the White House
and the vice president, forget it.''
   Bush received his free-expression pass from the White House as
public opinion polls showed him losing ground to Dukakis, the
all-but-certain Democratic nominee, a decline widely believed
linked in part to controversies involving Noriega and embattled
Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   The vice president, who stressed his loyalty to Reagan during
the early, competitive weeks of the primary campaign, has been
receiving unsolicited advice from Republican allies that he needs
to establish his own identity with the voters.
   ``Ronald Reagan is a very popular man but nobody wants a
clone,'' said New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, interviewed while
visiting London ``He must separate himself from Ronald Reagan.''
   Dukakis spent part of the day campaigning in New Jersey before
flying to California. The two states are among four that hold
primary elections on June 7, the last day of the Democratic primary
season.
   Dukakis is heavily favored to defeat Jesse Jackson in both those
primaries, and aides say he will have enough delegates to assure
his nomination by the time the results of those elections are
counted.
   The Massachusetts governor responded mildly to Reagan's call for
a bipartisan drug study commission. ``I have no problem with
another study,'' he said, although he also added, ``I don't think
we need another study.''
   Dukakis also criticized the administration as he spoke to
community leaders in a Camden, N.J., neighborhood known for drug
problems.
   He said that in 1985, Reagan signed ``a sweeping drug education
prevention act'' and then four months later cut the funding in half.
   ``There are modest sums that have been appropriated by Congress
for state and local law enforcement agencies to fight this war
against drugs. The president is the one who zeroed them out,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
