<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Missiles     05-19 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Missiles,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Plane Accidentally Drops Missiles on Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two missiles fell accidentally from a
Soviet military jet and exploded on a private farm Thursday,
damaging buildings and knocking out power but causing no injuries,
the official news agency PAP reported.
   The accident occurred near the southwestern town of Przemkow in
Legnica province, the report said. It gave no details on how the
accident occurred.
   The province is home base for the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact's
Northern Group of Forces. It is 200 miles southwest of Warsaw and
about 50 miles from the East German border.
   A resident reached by telephone said test flights are common in
the area.
   One year ago Thursday, a rocket accidentally dropped by a Soviet
fighter exploded in a barnyard in Wilkocin near Przemkow, killing
one man and injuring two people.
   The PAP report said the latest accident left two craters in a
private farm field, cracks and splits in some buildings and
unspecified damage to ``roof structures.''
   Also damaged was a 300-yard section of high-power lines,
interrupting electricity and shutting down the water pumping system
for Przemkow, a town of about 5,000 people.
   Police in Przemkow declined comment. But the resident said the
missiles fell several hundred yards from the nearest homes, setting
off loud explosions that knocked out windows.
   ``Luckily the missiles fell outside any residential area ...
because it would have been an awful thing,'' the man said. He said
one missile could be seen passing over the town into the fields.
``It made a great big crater.''
</TEXT>
