<HEAD>Old Clothes Pile Raises Tourist Interest Across N.C.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEACHLAND, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mountain of castoff clothing, offered
free in a pasture to bargain hunters who pay $5 to park, could
become North Carolina's hottest tourist attraction this weekend,
authorities say.
   ``We have been besieged with calls from all over the state
wanting to know how people can get to the free clothing,'' said
Sheriff Tommy Allen of Anson County.
   Lee Wright, a used-car dealer who owns the farm where the
clothes are stored, has refused to say where the garments came
from. But the sheriff said the clothing cost Wright nothing and was
hauled away from a second-hand clothing exporter in New York City.
   Allen said nothing apparently is illegal about giving the
clothing away or charging the $5 parking fee. And Anson County
Health Department officials said the operation will be considered a
flea market.
