<HEAD>Bok Named to Pulitzer Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sissela Bok, a philosopher and the author of
several books on issues of ethics and morality, has been elected to
the Pulitzer Prize Board, it was announced Thursday.
   Bok fills a vacancy created by the departure of University of
Chicago President Hanna Gray, who served for eight years, according
to the announcement by Michael I. Sovern, president of Columbia
University.
   David Laventhol, president of the Times Mirror Co., has been
elected chairman of the 17-member board for a one-year term, Sovern
said. He succeeds Roger Wilkins, who will remain a board member.
   Bok, an associate professor in philosophy at Brandeis
University, is the author of ``Lying: Moral Choice in Public and
Private Life'' and ``Secrets: On the Ethics of Concealment and
Revelation.''
