<HEAD>Kean Says Bush Must Not Be Reagan Clone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush must cast off his
``identical twin'' image and mark out his differences with Ronald
Reagan if he is to succeed Reagan as president, New Jersey Gov.
Thomas Kean said Thursday.
   Kean, sometimes mentioned as a possible vice presidential
candidate on a Bush ticket, said Bush can win only if he shows
voters how his presidency would differ from Reagan's.
   ``Vice presidents are often co-opted by the president when they
try to run. George Bush can't allow that to happen,'' Kean said in
an interview.
   ``Much as he likes and admires Ronald Reagan, he has got to,
with Ronald Reagan's full support, spell out where the differences
are,'' he said. ``If he does that effectively, I think he'll be
successful.''
   ``Ronald Reagan is a very popular man but nobody wants a
clone,'' Kean said.
   He did not rule out accepting the No. 2 pot on the Republican
ticket.
   ``I have said I did not want the position ... but it would be
totally arrogant to say that were the position offered ... you
would turn it down,'' Kean said.
