<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PCBs     05-19 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PCBs,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves to Tighten Control of PCB Handlers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation designed to close a loophole in
the handling of highly toxic chemicals known as polychlorinated
biphenyls, or PCBs, was approved Thursday by the House Energy and
Commerce Committee.
   The bill, endorsed by a voice vote, would require the
Environmental Protection Agency to write regulations controlling
so-called PCB brokers, the middlemen who contract to transport the
chemicals to disposal sites.
   ``There is no federal manifesting requirement to adequately
track PCBs from owner to final disposal,'' said Rep. Mike Synar,
D-Okla., the bill's principal sponsor. ``Literally, anybody with a
truck can get into the PCB brokerage business.''
   The manufacture of PCBs, most often used as insulators in
electrical equipment, has been banned since the late 1970s. The
nation faces a growing rate of PCB disposal in the coming years as
this equipment wears out.
   Synar said the broker loophole has resulted in PCB dump-and-run
cases across the nation. One broker who was paid millions of
dollars to handle disposal of 13{ million pounds of the chemicals
left them in Holden, Mo., and went bankrupt, leaving behind a site
cleanup bill of more than $30 million, he said.
   The legislation would require EPA to set up a system to keep
track of PCBs once they leave the original owner and to require
brokers to demonstrate they have the financial capability of
assuring safe disposal.
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said the bill has the support of the
environmental and business communities and of EPA, which is
drafting the type of regulations that would be required by the
legislation.
   Dave Colbert, an aide to Luken, said lawmakers feel EPA should
have a congressional directive to regulate PCB brokers in case the
president's Office of Management and Budget opposes such action.
   EPA and OMB have tangled during the Reagan administration over
the issue of whether the environmental agency should issue
regulations that haven't been specifically mandated by Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
