<2ND_LINE>AM-911 Arrest,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Arrested After Dispatcher Hears Boy Being Beaten</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father was arrested after an emergency
dispatcher heard a boy being beaten while the child sought help for
his father, who he believed had suffered a heart attack, police say.
   ``You can actually hear the child getting clobbered,''
Investigator Jack Simmons said.
   The emergency call made by the 11-year-old boy occurred May 12
and was recorded. Juvenile authorities investigating the case said
the boy feared his father was going to have a heart attack while
allegedly beating him.
   John Thomas Whiddon, 40, was arrested Wednesday, charged with
felony injury to a child and released on $2,000 bond.
   Simmons said Whiddon's son called the Fire Department's
emergency number and was describing his father's symptoms when a
man's voice was heard yelling, ``What are you doing on the phone?''
   ``The kid says, `I'm sorry, Dad,' then you hear blows, pops and
dull thuds and you hear the kid crying quite a lot,'' Simmons said.
   The call lasted less than two minutes because someone hung up
the telephone, Simmons said. The emergency dispatcher called police
and then redialed the number where the call originated.
   ``The dad gave the dispatcher a hard time,'' Simmons said. ``He
was cussing him out.''
   Simmons said six days elapsed between the incident and the
arrest because he did not get the case until Monday. The boy was
initially placed in the custody of Harris County Children's
Protective Services but has since been returned to his family.
</TEXT>
