<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSTrigger     05-19 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Trigger,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leukemia Virus May Trigger AIDS In Patients Infected By Both
Viruses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People infected by the AIDS virus may be more
likely to go on to develop the deadly disease if they also are
infected by a related virus that can cause a particularly fatal
form of leukemia, a study says.
   ``These laboratory results suggest that doubly infected
individuals have a worse prognosis for developing AIDS'' than those
who are infected only by the AIDS virus, said molecular virologist
Irvin S.Y. Chen, who published his study in Friday's issue of the
journal Science.
   ``The chances of any individual being infected by both viruses
are very slim, but among selected populations, such as intravenous
drug abusers, the chances are quite high,'' said Chen, of the
University of California, Los Angeles.
   Except among IV drug abusers, the leukemia virus is quite rare
in the United States. It is fairly common in southern Japan, the
Caribbean and parts of Africa, Chen said. So the study suggests
that people in those areas may be more likely to develop
full-fledged AIDS if they are exposed to the AIDS virus.
   But more study of people infected by both viruses must be done
to confirm the suspicion raised by laboratory studies, said Dr.
Stanley H. Weiss, chief of AIDS epidemiology at New Jersey Medical
School in Newark. Weiss is already undertaking such research in the
Newark and New York area.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by the human
immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, which usually remains dormant in
infected people for years before it may be activated to cause
full-fledged AIDS, which cripples the disease-fighting immune
system.
   Previous studies suggested almost any infection may help trigger
the dormant AIDS virus into an active killer.
   Chen and his colleagues performed experiments in laboratory
culture dishes showing that AIDS-infected white blood cells called
T cells produce large amounts of active AIDS virus if the cells
also are exposed to the human T-cell leukemia virus type I, or
HTLV-I.
   People infected by HTLV-I have a 1 percent lifetime chance of
developing a blood cancer called adult T-cell leukemia, which often
kills quickly. It is an important cause of leukemia in southern
Japan and the Caribbean. HTLV-I also is linked to a potentially
fatal, degenerative nerve disease that causes spasticity and
paralysis of the legs.
   Last month, the American Red Cross recommended that all donated
blood be tested for HTLV-I as soon as scientists develop a
practical test. A Red Cross study found about one out of every
4,286 units of donated blood carries HTLV-I. The risk of AIDS virus
in blood has been reduced to about one in 40,000 units because
donors are tested for signs of AIDS infection.
   A study performed by Weiss when he worked for the National
Cancer Institute showed HTLV-I is spreading among intravenous drug
abusers, with infection rates of 12 percent among New Jersey
addicts, 33 percent among New Orleans addicts overall, and 49
percent among black addicts in New Orleans.
   Intravenous drug addicts also are high risk for infection by the
AIDS virus, which also is spread in blood on shared needles and by
sexual contact.
   Infection by HTLV-I apparently activates the AIDS virus by
stimulating AIDS-infected white blood cells to divide, according to
the study Chen performed with molecular virologists Jerome Zack,
Alan Cann and James Lugo.
   While the study in Science deals only with HTLV-I, unpublished
laboratory results suggest full-fledged AIDS also may be triggered
in AIDS-infected people who also are infected by HTLV-II, an
extremely rare virus that can cause another type of leukemia.
   The AIDS virus is distantly related to the leukemia viruses.
   Dr. Edward L. Murphy Jr., a National Cancer Institute expert on
HTLV-I, agreed with Chen that the problem of dual infection by the
AIDS and leukemia viruses is mainly a problem for U.S. drug addicts
and for people in areas such as the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-KingTut     05-19 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-King Tut,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archaeology Student Finds King Tut Hoard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student rediscovered a forgotten hoard of grain,
dried fruit, spices and insects from the 3,300-year-old tomb of the
Egyptian King Tutankhamun, archaeologists said Thursday.
   ``It obviously is extremely important archaelogically because
it's a very large amount of material,'' said John Evans, director
of the University of London's Institute of Archaeology.
   ``Very little work has been done on material of this period in
Egypt, and I understand that some of the species which have been
identified are, in fact, the earliest occurrences,'' Evans said at
a news conference.
   Most of the discovery consists of the food placed in
Tutankhamun's tomb to sustain him on his journey to the afterlife.
Scientists said the material is well preserved and could provide
best evidence to date of the diet and lifestyle of the Egyptians at
the time of Tutankhamun's death in 1323 B.C.
   For more than 50 years, the hoard has lain undisturbed in 30
cardboard boxes in a musty storeroom at the Royal Botanical
Gardens. The specimens were sent in 1932 by Howard Carter, the
British archaeologist who discovered Tutankhamun's treasure-laden
tomb in the Valleys of the Kings at Luxor, Egypt, in 1922.
   They were to have been cataloged by the botanist Leonard Boodle.
But Boodle and Carter both died in the 1930s before the work could
be completed, and the specimens were stored in boxes labeled ``From
Ancient Egypt.''
   In February of this year, the material was turned over to a
French graduate student at the archaelogical institute, 23-year-old
Christian Tutundjian de Vartavan, for research leading to a
master's degree in archaeobotany, the institute's speciality.
   He recognized notations on the boxes as those of Carter,
providing the first clue that they might be from Tutankhamun's
tomb. Scientific analysis confirmed his theory and eventually
fragments were matched with photographs taken by Carter.
   ``It all fit in. It was beyond coincidence,'' said
archaeobotanist Gordon Hillmann, who supervised the student's work.
Tutundjian de Vartavan did not attend the news conference.
   Professor David Harris, director of the archaeology institute's
Department of Human Environment, said the announcement was delayed
until it had completed scientific analysis.
   ``We were anxious to announce it as soon as possible, lest it
should leak out, but we felt we had to keep it under wraps as long
as possible, so that we could get as much work accomplished as we
could,'' Harris said.
   He acknowledged that one reason for the secrecy was concern that
the Egyptian government might demand possession before the
institute had completed its analysis.
   Last week, the institute informed the Egyptian Embassy in London
about the discovery and offered to return the material. As of
Thursday, the institute had received no reply, Harris said.
   The hoard includes fragments of funeral wreaths and more than
five pounds of seeds, fruits and spices placed in Tutankhamun's
tomb, Harris said.
   Among identified species are emmer wheat for making bread on the
journey, barley for brewing beer, a large quantity of watermelon
seeds to chew on, coriander, fenugreek, black cumin, sesame seeds,
two kinds of juniper berries, grapes and a datelike fruit known as
a jujube.
   The grains, fruits and seeds were intended as raw materials that
figurines known as shawabtis found in the tomb would cultivate into
food needed by the ``ka'' _ one of the king's souls _ in the
afterlife, Harris said.
   Dr. Ken Thomas, a specialist in insects, said the remains of
thousands of beetles also had been identified. The foods were to
sustain the boy king through eternity, Thomas said, ``but the
insects got through first and had a pretty good crack at them.''
   The find represents only a fraction of the food buried in the
tomb. Harris said the remainder is in 110 to 120 original wicker
baskets and several pottery jars in the Cairo Museum and the Dokki
Agricultural Museum in Egypt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VenusVolcanoes 1stLd-Writethru a0681 05-19 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venus Volcanoes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Waves Provide New Hints Of Venusian Volcanic Action</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT; time set by source.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS wording of lead to show that two types of features
were detected, not three.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA scientists who bounced radio waves
off cloud-shrouded Venus detected huge blobs that may be lava flows
and rings that may be volcanic crater rims, both very bright and
possibly rich in fool's gold, a new study says.
   The study provides more evidence that Venus' volcanoes erupted
within the last few million years and possibly within recent
centuries, said researchers from the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Their findings appear in Friday's issue of the journal Science,
coinciding with the 10th anniversary of the launch of the Pioneer
Venus orbiter, a spacecraft that still circles the second planet
from the sun.
   JPL radar scientists Ray Jurgens and Martin Slade and geologist
R. Stephen Saunders transmitted radio waves from Goldstone to
Venus' equatorial region. Half the waves bounced back to three
210-foot-diameter, dish-shaped antennas at the Mojave Desert
facility.
   The fuzzy radar pictures revealed bright, or highly reflective,
rings of material on the surface, as well as bright blobs.
   The largest blob, measuring 350 miles long and 180 miles wide,
apparently is a large lava flow and has a large mound, possibly a
volcano, at its west end, Jurgens said.
   The largest ring is roughly 60 miles across and appears to be
the rim of a crater caused by a meteorite impact. But other rings
about 18 miles across may be rims of large volcanic craters called
calderas, he said.
   The researchers speculate the blobs and rings are so highly
reflective to radar because the lava flows and crater rims are rich
in iron pyrite or other metallic minerals blasted to the surface of
the planet by volcanic eruptions or meteorite impacts. Iron pyrite
is known as fool's gold because it looks like gold.
   Because fool's gold or other metallic minerals should decompose
and lose their reflectivity over time, the discovery ``certainly is
evidence of relatively recent volcanism,'' since old craters lack
bright rings, Jurgens said.
   It isn't possible to say whether ``recent'' means within the
last few million years or last few centuries because researchers
don't know how quickly rocks break down on Venus, said Jurgens and
Saunders, who is project scientist for the Magellan Venus Radar
Mapper spacecraft, set for launch next April.
   Radar readings from Pioneer suggested volcanoes existed on
Venus. Previous radar pictures made from Earth and by Soviet
spacecraft in 1983 revealed lava flows, volcanic craters and
craters from meteorite impacts.
   But researchers don't know if volcanoes still are active on the
planet, which is covered by thick, acid-laden carbon dioxide clouds
that prevent direct observation by telescopes.
   In 1984, scientists announced that Pioneer detected lightning
bolts and a 50-fold increase in sulfur dioxide concentrations in
Venus' atmosphere after 1978. Because lightning and sulfur dioxide
can be caused by eruptions, the discoveries suggested a gargantuan
volcano may have erupted shortly before 1978.
   Other studies also found highly reflective features on Venus'
mountains, but scientists debated whether the brightness was from
volcanic metallic minerals or simply artificial brightness created
by rough landscape.
   The blobs and rings found by the JPL study are the first highly
reflective features discovered on Venusian lowlands, and thus
support the theory that the brightness is caused by metallic
minerals, Jurgens said.
   ``It's a good working hypothesis to say these (blobs) are young
lava flows,'' but the radar images aren't good enough to determine
which rings are volcanic craters and which are impact craters, said
Harold Masursky, a planetary geologist with the U.S. Geological
Survey in Flagstaff, Ariz.
   ``We'll settle this argument with Magellan,'' which is scheduled
to reach Venus in August 1990 and map most of the planet using
radar, he said.
   ``Some of the big volcanoes on Venus may still be active, which
would be ... interesting,'' Masursky said. ``The only other places
we have ongoing volcanism are the Earth and (Jupiter's moon) Io.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0663 05-19 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armacost Hits Soviet Plan To Leave $1 Billion in Material in
Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RECASTS lede to include U.S. vow to aid rebels; INSERTS 1
graf after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: `We've heard, with background.
INSERTS 5 grafs after 9th graf pvs, `The position, with
congressional hearing. Picks up 10th graf pvs, With the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking State Department official on
Thursday criticized plans by retreating Soviet forces to leave up
to $1 billion in equipment and facilities for the Kabul government,
and reaffirmed the U.S. intention to continue backing the Afghan
rebels.
   ``There have been indications that we have picked up that the
intention of the Soviets to turn over equipment and facilities will
be on a fairly large scale,'' said Michael H. Armacost,
undersecretary of state for political affairs.
   ``We've heard estimates ranging from a half a billion to $1
billion worth of equipment and, or, installations and facilities,''
he added. ``That doesn't strike me as a demonstration of tremendous
restraint.''
   He was referring to statements by Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov, the
Soviet commander in Afghanistan, that the value of Soviet bases and
equipment left behind after the withdrawal would be 600 million
rubles, the equivalent of $1 billion.
   During negotiations that led to the Soviet agreement in Geneva
to withdraw its estimated 115,000 Red Army troops from Afghanistan,
Armacost and other U.S. officials proposed a mutual phase-out of
superpower military assistance to the Soviet-backed Kabul
government and U.S.-supported mujahadeen.
   The Soviets rejected the offer, but the United States kept its
promise on the table, saying it would match Soviet restraint with
``symmetrical'' reductions in aid to the mujahadeen. Otherwise,
U.S. support to the rebels would continue.
   Armacost said on Thursday, ``I would recall, simply, what we
said at the time we signed the Geneva agreement: that we retain the
right to support our friends. We will exercise the right in the
event the Soviets continue to supply equipment to Kabul. And we'll
have practical ways of accomplishing that purpose.''
   Armacost made the comments to reporters while outlining various
regional issues President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev are likely to discuss at their Moscow summit, May 29-June
2.
   He declined to predict whether Gorbachev would ask Reagan to
help ease the Soviet withdrawal by advising the mujahadeen to
refrain from harassing Red Army forces. As the first Soviet unit
crossed into its homeland on Wednesday, there were reports that
guerrilla attacks were continuing.
   ``The position we've taken on that has been generally that a
prompt timetable would be one which is more likely to elicit
cooperation from the mujahadeen.'' Armacost said. Beyond that, the
best way to protect withdrawing forces from attack is to make
``local arrangements'' with guerrilla groups, he said.
   On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, the Afghan accord was criticized as
betrayal of the resistance and an invitation to chaos and civil war.
   With the superpowers continuing the arms flow, ``What's to
prevent a continuing series of civil wars?'' Rep. Chester Atkins,
D-Mass., said at a hearing of the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Asian and Pacfic affairs.
   ``My fear is we are going to see a continung inferno in
Afghanistan that in time will lead to some kind of Soviet presence
unacceptable to the United States,'' Atkins said.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., also said he was concerned about
the ``apparent contradiction'' in the United States and Soviet
Union vowing to halt ``interference'' in Afghan affairs while at
the same time reserving the right to aid the rival factions.
   Dan Burton, R-Ind., declared his ``disgust'' that ``our State
Department with its appeasement policy has settled for half a loaf.
... There is no substitute for victory and they (Afghan resistance)
were well on their way to victory. We stopped them short of it.''
   With the removal of Afghanistan as the No.1 issue on Reagan's
list of regional confrontations with the Soviets, more attention is
likely to be given at the summit to conflicts in southern Africa
and Cambodia.
   Armacost said he was optimistic about the prospects for progress
in resolving conflicts in southern Africa, in part because of what
he termed ``quite successful'' talks recently among officials from
the United States, Angola, South Africa and Cuba.
   The United States is seeking a formula under which all Cuban
troops _ estimated at up to 45,000 _ would be withdrawn from
Angola, and South Africa would turn over Namibia to an independent
government.
   Armacost said the United States is hopeful that the Soviets will
use their influence with Cuba and Angola, but he expressed concern
that a reported increase in the number of Cubans in Angola might
set back the process.
   To lay the groundwork for discussion of the issues at the
summit, Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker was in
Portugal on Thursday winding up talks with a Soviet deputy foreign
minister, Anatoly Adamishin.
   Armacost reiterated administration views that the regional issue
most ripe for settlement is the restoration of a neutral Cambodia,
which is controlled by an estimated 120,000 Vietnamese troops.
Vietnam, which is beset by major economic problems, has stated its
intention to withdraw its forces in the early 1990s.
   ``The principal things we would like to see from the Soviets
here are that they press Hanoi to accelerate the timetable for
their withdrawal,'' the official said. He also said the Soviets
should talk directly with Prince Sihanouk, who represents the
anti-Vietnamese factions.
</TEXT>
