<HEAD>Byrd Renews Call For Meese To Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
on Thursday renewed his call for the resignation of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III and said that if Meese doesn't quit, ``the
president ought to do it for him.''
   Meese has launched a counterattack against his critics and has
told conservatives that he won't quit in the absence of evidence of
wrongdoing.
   Byrd, asked about Meese's comments, said, ``I think Mr. Meese
ought to resign.''
   ``The perception is that there's a great loss of morale'' at the
Justice Department because of the ongoing investigations of Meese,
said Byrd.
   Later, Byrd said again that Meese should go and added, ``if he
doesn't do it, the president ought to do it for him.''
   Byrd was commenting a day after Meese met with conservative
senators to say again that he wouldn't quit.
   A Senate subcommittee report issued earlier this month accused
Meese of violating a White House policy by helping the
scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   In addition, independent counsel James McKay has been conducting
a criminal investigation of Meese's involvement with Wedtech and
other matters. McKay is expected to issue a report within several
weeks which will raise ethical quetions about the behavior of
Meese, according to sources familiar with the investigation.
   According to Byrd, Meese and any occupants of high political
office should be willing to resign if their actions put their
offices ``under a cloud.''
   A president should tell his top appointees that ``if your
actions are such to put the office under a cloud, you'll have to
leave,'' Byrd said. He suggested that is what had occurred with
Meese.
