<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVA     05-19 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TVA,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sequoyah Plant Shut Down After Problem Develops In Non-Nuclear
Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sequoyah Nuclear Plant, which
resumed power production last week after more than 2{ years, shut
down Thursday because a problem developed on the non-nuclear side
of the plant, officials said.
   Herb Abercrombie, Sequoyah site director, said the Unit 2
reactor automatically shut down after a level control valve caused
a problem in the feed water system.
   A Tennessee Valley Authority investigative team was looking into
the cause of the valve problem. Abercrombie said all emergency
systems functioned properly and the plant shut down safely.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission was notified.
   TVA nuclear chief Steven A. White said he wants to make sure all
equipment is functioning properly before the plant is brought back
on line.
   TVA's nuclear program was idle for 2{ years because of safety
concerns.
   Sequoyah was generating power at about 73 percent of capacity
when the reactor was shut down at 2:15 p.m. Minutes before that,
White had said at a news conference that he expected the plant to
reach 100 percent production by Saturday.
</TEXT>
