<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-BYU     05-19 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-BYU,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Governor Barred From Speaking At Utah School</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham says he is unfazed
that a morality clause at Brigham Young University prevents him
from speaking there.
   ``I don't get too upset about anything,'' Mecham said Wednesday.
``It was just a group of young Republicans who wanted me to speak.
If they have a policy, they have a policy, and I won't speak.''
   The policy says that to appear at BYU, which is owned by the
Mormon Church, a speaker ``must not, in his or her personal life
(as reflected in the news media and common understanding of the
public), have committed acts of immorality, dishonesty or other
conduct that would make it inappropriate for the Church Education
System to feature him or her as a speaker. His or her life and
advice should make an appropriate model for students in an
educational system with our ideals.''
   Mecham, a Mormon, had been scheduled to speak at the Provo,
Utah, campus on May 26 or 27, in an appearance sponsored by Campus
Republicans, a student group.
   ``We do not allow to speak on campus people who are not worthy
examples,'' said Brad Hanesworth, a communications professor who is
the Campus Republicans' faculty adviser. ``I thought it was clear
that he did not meet the criteria'' on which speakers may appear at
BYU.
   ``We haven't decided that Evan Mecham is guilty, but now is not
the appropriate time for him to appear on campus,'' said Brent
Harker, a university spokesman.
   Harker pointed out Mecham is under indictment. Jury selection
began Thursday in Phoenix, Ariz., in Mecham's criminal trial on
charges of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   ``When a person is involved in (a court case), if he comes to
speak, that would imply an endorsement by the university,'' Harker
said. ``People would say, `Oh, he's speaking at BYU. They must
think he's OK.'''
   Mecham, 64, was impeached by the state House in February and
removed from office by the state Senate April 4.
   He could face up to 22 years in prison if he is convicted in the
criminal trial on all six felony counts on charges of perjury,
filing false documents and fraud.
</TEXT>
