<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DeathSquads     05-19 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Squads,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State-Sponsored Death Squads Blocking Third World Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State-sponsored death squads and terrorist groups
are blocking economic development in Central America, southern
Africa and the Philippines, speakers at an international conference
said Thursday.
   ``People like agricultural extension workers will not go out
into rural areas organizing people into agricultural programs if by
doing so they are branded as communists and are liable to be
harassed, attacked and even murdered,'' said Ian Linden, general
secretary of the Catholic Institute for International Relations.
   Linden said the independent charity sponsored the two-day
conference on the ``growing phenomenon'' of development projects
shut down by death squads and vigilante groups. He said such
shutdowns, which had occurred in the Philippines, southern Africa
and Central America, had created anxieties in many development
agencies including the Catholic Institute.
   In Mozambique, a member of the country's ruling Politburo said
South African-backed death squads were ``destroying Mozambique's
potential for independent, self-sustaining economic development.''
   Jorge Rebelo blamed South African-sponsored attacks for severe
food shortages.
   A Haitian priest said ``repression and terror'' by
state-sponsored death squads remain the reality in his nation, the
Western hemisphere's poorest country.
   The Rev. Freud Jean, who is general secretary of the Roman
Catholic church's National Commission of Justice and Peace, said
there is no possibility for development if people continue to be
terrorized by the paramilitary Tonton Macoutes, which started
operating with backing from former President Francois Duvalier 30
years ago.
   In the Philippines, there is a growing perception that active
church members, anti-nuclear activists and proponents of agrarian
reform are communists or radicals, said a Philippine human rights
advocate.
   Dr. Maria Serena I. Diokno, head of the National Movement to
Disband Vigilantes, said these people and farmers have little
chance for judicial recourse if they are harmed because vigilante
groups enjoy government sanction.
   Mrs. Diokno said ``massive poverty and inequality, which cause
and nurture insurgency, must be attacked from the roots.''
   Author and university lecturer Jorge Caceres Prendes said that
in Central America, economic development has been hindered not only
by state-sponsored terrorism but by the continued U.S. intervention
in the region.
   Linden said virtually every speaker provided evidence that
national security forces are sponsoring vigilante groups and death
squads ``in one way or another.''
   Some speakers, such as Caceres, said one solution to these
paramilitary forces is for governments to be held accountable to
world opinion. Others called for threatened groups to form their
own self-defense units.
   But Linden said: ``Obviously the solution is going to be along
the lines of strengthening poor communities with education, with
community organanization and with the type of development projects
that will ... give them the courage and the mutual trust and the
solidarity among themselves to withstand some of these assualts.''
</TEXT>
