<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-19 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislator Criticizes Mass Arrests of Arabs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli officials in the occupied territories
have jailed one out of every 200 Arab men over the age of 18 for
six months without trial, a legislator said Thursday.
   In addition to the 1,900 jailed under emergency regulations
requiring no trial or specific charges, another 8,100 Palestinians
are in prison awaiting trial or serving sentences for specific
actions, left-wing legislator Dedi Zucker said.
   ``The scale of the arrests shows the political echelon has lost
all control over the situation,'' Zucker, of the Citizens Rights
Movement, alleged.
   Army and Defense Ministry officials refused comment, saying only
they were checking Zucker's figures.
   Chief military prosecutor Brig. Gen. Amnon Strachnov said last
week that 5,000 Palestinians were jailed since the start of the
Arab uprising on Dec. 8. Of those, 1,700 were being held without
trial, he said.
   But former Cabinet member Amnon Rubinstein of the Center
Movement told Israel radio that close to 2,000 Palestinians were
being held without trial.
   Rubinstein, a law professor, also criticized authorities for
abolishing a legal safeguard that required administrative detainees
to appear before a judge within four days of their arrest.
   The requirement was scrapped when the number of administrative
detainees skyrocketed during the uprising, and Rubinstein demanded
reinstatement.
   Israeli officials have said the mass arrests have helped calm
the violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Also Thursday, the American-born director of the Jerusalem
Visitors Information Bureau, a Palestinian information service,
said she visited a village of 6,000 near the West Bank town of
Ramallah that was raided by Israeli troops for three straight days
this week.
   Lesley Abukhater, originally of Louisville, Ky., said she saw
five Arab homes with broken furniture and windows in the village of
Beita Laqya, and the owners told her Israeli troops were
responsible for the damage.
   She said six villagers were arrested in the raids and that local
residents said many people were beaten.
   Mrs. Abukhater said Beit Laqya apparently was targeted because
it is a so-called ``liberated'' village, meaning Arab residents
have blocked off roads to outsiders and fly the Palestinian flag,
outlawed in Israel.
   Two other ``liberated'' villages near Ramallah were raided
Wednesday, and one Palestinian was killed and 10 wounded, hospital
officials said. About 300 Arabs were detained.
   Zucker said that before the Arab uprising began, only about 70
Palestinians were held without trial under emergency regulations at
any one time.
   He said the present detainees were denied special privileges,
including access to radio, television and newspapers, that they are
supposed to enjoy since their detention is viewed as a preventive
measure instead of punishment.
   Zucker said he also conducted a random study of 3,300 Arabs held
for six months without trial and determined the average age of the
detainee was 25. Fifteen percent of the detainees were between the
ages of 16 and 21, while 58 percent were between 21 and 30 years
old.
   In other developments:
   _ The West Bank's military government permitted the
reunification of 40 Palestinian families as a goodwill gesture.
   The military government applies stringent standards in issuing
residency permits, for example often only granting temporary
tourist visas to the foreign-born spouses of West Bank residents.
As result, hundreds of Palestinian families are separated.
   _ In Tel Aviv, a district court judge rejected a motion to
release from custody four staff members of the ultra left-wing
newspaper Derech Hanitzotz.
   The four were jailed for unspecified security offenses.
Providing the first details on the case, the court said Thursday
the prosecution presented evidence the defendants were members of a
hostile organization, Israel radio reported.
</TEXT>
