<HEAD>Nicaragua Says Journalist Infiltrated CIA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge was
quoted Thursday as saying a Nicaraguan journalist penetrated the
CIA as a Sandinista counter-intelligence agent.
   The reporter was identified as Maria Lourdes Pallais Checa, a
graduate of Columbia University in New York.
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada quoted Borge as saying that
she was ``a counter-intelligence agent who worked in enemy ranks.''
   It said he made the remarks Sunday at an appearance on the
remote Caribbean coast of Nicaragua.
   Barricada said Pallais had lived for five years in the United
States and had been employed by various American and European news
organizations.
   (Pallais worked for The Associated Press in New York from August
1978 until November 1979, first on the editing desk of the Latin
American service and later in the New York City bureau.)
   Borge was quoted as saying: ``She carried out missions in the
heart of the CIA.''
   ``Some have been there for several years and continue there;
others we have been forced to take out of there for different
reasons, and one by one they will continue to be claimed back by
our people,'' he said.
   No one answered the telephone at Pallais' home in Managua
Thursday.
   Pallais' brother, Marcel Pallais Checa, a supporter of the
Sandinista National Liberation Front, was killed by the National
Guard of then-President Anastasio Somoza during the 1978-79
revolutionary war.
   (Pallais resigned from the AP in 1979, saying she wanted to
investigate her brother's death and help care for her ill mother.)
   The Sandinistas came to power in July 1979, ending 42 years of
rule by the rightist, pro-American Somoza dynasty.
