<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-QuittingSmoking     05-19 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quitting Smoking,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Variety of Help over Long Term Key to Quitting Smoking, Survey
Finds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The method a smoker chooses to try to kick the
habit is less important than a doctor's firm advice and the
long-term support of others, a new survey says.
   ``There is no single intervention method clearly more effective
for all people than the other methods,'' said Dr. Thomas K. Kottke,
a Mayo Clinic heart specialist and co-author of the survey.
   He and his colleagues on the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force
reviewed 39 studies of ways to stop smoking. Those techniques
ranged from ``one-shot'' strategies such as sensory deprivation and
injections, to combinations of techniques such as physician
counseling, nicotine gum and behavorial therapy.
   ``Success was not associated with novel or unusual
interventions,'' the team reported in Friday's Journal of the
American Medical Association.
   ``It was the product of personalized smoking-cessation advice
and assistance, repeated in different forms by several sources over
the longest feasible period.''
   Most effective were approaches in which physicians and
counselors worked with smokers, and the smokers also attended
stop-smoking groups and perhaps used booklets, videotapes and
homework, Kottke said.
   Nicotine gum was also helpful, though not everyone can use it,
he said.
   After a six-month period, such programs achieved a success rate
37 percent above that for individuals trying to quit on their own,
he said.
   Least effective, and often costly as well, were one-time
techniques such as sensory deprivation treatments, he said.
   A related report in the Chicago-based medical journal said a
blood-pressure drug called clonidine has been shown effective in
reducing the craving to smoke.
   Seventy-one heavy smokers who had tried unsuccessfully to quit
were recruited for the study.
   Thirty-three took clonidine and 38 took a tablet containing no
medication. Neither group knew what it was taking. All subjects
also underwent behavioral therapy.
   Six months after discontinuing medication, 27 percent of the
clonidine subjects reported they were still not smoking compared
with 5 percent of those who took the placebo, the researchers said.
   Clonidine, also marketed as Catapres, inhibits some of the
action of the nervous system and has previously been shown to
reduce opiate and alcohol withdrawal symptoms, the study said.
   Its success in helping people quit smoking is similar to that
reported with nicotine gum, but clonidine may eventually prove
superior because it doesn't perpetuate nicotine dependence, the
study suggested.
   But the researchers said larger studies over longer periods are
needed before it becomes a standard treatment.
   One surprising finding, according to Dr. Alexander H. Glassman
of Columbia University in New York, was that 61 percent of the
subjects had suffered from major depression at some time in their
past.
   People who have made several attempts to stop smoking and failed
often believe they have a ``moral weakness,'' the study said.
   But its findings suggest ``that for many smokers who try to stop
and cannot, the problem is not a moral one but rather an associated
vulnerability between affective (mood) disorder and nicotine.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
