<HEAD>`Best Mouser in Britain' Dies in His Sleep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last 3 grafs with 5 grafs to ADD more background on
Wilberforce. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilberforce, a black and white tomcat who was a
companion to four British prime ministers after straying into
Downing Street in 1973, died in his sleep Thursday at the age of 15.
   The feline, often seen lounging on the front doorstep of the
prime minister's official residence at No. 10 Downing St.,
developed a reputation for being ``the best mouser in Britain.''
   Wilberforce was found during the tenure of Edward Heath, and
served as a mouse-catcher and pet for successive administrations.
   ``He received lots of mail, people wanting to know how he was,
wish him luck,'' and the Downing Street staff answered for him, a
staff spokesman said.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher talked to Wilberforce when she
encountered him in the corridors of power, and she gave him a
special farewell present when he retired to a private home at an
undisclosed location in Essex, northeast of London, more than a
year ago.
   One of his last meals at Downing Street was a tasty tin of the
best Soviet pilchards _ a kind of herring _ picked out specially by
Mrs. Thatcher at a Moscow supermarket during a tour of the Soviet
Union.
   Mrs. Thatcher was saddened by the news of Wilberforce's death,
which was given to her at the end of a morning Cabinet meeting, her
press office said.
   Wilberforce will be buried near his home, the office said. He
had no known survivors.
</TEXT>
