<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CheeseMuseum     05-19 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cheese Museum,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Cheese: Museum Will Open With Pork Barrel Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new exhibit deals with a product that
comes from cows, but to many lawmakers it's just plain pork: The
New York State Museum of Cheese opened Thursday.
   Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann was scheduled to preside over the
ribbon cutting for perhaps the state's most notorious pork-barrel
project.
   The museum was developed with the help of money tucked into the
state budget at Hoffmann's request. The $425,000 museum received
$175,000 over the past three years from the state Legislature's
pork barrel, with the rest of the cost coming mainly from local
sources in this central New York community.
   The museum is housed in the former Weeks and Merry Cheese
Factory, which shipped cheese to England a century ago. The
building was moved from nearby Verona to Erie Canal Village here, a
re-creation of a mid-19th century Erie Canal community.
   Cheese-making tools and equipment, including curd knives, cheese
forms and a cheese press, were collected from barns and old cheese
factories across the state.
   While almost everyone else calls it pork barrel spending,
legislators and Gov. Mario Cuomo refer to the allocations such as
the ones to the museum as ``member items'' or ``legislative
initiatives.''
   The items, proposed by individual legislators, are reviewed by
the state budget division but in general don't get the kind of
scrutiny that major spending items do.
   Hoffmann, who admits that ``the Cheese Museum sounded kind of
funny the first time I heard it, too,'' said the project makes
``good economic sense'' for Rome, which lost more than 50 percent
of its manufacturing jobs in the last decade.
   ``The people of Rome have experienced three years of being the
brunt of everybody's joke and recurring stories about pork barrel
spending,'' said Hoffmann, a Syracuse Democrat.
   ``The cheese musem is something of which they are enormously
proud,'' she said.
   She added that she hopes the publicity ``can be turned into an
advertising plus for the tourist industry being developed by Rome.''
   Meanwhile, ``cheese museum'' continues to be synonymous with
``pork barrel'' and the brunt of jokes in the state capital, Albany.
   Even Cuomo got a few guffaws Wednesday when asked why he wasn't
attending the ceremony.
   ``I gave (scheduling aide Larry) Belinsky some beef when I found
out I was going to be in New York City instead of the cheese
museum,'' said Cuomo, who will be watching his chief of staff,
Gerald Crotty, receive an award from a citizens' group. ``It was a
close call, the cheese museum or Crotty.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     05-19 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Rejects White House Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Thursday
rejected indirect White House criticism of his refusal to accept a
U.S. Middle East peace plan and blamed Arab leaders for blocking
peace talks.
   Shamir did not directly criticize the Reagan administration for
issuing a statement that also praised his political rival, Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres, who supports the U.S. plan.
   But leaders of Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc accused the White
House of interfering in Israel's domestic affairs, and warned such
actions would backfire in Israel's November election.
   ``This will just strengthen the Likud because we don't want to
be a banana republic,'' Likud legislator David Magen was quoted as
saying by the domestic Itim news agency.
   The White House statement, issued after a meeting in Washington
on Tuesday between Peres and President Reagan, praised Peres for
``the courage and wisdom to say yes when real opportunities arise.''
   In an oblique reference to Shamir, the statement criticized
``those leaders who are negative, consistently reject new ideas and
fail to exploit realistic opportunities to bring about
negotiations, make progress impossible. In the end, they will have
to answer to their own people for the suffering that will
inevitably result.''
   Labor and Likud have governed in a fragile coalition since 1984,
but the alliance has all but disintegrated because of the dispute
over the Middle East peace process.
   Peres backs the U.S. plan which calls for an international
conference to launch direct talks between the parties to the
conflict. The plan also provides for talks on a final settlement to
begin by the end of 1988.
   Shamir objects to the international conference and to setting a
timetable for negotiations.
   Responding to the White House statement Thursday, Shamir said he
did not believe it was directed at him.
   ``I think that if there are elements in the Middle East who
reject peace, who avoid peace talks, it's the Arab leaders,''
Shamir was quoted as saying by Israel army radio.
   Shamir also said he hoped the United States would continue its
policy of not interfering in Israel's internal affairs.
   Likud leaders, meanwhile, criticized Peres, saying he should be
recalled to Israel and had no authority to speak for the Israeli
government.
   Peres told Israel radio that ``we should always ask what's good
for the state, not what's good for the Likud. I think this was a
trip with important possibilities during which we explained
Israel's position in a positive way.''
   Peres was scheduled to return to Israel Friday after a two-week
trip that included stops in Hungary, Spain and the United States.
   Shamir also criticized Peres for meeting Tuesday in Washington
with Yuri Dubinin, the Soviet ambassador to the United States.
   Shamir demands that the Soviet Union establish diplomatic ties
with Israel before getting involved in the Middle East peace
process. Moscow cut the ties after the 1967 Middle East war.
   Peres told Israel radio an intensive dialogue with the Soviet
Union is in Israel's interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
