<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Right-Left     05-19 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Right-Left,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baseball Players Prompt Suggestion that Right-handers Live Longer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of lifespans of baseball players leads two
doctors to suggest that right-handed people may live slightly
longer than left-handers.
   In a letter published Thursday in the science magazine Nature,
they said they studied The Baseball Encyclopedia and found that
right-handers averaged a lifespan of 64.64 years, compared with
63.97 years for left-handers.
   The letter was signed by Diane F. Halpern of the psychology
department of California State University and Stanley Coren of the
psychology department of the University of British Columbia.
   They said their study covered 1,472 right-handers and 236
left-handers, and excluded players who batted with one hand and
threw with the other.
   No discrepancies appeared until after age 33. After that, about
2 percent more right-handers than left-handers survive at each
following five-year period, the researchers said.
   They said the study gave no information about the possible cause
of the apparent discrepancy, but suggested three possibilities:
that left-handers may suffer stresses in the womb or around the
time of birth that affect their longevity; that genetic effects or
hormones may have hampered their immune system, or that
``left-handers may have more accidents in an environment designed
for a right-handed majority.''
   They concluded: ``These factors may act singly or in concert to
account for the fact that left-handers seem to have a shorter
lifespan.''
</TEXT>
