<DOCNO> AP880519-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&LFund     05-19 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Fund,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Renew Pledge to Have U.S. Stand Behind By S&L Deposits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators renewed the government's pledge
Thursday to stand behind deposits in the nation's savings and loan
institutions, after a congressional agency reported the doubling of
red ink in the federal S&L insurance fund.
   ``There is absolutely no doubt the U.S. Congress stands behind
our deposit insurance program,'' Banking Committee Chairman William
Proxmire, D-Wis., said at a hearing by his panel.
   Frederick D. Wolf, director of the accounting and financial
management division of the General Accounting Office, said the
liabilities of the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
exceeded its assets by $13.7 billion at the end of 1987, up from
$6.3 billion a year earlier.
   Further, he said, the money available to the insurance fund _
$28 billion over the next 10 years _ ``probably will not be
adequate'' to restore the industry's health by closing or merging
505 institutions listed as insolvent.
   Wolf estimated it would cost $30 billion to $35 billion to clean
up the S&L mess, which is primarily centered in Southwestern states
hard hit by depressed real estate and oil markets. That estimate
does not include an additional 435 ``barely solvent'' institutions,
he said.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates 3,120
federally insured institutions, says the cost will be $21.8
billion, but Wolf said that projection was based on some
``extremely optimistic'' assumptions.
   Private analysts, who testified after Wolf, put the price tag as
high as $64 billion and growing. Proxmire called that sum,
equivalent to 2.5 percent of the national debt, enormous.
   However, Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking Republican on the
committee, said the $64 billion estimate offered by Bert Ely, an
Alexandria, Va., analyst, was ridiculous.
   ``I don't want to minimize the problem. ... But let's not panic
the American people and create a self-fulfilling prophecy,'' Garn
said. ``I want to keep this in perspective. ... Not one single
federally insured depositor, up to the $100,000 limit, has lost one
dime.''
   The GAO report comes only nine months after Congress authorized
the sale of $10.8 billion in bonds over three years to bring in
money to the insurance fund. The bonds are being paid off through a
special assessment on savings institutions.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., considered the likely
successor to Proxmire when the committee chairman retires next
January, said Congress should be ready to act again soon after the
next president takes office.
   He accused the Reagan administration of papering over the
problem, adding, ``It's clear we have a big problem here. ... I
think it's getting worse, not better.''
   Bank Board Chairman M. Danny Wall, speaking with reporters
outside the hearing room, said it is too early to tell if FSLIC
will need more money. For now, he said, the bank board has $4
billion in cash on hand and enough additional money coming in over
the next two years.
   ``We don't think we can responsibly shut down thrifts at a
faster pace,'' Wall said.
   However, most of the private analysts appearing before the
committee urged swift action to stem mounting losses.
   Because the insurance fund needs to conserve cash, it has been
keeping hundreds of money-losing institutions open, hoping to
persuade private investors or healthy S&Ls to take them over with
federal assistance.
   If regulators are to move faster, the key question is who should
pay.
   Theo H. Pitt Jr., chairman of the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, the industry's largest trade group, stopped short of
calling for a taxpayer bailout, but he told reporters the industry
has reached the limit if what it can pay.
   ``We can't pay any more and not reduce the capital levels of
this industry to perilous levels,'' he said.
   Proxmire said he hoped a taxpayer rescue could be avoided, and
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said flatly he would oppose use of tax
money.
   However, Ely, Stanley C. Silverberg of the Washington-based
Golembe Associations and Stuart I. Greenbaum, a professor at
Northwestern University, said $30 billion to $40 billion in tax
money would have to be spent.
   ``The key thing the next president has to do is recognize that
the big hit must be taken quickly,'' Ely said.
</TEXT>
