<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Shrine     05-19 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Shrine,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Experts Search Golden Temple; Sikhs Reportedly Kill 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-India-Sikhs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bomb experts searched the Golden Temple
on Thursday after a 10-day standoff between militant Sikhs and
Indian security forces, and Sikh gunmen reportedly killed 25 people
to avenge the siege of the holy shrine.
   As the search for hidden explosives began, a committee of Sikh
elders that manages the 400-year-old temple began trying to work
out ways to reopen the temple to worshipers.
   Police Chief K.P.S. Gill said workers found four bodies inside
the shrine Thursday, one day after the last of the militant Sikhs
emerged and surrendered to Indian authorities.
   ``We are still searching for dead men and arms. It may be by the
weekend we can say it is all clear,'' Gill said.
   A curfew was in effect in the temple's immediate vicinity.
Residents were kept out of an area extending for 300 yards outside
the walls of the sprawling complex.
   The temple is the center for Sikh extremists who have waged a
guerrilla war since 1982 for an independent Sikh homeland in the
rich farming state of Punjab. Sikhs are a religious minority in
India but a majority in Punjab.
   Forty-five men and one woman walked out of the temple Wednesday
during a cease-fire by the 2,800 policemen, commandoes and
paramilitary troops posted outside.
   Twelve of the men, described by authorities as ``hard-core
terrorists,'' were charged with murder and possession of arms.
   At least 46 people, mostly militant Sikhs, died in the siege,
according to official statements. Four other militants committed
suicide.
   Despite the government's success in ending the siege, its
authority is still challenged by continuing Sikh attacks elsewhere
in Punjab state.
   The United News of India said Sikh gunmen shot and killed 25
people across Punjab in seven separate overnight attacks, raising
the death toll since the start of the year to 1,088.
   At least 40 people were killed Tuesday and Wednesday, including
30 migrant Hindu laborers shot to death as they slept at a camp
near the state capital, Chandigarh. A note found near the laborers'
bodies said the killings were to avenge the siege of the Golden
Temple.
   The temple siege _ the strongest government anti-terrorist
action since a 1984 army raid on the shrine _ began May 9 after
Sikh extremists inside fired at police commanders on an inspection
tour outside the temple. Five officers were injured.
   Eight hundred pilgrims and temple workers were evacuated from
the temple May 10, and 146 people, including some Sikh extremists,
surrendered during a cease-fire Sunday.
   During the surrender Wednesday, the last of the militants
emerged from the temple in small groups and were taken for
questioning by police.
</TEXT>
