<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CongressionalSpending     05-19 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressional Spending,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Spending $1.4 Billion on Legislative Branch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a $1.4 billion legislative
branch spending bill Thursday after voting a policy of zero
tolerance of drug use among its employees but refusing to extend to
them any civil rights protections.
   The bill, passed 277-104, would increase spending by Congress
and its agencies by 1.6 percent above current levels, including a
16.5 percent hike for its leadership staffs.
   The House rejected several amendments aimed at freezing or
cutting costs, accepting only a symbolic $5 million reduction in
its estimated postage costs.
   For the third straight day, the House approved an amendment
requiring that no federal funds go to a workplace where drugs are
used, sold or made.
   The provision, offered by Rep. Robert Walker, R-Pa., was
approved 286-98, despite complaints that it was an election-year
gimmick that wouldn't solve the problem.
   The amendment gives ``the impression that we've done something
about drugs, but ... we won't have done a whit,'' said Rep. David
Obey, D-Wis., who called it a ``garbage'' amendment.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., was forced to withdraw her amendment
requiring Congress to obey the civil rights law it imposed on the
rest of the nation 24 years ago. The amendment banning
discrimination based on race, sex, religion, age, national origin
or physical handicap was deemed out of order on the spending bill.
   The House bill, by tradition, does not include the allowance for
the Senate, where the bill was sent. The House Appropriations
Committee estimated the Senate portion would add $413 million to
the total.
   The bill did not address the question of pay raises for members
of the House and Senate, leaving that until later in the year when
President Reagan makes his annual recommendation.
</TEXT>
