<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0629 05-19 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Beirut Fighting Rages Despite Syrian, Iranian Efforts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with shelling
rages into night, Iranians no longer oppose Syrian intervention. No
pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells crashed near the Syrian-held
airport highway Thursday as rival Shiite Moslem militias battled
with artillery and machine guns for a 14th day despite efforts by
Syria and Iran to end the fighting.
   Iran's chief mediator, acting Foreign Minister Ali Mohammed
Besharati, toned down his earlier public opposition to Syrian
military intevention to snuff out the fighting for control of south
Beirut's slums.
   The thud of shell explosions reverberated across Beirut. The
Iranian-backed Hezbollah and the pro-Syrian Amal militia, who have
been battling since May 6, accused each other of starting the duel.
Shelling broke out at midafternoon and raged after nightfall.
   Police reported earlier that one man was killed and 10 people
were wounded in daylong machine-gun clashes between Hezbollah, or
Party of God, and Amal, Arabic for hope. Authorities said they had
no new reports of casualties.
   The Syrian command said no Syrian troops or positions along the
5-mile highway that abuts the shantytowns were hit in the shelling.
   Thursday's casualties brought the overall toll to 244 dead and
772 injured since fighting flared in the slums, where
Hezbollah-affiliated groups are believed to hold most of the 18
foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   In Jerusalem, Vernon Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, said he will return to Syria on Friday on a mission to
secure the release of the nine American hostages.
   He declined to go into details of his Damascus trip.
   Walters said his return to the region was prompted by concern
for the safety of the hostages as the fighting between Amal and
Hezbollah escalated.
   He also apparently is seeking Israel's assurances that it will
not conduct raids into Lebanon against Hezbollah and thereby
endanger the hostages. Israel has blamed Hezbollah for helping
Palestinian guerrillas attack northern Israeli settlements.
   The independent Beirut daily paper An-Nahar said Iran was
opposing a Syrian military deployment throughout the 16-square-mile
slums to quell the fighting. More than 80 percent of the estimated
250,000 residents have fled.
   But Besharati told reporters after meeting with Lebanese
Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite, on Thursday evening
that ``if the entry of the Syrian forces to the suburbs guarantees
security, we will not object.''
   He said Wednesday that Iran opposed Syrian deployment because
there was some opposition in the suburbs to such a move.
   There was no explanation for Besharati's change of heart.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, is Iran's principal
Arab ally. But the government of President Hafez Assad is alarmed
by Tehran's efforts through Hezbollah to dominate Lebanon's 1.2
million Shiites, the country's largest single sect.
   Justice Minister Nabih Berri, who heads Amal, announced a
sweeping purge of the militia's military command because of its
poor performance against the outnumbered Hezbollah.
   The communique did not say whether new commanders had been named.
   A police spokesman said before the shelling that the fighting
had ``settled into mere exchanges of machine-gun fire'' between the
Amal fighters entrenched in the district of Shiyah on the northern
edge of south Beirut and Hezbollah gunmen in control of 90 percent
of the slums.
   He said most of the casualties were civilians injured in Shiyah
by sniper fire. One man was killed by a bullet in Shiyah as he
tried to check on his damaged apartment, the spokesman said.
   An-Nahar said Iran wants Syria to deploy only a ``disengagement
force'' to separate the fighters and rejects any effort to disarm
Hezbollah.
   Iran also wants ``the case of releasing (foreign) hostages to be
separate from the objectives of the Syrian deployment,'' the paper
added, without further elaboration.
   There have been unconfirmed reports that Hezbollah was
threatening to kill foreign hostages if Syrian forces moved into
the slums.
   Nine of the foreign hostages are American. The longest held is
Terry Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press. He was seized in west Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Syria deployed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks and armored vehicles
on the southern, western and northern edges of south Beirut on
Sunday and said the force was prepared to move in to quell the
fighting.
</TEXT>
