<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Drugs     05-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Hepatitis-Drugs,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Reports Increasing Number Of Hepatitis Cases Among Drug
Abusers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So-called ``type A'' hepatitis, a liver disease
traditionally linked to poor hygiene, is showing up more and more
in outbreaks among drug abusers, federal health researchers said
Thursday.
   Outbreaks of Hepatitis A among drug abusers have occurred in New
York, California and a variety of other locations across the
country in the past two years, the national Centers for Disease
Control said.
   In New York's upstate Cortland County, for example, 58 percent
of the hepatitis A cases last year occurred among ``known or
suspected drug abusers,'' the CDC said.
   Between 1982 and 1986, the percentage of hepatitis A patients
admitting previous use of injectible drugs rose from 4 percent to
19 percent, according to the CDC's Viral Hepatitis Surveillance
Program. Those statistics are not complete, since the program does
not cover all cases, CDC researchers stressed.
   ``How widespread this is, we can't really tell,'' said Dr. Craig
N. Shapiro, a CDC hepatitis specialist. ``Where there's a greater
percentage of drug users, there might be a greater problem.''
   Shapiro noted that health officials reporting hepatitis cases to
the Atlanta-based federal agency do not routinely report patients'
risk factors.
   Hepatitis B, a blood-borne disease, has for some time been known
to plague intravenous drug abusers, who can pass the disease
through sharing of contaminated needles.
   ``But it's only newly recognized that they are a risk group for
hepatitis A,'' Shapiro said. Hepatitis A is often transmitted in
cases of poor hygiene, through fecal contamination.
   About 25,000 cases each of hepatitis A and B were reported to
the CDC last year. Hepatitis is a serious inflammation of the
liver, causing fever and aches, which can, in rare cases, be fatal.
   Two explanations have been proposed for the new link between
hepatitis A and drug abuse, the CDC said. The illness may be spread
through use of drugs contaminated with the virus. Or the virus
might be spread in direct person-to-person contact, perhaps in
needle sharing, sexual contact or poor personal hygiene.
   ``Investigations of the various outbreaks ... have not revealed
clear modes of transmission,'' the CDC said in its weekly report.
``It is possible that each outbreak has multiple modes of
transmission.''
   In upstate New York, in addition to the Cortland County
outbreak, 87 cases of hepatitis A were reported in Monroe County
from December 1986 to May 1987; 24 patients were injectible drug
abusers, and eight more were sexual or household contacts of the
drug users, the CDC said.
   In northern California, in the wake of a food-borne hepatitis A
outbreak, 33 other patients not connected to that outbreak were
questioned; 24 of the 33 patients were abusers of injectible drugs.
   Other drug-linked outbreaks have occurred in recent years in
Alaska, Oregon, Washington state, southern California, Oklahoma and
Connecticut, the CDC said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
