<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KillerBees     05-19 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Killer Bees,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Killer Bees' Found On Ship Arriving In Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten thousand super-agressive ``killer
bees'' almost got a free ride into Florida aboard a ship, state
agriculture officials said Thursday.
   The killer bee colony, complete with queen bee, that was
destroyed earlier this month aboard a freighter at Port Everglades
was the third and by far the largest swarm of the deadly
Africanized bees that have been found on ships arriving in Florida
within the last two years, officials said.
   There was chance that the swarm could have helped establish the
killer bee problem in the United States, but the odds were against
that happening because the bees would probably have bred with their
gentler cousins, officials said.
   The nasty little bugs, descended from South African bees that
escaped from a researcher in Brazil in 1956, attack much more
agressively when riled than do ordinary honeybees.
   They have been blamed for several deaths of humans and livestock
in the areas in South and Central America where they have taken
over, and are also a threat to the commercial beekeeping industry.
Some researchers fear they could spread across the Mexican border
into Texas as early as the end of this year.
   About 10,000 bees were clustered aboard the containerized
freighter Senate, carrying fruit and vegetables from Guatemala,
when it docked May 6 near Fort Lauderdale, said state Agriculture
Commissioner Doyle Conner.
   The inspector who destroyed the swarm, John Bastianelli, was
stung more than 100 times. But it takes about 2,000 stings to kill
an average adult, said Laurence Cutts, the state's chief apiary
(beehive) inspector.
   If they had gotten ashore, Bastianelli said, the bees could have
set up a hive and begun expanding because they included a queen,
the only member of a colony that can reproduce.
   But Cutts said a single colony is not much of a threat in itself
because bees do not inbreed. A single colony would breed with
European honey bees and the Africanized strain would be reduced
with each generation until eventually it would be bred out of
existence, he said.
   ``There's always a chance'' of the bees becoming established,
said Cutts. ``Just what that chance is, we don't know.''
   Since 1986, signs have been posted at ports urging crews and
dock workers to report swarms and its now common knowledge among
seaman that authorities want to know about bee activity on ships.
Also, bee-nesting lures have be placed at major ports to attract
bees before they can move inland, officials said.
   ``They'll go to a bee box before they go anywhere else,
hopefully,'' Bustianelli said. ``Once we find out there are bees
there we can get them, although we might have to fight them a
while.''
   In late 1986, a colony of killer bees was discovered and
destroyed aboard a ship docked in West Palm Beach. Another was
removed by a hobbyist beekeeper in April 1987 from a freighter in
Panama City and later destroyed by agriculture officials.
   The Port Everglades swarm was considerably larger than the
others, Cutts said, but it was still about a fifth the size of a
normal, established colony.
   The bees also were infested with Varroa mite, a honeybee pest
detected in Wisconsin two years ago and since found in 13 other
states including Florida, Cutts said.
   Like the killer bee, the mite is considered a potential major
threat to the beekeeping industry. The mite feeds on the body fluid
of bees and pupae, eventually causing high bee mortality and
weakening of colonies.
   The discovery of mites in the Port Everglades swarm has
increased suspicion the mite infestation that began two years ago
was caused by an Africanized colony which became established
without detection, Cutts said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
