<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     05-19 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Activist Reports Mass Gathering in Yerevan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200,000 people gathered peacefully in a
square in Yerevan Thursday in the second large demonstration in the
Armenian capital this week, an Armenian activist said.
   Several assemblies were held this week in Armenia and Azerbaijan
to address ethnic unrest in the republics. Armenians want the
Nagorno-Karabakh area of neighboring Azerbaijan to become part of
their republic.
   Activist Rafael Popoyan said in a telephone interview from his
home in Yerevan that some people in the crowd Thursday carried
banners demanding annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
However, it was not clear who called Thursday's demonstration, or
what its purpose was, he said.
   There were rumors it had been organized by officials, and people
may have been attracted by curiosity, he said. But nothing happened
in the two hours after people began to gather at 6 p.m. (9 a.m.
EDT) in a square near the city opera house, he said.
   ``People were standing around; there weren't any microphones,''
Popoyan said.
   Police surrounded the square but did not interfere, he said.
   The majority of the people in Nagorno-Karabakh are Christian
Armenians, and Armenians say they are repressed by Azeris, who are
Moslems.
   Papoyan said there was a ``constant danger of an explosion'' of
rage in Nagorno-Karabakh. Armenians had been forced out of the city
of Shusha in the region by other residents, and soldiers were
surounding Nagorno-Karabakh, he said.
   Other calls to officials and activists in Armenia and Azerbaijan
did not go through.
   Armenians began protesting in mid-February for the annexation of
Nagorno-Karabakh. At the end of the month ethnic rioting broke out
in the Azerbaijan city of Sumgait. Thirty-two people, six Azeris
and 26 Armenians, were killed.
   The Soviet government rejected the demand to change jurisdiction
over Nagorno-Karabakh, opting instead for an expensive program of
social and economic development of the area.
   Popoyan and Moscow dissidents said about 150,000 people gathered
in Yerevan on Tuesday in a meeting called by the Karabakh committee
leading the effort to annex the section of Azerbaijan.
   They said the figure of 15,000 people reported earlier by other
Moscow dissidents was wrong.
   The rally was called a day after the first defendant in the
Sumgait riots was convicted of murder and sentenced to 15 years in
prison.
   Popoyan said protesters are demanding that trials of those
accused in the rioting be open and broadcast on television.
   The official Baku radio said young people, intellectuals and
workers attended ``crowded'' meetings Monday and Wednesday in
Azerbaijan.
   They called on the government and Communist Party to protect the
interests of Azeris living in Armenia, said the radio, reporting
from Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan.
   The broadcasts, monitored by the British Broadcasting Co. in
London, did not say how many people were involved.
   It said ``incidents'' took place in some residential areas of
the Ararat district of Armenia on May 11 that had worried some
Azeris. It did not elaborate.
   Popoyan said there had been reports of clashes between Azeris
and Armenians in the region, but that he did not have details.
   Baku radio said members of the Central Committee of the
Azerbaijan Communist Party and of the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet met with some of those attending the meetings and urged
restraint.
   Vladimir Ryabokon, an editor of the dissident journal
Express-Khronika, said in a telephone interview that tens of
thousands of people gathered in Baku on Monday and Tuesday to
demand that courts not give the death sentence to any of those
charged in the Sumgait riots.
</TEXT>
