<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0743 05-19 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Many Statements Made To Congress Can Be Used in
Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with more details from filings.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver L. North and former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter made damaging admissions to Congress
about the Iran-Contra affair that could be used as evidence against
them in court, prosecutors said Thursday.
   Poindexter's statement that he approved North's plan to funnel
profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels and
admissions by him and North that they destroyed documents during a
1986 investigation were among numerous excerpts of congressional
testimony that prosecutors said were admissible in court.
   Even though they testified on Capitol Hill under limited grants
of immunity from prosecution, former National Security Council aide
North, Poindexter and arms dealer Albert Hakim made statements that
can be used against them when the Iran-Contra case goes to trial in
federal court, the prosecution said.
   ``Volunteered testimony by defendants in their congressional
testimony is not immunized and may be directly introduced at trial
against them,'' independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh said in
briefs filed in U.S. District Court.
   The three defendants are accused along with retired Air Force
Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord, who gave congressional testimony
without an immunity grant, of conspiring to defraud the government
by diverting profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   The indictment includes charges that North destroyed documents
during the November 1986 Justice Department investigation of the
Iran-Contra affair that uncovered the diversion of arms-sale
profits.
   It also accuses Poindexter and North of lying to congressional
committees by denying involvement in private Contra resupply
efforts.
   Walsh offered to ``forego the use of congressional testimony''
to smooth the way for a quick trial as a way of satisfying defense
complaints that the prosecution illegally relied on immunized
statements of the defendants.
   However, Walsh cited hundreds of statements by North, Poindexter
and Hakim that were either voluntary or not responsive to the
specific question posed by the committees and therefore not covered
by the immunity grants.
   In a joint filing, defense lawyers called ``simply absurd''
Walsh's claim that the three defendants waived their privilege
against self-incrimination during the congressional hearing.
   ``Each defendant claimed his privilege at the very outset and
never relinquished it,'' the defense said. ``The court should
flatly reject the IC's (independent counsel's) attempt to
circumvent the immunity statute.''
   The defense also urged the judge to dismiss the indictment on
the ground that Walsh took insufficient steps to isolate his staff
from the defendants' immunized testimony, which ``has seeped into
every corner of this case.''
   The statements that Walsh maintains are not covered by the
immunity grants included Poindexter's assertion that the diversion
proposed by North ``was clearly a new aspect that I had not thought
about before. To make a long story short, in the end I thought it
was a very good idea ... and I personally approved it.''
   ``In my view,'' Poindexter continued, ``it was a matter of
implementation of the president's policy with regard to support for
the Contras.''
   Poindexter also admitted that he ``made a very deliberate
decision not to ask the president so that I could insulate him from
the decision and provide some future deniability for the president
if it ever leaked out.''
   The excerpts also include North's statements that he shredded
NSC documents while Justice Department officials were in the next
room during the November 1986 inquiry, prosecutors said in the
briefs.
   ``I remember shredding documents while they were in there
reading documents,'' North told the committee.
   ``Do you remember _ shredding them in their presence?'' asked
Arthur Liman, counsel for the Senate panel.
   ``I mean, they were sitting in my office and the shredder was
right outside and I walked out and shredded documents,'' North said.
   Walsh contended he could also use Poindexter's statements that
he intended to withhold information from the chairman of the House
Intelligence Committee and his belief that North was evasive and
withheld information from Congress.
   ``I testified that I have withheld information from Congress and
with regard to Cabinet officers, I didn't withhold anything from
them that they didn't want withheld from them,'' Poindexter told
the panel.
   Of North's testimony to the House Intelligence Committee,
Poindexter testified, ``I expected him to be evasive.''
   Poindexter said he was sure North's answers ``were very
carefully crafted, nuanced. The total impact, I'm sure, was one of
withholding information from the Congress.''
   Walsh, meanwhile, also asked U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell to set a trial date, arguing that defense claims that the
prosecution illegally relied on compelled congressional testimony
were meritless.
   He argued that Gesell should set a trial date and reserve
judgment on the immunity issues until later. ``A demand for any
further pre-trial hearings (by the defense) would constitute a
transparent attempt at delay,'' Walsh argued.
</TEXT>
