<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsTreaty 3rdLd-Writethru a0757 05-19 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Treaty, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0757,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative Republicans Urge Lengthy Debate Over Missile Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to MOVE UP what the INF Treaty
is and INSERTS 9 grafs after 9th graf pvs bgng, `Sen. Jesse,' to
UPDATE with introduction of Symms amendment; PICKS UP 13th graf pvs
bgng, `Sen. Pete;' Senate has adjourned for the evening so this
should stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Republicans, spurning appeals
from the Senate's GOP and Democratic leaders, urged colleagues on
Thursday to ignore the fast approaching U.S.-Soviet summit and
debate the medium-range arms reduction treaty for weeks.
   But Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said: ``It's our
president who will be in Moscow next week and he'd like to have
this treaty. I say that as Republican leader on behalf of a
Republican president.
   ``We have a special responsibility to President Ronald Reagan,''
Dole said.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty calls for the
elimination of all ground-launched missiles with a range of 300 to
3,400 miles.
   Shortly before Dole appealed to senators to bring any amendments
they may have to the Senate floor for action, Sen. Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo., told his colleagues: ``We should not be playing beat the
clock in our debate over the treaty.''
   ``We cannot feel rushed by the artificial deadline of next
week's summit,'' Wallop said. ``It should be beside the point to
meet a deadline.''
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., said: ``Let us examine this treaty
carefully and let the public relations deadline in Moscow be
damned.''
   President Reagan's summit meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev is set to open May 29.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., noting that no
amendments had been offered to the text of the treaty at that
point, asked unanimous consent to move to the resolution of
ratification.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the leading opponent of the treaty,
objected, saying amendments were being prepared by as many as four
senators.
   About an hour later, Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, introduced an
amendment that would prevent the treaty from going into effect
until the president certifies the Soviets are in compliance with
all other arms control treaties.
   He asked for separate roll call votes on all five sections of
the amendment, probably on Friday morning.
   ``The Soviets cheated in the past and I think we can expect they
are going to cheat in the future and I think each senator ought to
go on record whether he wants to condone cheating or not,'' Symms
said.
   But Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, noted that Secretary of State George P. Shultz
testified that the treaty ``stands on its own merits and should not
be linked to other arms control treaties or other issues.''
   ``It would be like cutting off our nose to spite our face,''
Pell said.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said that linking the INF treaty to
other issues ``is not in the best interest of our country.''
   ``The INF treaty is not a favor to the Soviet Union,'' he said.
``To make implementation depend on compliance with other treaties
is nonsensical.''
   ``To deny ourselves a national security option does not make
good sense,'' Lugar said. ``This treaty stands on its own merits.''
   Earlier, Wallop conceded the Senate eventually will ratify the
treaty, but he urged rejection of ``the drumbeat from the White
House and our leadership which demands our swift consent to the INF
treaty.''
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, R-N.M., raised the possibility a
filibuster may have begun and said, ``I think if we were to vote
tonight it would be a surprise if there were 10 no's. I think the
president of the United States deserves an opportunity for this
body _ before he meets in Moscow _ to say yes or no.''
   Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., told him: ``I don't think now is the
time to start harping that we have to do this by a certain
deadline.''
   Wallop added: ``For us to be hurried to suit the climate of a
summit is just a wrong urging at this moment.''
   Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., a treaty supporter, said: ``This treaty
should not be asked to bear the burden of amendments which are
nothing more than thinly veiled attempts to delay its
ratifications.''
   Evans said hardcore arms control opponents have described the
treaty unfairly.
   ``For some, the treaty apparently would result in apocalyptic
military consequences,'' he said. ``That means we have had a steady
stream of misleading, false testimony from the very military
leaders we depend upon, and I don't think that's true.''
   ``We do this treaty a disservice if we treat it as something
more or less than what it is, a single step back from the nuclear
precipice,'' Evans said. ``I think it is time to focus on what is
in front of us instead of trying to bring in all of the
non-related, non-germane elements.
   Although debate was sporadic, Sen. John Stennis, D-Miss., the
Senate's most senior member, endorsed the pact, calling it a
``small first step in the long and difficult process'' of
``reducing the likelihood of a nuclear holocaust.''
   But Humphrey denounced it, saying, ``The INF treaty is a fraud,
a dangerous fraud.''
   The Senate voted 91-6 Wednesday to reject the first conservative
attack on the treaty. That was a point of order raised by Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who claimed Gorbachev wasn't authorized to
sign the pact and it was therefore invalid.
   Byrd told reporters on Thursday: ``The first vote would indicate
the Senate did not think it was a serious point. I did not think it
was.''
</TEXT>
