<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0700 05-19 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Confirms 15,000 Soviets Died in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Pakistani official implying
aid to continue, Afghanistan filing protest; picks up 5th graf pvs,
``The withdrawal ...; SUBS last 2 grafs, ``In Washington ... with 5
grafs details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union lost up to 15,000 soldiers in
Afghanistan, a government official said Thursday as the first
contingent of Red Army troops was arriving home from the war with
Moslem guerrillas.
   Eduard Rosental, a political observer for the official Novosti
press agency, told reporters that a Western estimate of 12,000 to
15,000 Soviet deaths in the army's 8{ years in Afghanistan was
approximately correct.
   It was the first time a Soviet official gave any estimate of
Soviet losses in Afghanistan. Soviet officials have refused to
specify the death toll or even the number of Soviet troops deployed
there.
   In other developments Thursday, Pakistan's acting foreign
minister implied his country will continue to help arm the
anti-communist guerrillas, and Tass said Afghanistan's Foreign
Ministry complained to U.N. monitors that Pakistan was sending arms
to the Afghan guerrillas.
   The Soviet withdrawal began Sunday, in accordance with a
U.N.-mediated peace accord signed April 14 in Geneva. The first
1,300 Soviets to leave Afghanistan crossed the border into Soviet
Uzbekistan on Wednesday.
   Radio Moscow reported that the returning soldiers sent a message
to President Reagan urging him ``to use America's prestige and your
personal authority on behalf of this humane goal _ that of bringing
war in Afghanistan to an end and to ensure that no more bombs fall,
no more people die and no more children become invalids.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Thursday
that high-ranking Defense and Foreign ministry officials would meet
with reporters next week to discuss Afghanistan.
   Rosental was asked at a news conference how many Soviet soldiers
had died in Afghanistan.
   He reviewed various Western media assessments, including a
report by Agence France-Presse that 12,000 to 15,000 Soviets had
been killed.
   ``I think the figures cited by Agence France-Presse are more or
less correct, but you can obtain more correct figures from our
military men,'' Rosental said.
   A Soviet-inspired revolution in April 1978 brought a Marxist
leadership to power in Afghanistan. The Kremlin dispatched troops
and tanks in December 1979 to help the Kabul government fight
guerrillas.
   A State Department report released in December estimated the
number of deaths and injuries among Soviets serving in Afghanistan
since 1979 to be ``at least 33,000 to 38,000,'' with at least a
third of them fatalities.
   In addition, many soldiers died from diseases, the report said.
   If the death figures mentioned by Rosental are correct, the
Soviet Union suffered far fewer losses in Afghanistan than the
United States did during the Vietnam War, when about 50,000
Americans were killed or mortally wounded.
   Rosental rejected a reporter's suggestion that the Kremlin was
abandoning an allied government still beleaguered by a nationwide
insurgency.
   ``To withdraw troops does not mean to leave the country in the
lurch,'' he said. ``We leave many cultural and economic facilities
there.''
   The head of the Soviet contingent in Afghanistan, Lt. Gen. Boris
Gromov, told reporters in Kabul last week that more than $1 billion
in bases and equipment were to be left behind for the Afghan
government's use.
   Soviet soldiers have contended the Afghan army, estimated at
40,000 soldiers, can protect the government.
   Pakistan's acting foreign minister, Zain Noorani, returned
Thursday from a visit to Moscow.
   The official Pakistani news agency, APP, quoted him as saying
that although ``the purpose of the Pakistan mission to Moscow was
of goodwill,'' his country would abide by the Geneva accord and the
policy of ``symmetry.''
   Under that policy, the United States and Soviet Union will
continue to supply the guerrillas and Afghan government forces,
respectively, until one of the sides stops.
   ``I have been quoted as saying that Pakistan will stop all
assistance to the mujahedeen (rebels),'' Noorani said, according to
APP. ``This is incorrect ... We will fulfill all obligations that
we have taken upon (ourselves) in the Geneva accord and after (the
Soviet pullout) becomes operative on May 15, 1988.''
   Pakistan is bound by the accord to stop serving as conduit for
military supplies to the rebels, which mainly come from the United
States. Pakistan officially denies it has ever helped ship the arms.
</TEXT>
