<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Corruption     05-19 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Corruption,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crimes by Brezhnev Protege Said to Total Over $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protege of former President Leonid Brezhnev
embezzled $1.1 million in state money and used it to buy furs,
foreign cars and crystal chandeliers for himself and his family, a
newspaper said.
   The article about the late Interior Minister Nikolai Shchelkov
struck another blow at the legacy of Brezhnev, who ruled the
country for 18 years before he died in 1982. The piece by writer
and juriest Arkady Vaksberg appeared Wednesday in the weekly
Literaturnaya Gazeta.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev has branded Brezhnev's rule as
stagnant and corrupt. The newspaper article charged that Shchelkov
was one of the most corrupt people surrounding Brezhnev.
   Brezhnev's son-in-law, Yuri Churbanov, was appointed Shchelkov's
first deputy. He is now under arrest and facing trial on corruption
charges.
   Soon after taking power, Yuri Andropov fired Shchelkov.
   Shchelkov died in December 1984 at age 73 and was buried without
ceremony in a Moscow cemetery. He is thought to have committed
suicide because of an investigation of his affairs.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta said Shchelkov bought nine Mercedes cars
for the ministry but then gave vehicles to his son, daughter and
himself. Foreign cars were registered to other family members as
well, the paper said.
   He used $80,000 in state money to buy 62 crystal chandeliers for
himself, his friends and relatives, and had several apartments in
Moscow neighborhoods, the paper said.
   Shchelkov's personal staff included an architect, photographer,
biographer, cook and other personnel, it said.
   He spent $67,000 on furs in his last three years as minister and
almost $12,000 on perfume, the paper said.
   Literaturnaya Gazeta said the total loss to the state from
Shchelkov's theft was $1.1 million, but an investigation recovered
about $780,000 of that.
</TEXT>
