<HEAD>Polish Train Derailment Kills 10 Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military transport train derailed
Thursday in northwestern Poland, killing 10 soldiers and injuring
at least 16, the official PAP news agency said.
   The report said the train ``tore apart'' the station at Pila, a
city of 68,000 people about 240 miles northwest of Warsaw.
   PAP did not say how many troops were aboard or give the
destination.
   It said cause of the derailment was being investigated.
   PAP identified three of those killed as career soldiers,
indicating the other seven were draftees serving a mandatory two
years in the military.
   The agency said none of the 16 victims being treated at military
and civilian hospitals appeared to be critically hurt.
   The derailment appeared to be Poland's worst train wreck since
April 13, 1981, when 23 people were killed near Zabrze in southern
Poland.
