<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-19 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion Injures Four In French Territory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb explosion at an apartment
building occupied mainly by native Melanesians injured four people
Thursday in this French South Pacific territory, police said.
   No one claimed responsiblity for the attack in suburban
Montravel, outside the capital of Noumea.
   The explosion occurred shortly before a government-appointed
delegation from Paris was to arrive to study the situation in New
Caledonia.
   The bomb, placed on the second floor of the apartment building
before dawn, caused considerable damage.
   Melanesians, also known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of the
territory's 142,000 people. Most favor independence from France.
   The rest of the inhabitants of New Caledonia are European
settlers, Asians and Polynesians who, for the most part, wish to
remain French.
   France has governed New Caledonia, a former French penal colony,
since 1853.
   On May 2, a bomb wrecked a car belonging to a European man
working for the Kanak Socialist Liberation Front, the main
separatist group. A group calling itself the National Committee
against Independence claimed responsibility.
   The Liberation Front condemned Thursday's bombing and said ``the
more the Kanak people suffer, the more our determination will be
reinforced.''
   The French mission sent here was appointed by Premier Michel
Rocard and includes three high-ranking public servants and three
religious leaders.
   New Caledonia, 1,000 miles east of Australia, has been the scene
of sporadic violence since November 1984.
   In April and May, Melanesian separatists raided a police station
on Ouvea island, killing four gendarmes and abducting two dozen
others.
   On May 5, French security forces freed the hostages in a rescue
operation that killed 19 Melanesian militants. Twenty-nine
separatists were arrested in the incident and will be tried in
Paris.
   On Thursday, police arrested Chanel Kapoeri on Ouvea, one of the
Loyalty Islands northeast of the main island. They said he was
suspected of having led the attack at the police station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
