<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Archbishop     05-19 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Archbishop,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Prelate Asks Superpowers To Send Development Aid, Not
Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS R. VARELA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PONCE, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas of San
Salvador called on the United States and the Soviet Union Thursday
to stop intervening militarily in Central America and instead send
tools that will promote growth.
   He said nations in the region must find political solutions to
their difficulties and the problems must be tackled from within.
   ``Instead of sending weapons, the United States should send
implements for development,'' Rivera Damas said. ``But no matter
how much we shout to them not to send arms, they will keep sending
them as long as the other side (communist countries) keeps sending
them.''
   ``The problems in Central America are geopolitical,'' he said.
``In some countries the United States intervenes and in others the
socialist bloc and through them, the Soviet Union.''
   The archbishop is in Puerto Rico attending a conference on peace
in Central America. He said the Roman Catholic Church has always
supported ``non-intervention and the self-determination of our
peoples.''
   He said Central American leaders should intensify efforts to put
into effect the peace accord proposed by President Oscar Arias of
Costa Rica in August 1986 at Esquipulas, Guatemala. But he admitted
that talks between the Salvadoran government and the guerrillas
have been a ``dialogue of the deaf.''
   ``The Church thinks Esquipulas II (the agreement) is an
opportunity we should not let go by,'' he said.
   The 65-year-old church leader criticized repression by Central
American governments of political opponents, saying, ``We can't
exclude dissidents just because of their ideas.''
   He noted that ``death squads'' are still active in San Salvador,
but less so than in the past.
   More than 70,000 people have died in San Salvador in violence
since 1981, including Rivera Damas's predecessor, Monsignor Oscar
Romero.
</TEXT>
