<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0714 05-19 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Speaker Denies He Violated Ethics Rules</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Common Cause ...'' to restore
dropped first name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright on Thursday denied he
violated ethics rules and said a watchdog group's call for an
official investigation was based on ``unsubstantiated allegations.''
   But a right-wing opponent of the speaker said pressure for a
House probe was increasing.
   Common Cause, a non-profit group which promotes tougher campaign
and ethics laws, called Wednesday for the House ethics committee to
hire an independent counsel to examine two possible breaches of
conflict-of-interest rules by Wright which have been the subject of
newspaper reports.
   In one case, Wright has received far above the normal percentage
of royalties for a book he wrote. The publisher was a campaign
supporter who received more than $250,000 in business from Wright's
re-election committee in the 1985-1986 period.
   Common Cause President Fred Wertheimer said the ethics committee
needed to examine whether the speaker's campaign committees were at
all involved in publishing or selling the book, which he said could
be a violation of House or other federal conflict-of-interest rules.
   Wright on Thursday denied there was a campaign link.
   ``My campaign committee did not pay any amount for publishing
the book, nor did it purchase any copies of the book,'' he said. He
said the House rules ``clearly authorize members of Congress to
receive royalty payments of this kind.''
   Wright also denied anything improper in a second issue raised by
Common Cause, his efforts to help constituents, including some
campaign contributors, in their dealings with the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board.
   ``Nothing in the House rules prohibits a member from acting as
an ombudsman for the citizens he represents _ in fact it is
considered to be an important part of our job as representatives of
the people,'' he said.
   Conservative opponents of the speaker, led by Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., have been spotlighting reports of his personal
dealings.
   But they have not formally asked the ethics committee for an
investigation. If a member makes such a request, the ethics
committee is required to respond.
   Gingrich said Thursday his plans to submit such a complaint had
been delayed by GOP lawyers examining the case, but he hoped to
have it ready early next month.
   ``If you are going to take on the second most powerful elected
official in America, you have got to have arguments that are
ironclad,'' he said.
   The Common Cause request, Gingrich said, means the ethics
committee will face an ``overwhelming burden to at least initiate
an investigation'' when he makes his own request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
