<DOCNO> AP880519-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka-India     05-19 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka-India,0389</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior government minister announced
Thursday that Indian troops battling Tamil rebels in Sri Lanka will
withdraw from the island nation.
   ``The government is very keen to see the Indian peacekeeping
troops leave,'' the land and river development minister, Gamini
Dissanayake, told Parliament. ``They are definitely going.''
   India has more than 50,000 troops in Sri Lanka to enforce an
accord designed to end the five-year war by militant Tamils
fighting for a separate homeland.
   Dissanayake said the Indian troops would leave in a phased
pullout, but that the date for the initial withdrawal had yet to be
discussed.
   Official sources in the capital, Colombo, said the matter was
likely to be discussed this month when India's defense minister,
Krishna Chandra Pant, visits Colombo. President Junius R.
Jayewardene said Pant will visit the capital May 30.
   Pant is also likely to discuss peace proposals with Tamil
militants, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   India, this island nation's northern neighbor, has a large Tamil
population of its own and mediated the peace accord signed last
July. The accord grants some autonomy to Tamils in exchange for a
surrender of weapons, but it has been rejected by the main Tamil
guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of Eelam.
   Indian officials have been holding talks with Tamil rebel
leaders to try to persuade them to accept the accord, but Tamil
rebels say it doesn't go far enough in giving them autonomy.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population, They claim they are discriminated
against by the majority Buddhist Sinhalese.
   Many Sinhalese also have rejected the peace accord on grounds it
makes too many concessions to the Tamils. Sinhalese extremists have
threatened to kill politicians and others who support it.
   A senior police official said Thursday that Sinhalese extremists
killed a candidate of the governing United National Party in the
central Kandy district. The officer, speaking on condition of
anonymity, identified the victim as Jayaratna Heenbanda, who was
going to run in provincial council elections.
   A 19-year-old student, Aruna Saman Dissanayake, also was killed
when gunmen shot at another governing party candidate, Sella
Jayakody, at Horona town, just south of Colombo.
</TEXT>
