<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OfficerFiring     05-19 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Firing,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Black Officers Quit Union As Controversy Heats Up Over Fired
Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine black police officers have quit the
Tampa police union to protest its staunch support of a white
officer fired for making racist and sexist slurs.
   Mayor Sandy Freedman's firing last week of Officer Charles W.
Glass, who admitted making the remarks, was criticized by the
Police Benevolent Association, who said the firing was a violation
of due process.
   The association's support of Glass in turn caused nine black
officers to withdraw from the union in protest.
   R. Jeffrey Stull, an attorney for the police union, urged the
mayor to reinstate Glass, but the mayor was awaiting the return
next week of Public Safety Director Robert Smith, mayoral spokesman
John Dunn said Thursday.
   Then-acting police chief Col. George Fox reprimanded Glass last
month after Glass told police investigators he made sexually and
racially derogatory comments about Officer Vicky Thomas.
   The mayor's policy, however, calls for a punishment of at least
15 days suspension or possibly dismissal for such violations, said
Dunn. The mayor fired Glass last Friday.
   Dunn said there has been no decision on whether Fox should be
disciplined for not following the policy. Both Fox and Police Chief
Austin McLane were out of town Thursday and unavailable for comment.
   One of the nine officers who quit the union said his decision
was prompted not only by the association's backing of Glass but
union president Bob Sheehan's criticism last month of a stinging
manuscript on race relations by Hillsborough County sheriff's Maj.
Arnie Myers, who is black.
   Excerpts of the manuscript were published in The Tampa Tribune
and sparked a flood of complaint calls to the sheriff's office.
   ``The PBA is not in my best interest,'' said detective Bob
Wright, 32, a 10-year officer and union member for the past two
years who said he supported Glass' firing.
   Sheehan met with 20 black officers for three hours Wednesday. He
said the group discussed forming a minority officers' committee to
address complaints, but no action was taken.
</TEXT>
