<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CatholicEducation     05-19 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Education,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholic Schools Can Stave Off Enrollment Drop, Educator Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ninety percent of Catholic educators and
church officials surveyed believe enrollment in Catholic schools
will decrease by more than half in the next 15 years, according to
a survey released Thursday.
   Although the survey did not ask respondents why they thought
enrollment would drop, one Catholic educator suggested three
causes: fewer children being born, more parochial schools being
closed, and new schools not opening as people move around the
country.
   The educator, the Rev. Thomas Gallagher, the United States
Catholic Conference secretary for education, suggested that
Catholic education can be marketed better to draw more students.
   He urged parochial schools to return to incorporating the gospel
and academic excellence, a sense of church and community, public
service to that community, and prayer.
   The survey, sponsored by the National Catholic Educational
Association, was released as the weeklong Catholic Education
Futures Project conference got under way Thursday at the University
of Dayton.
   Gallagher said this was the first time 22 groups in Catholic
education have met to discuss religious education problems. More
than 300 people were expected to attend the conference.
   Among the findings in the survey were comments by a few
respondents that Catholic schools were becoming elitist because of
their expense and their dwindling numbers.
   ``Education will be in the hands of the rich because of the
cost,'' wrote one respondent.
   NCEA member and conference chairwoman Sister Suzanne Hall said
of the comments on elitism: ``My sense from all these folks is that
we don't want Catholic schools, Catholic education to become
elitist. I don't see it as inevitable. ...
   ``I think a lot more things need to be done on collaboration at
the parish level,'' she said.
   Gallagher said schooling traditionally has been a community
responsibility deserving of parish subsidy but that this attitude
has faded as fewer parishoners have had children to send to school.
   The report surveyed 336 people representing 18 Catholic
educational organizations, including traditional parochial schools,
youth ministries, adult religious education, Catholic universities
and seminaries. They agreed or disagreed with 50 statements about
the future of Catholic education and said whether they thought the
expected result was desirable.
   Ninety percent of the respondents predicted enrollment in
Catholic elementary and secondary schools would drop to slightly
more than 1 million by 2007, compared with 2.9 million in 1985.
More than 4,300 Catholic schools have closed since the mid-1960s.
   Among other responses to the questions, a majority felt it
unlikely that the government will provide much financial support to
church schools.
   And although most respondents felt that Catholic schools and
parishes will cooperate with one another to broaden religious
education, some felt that pastors are ``too provincial'' or that
high schools ``do not value cooperation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
