<HEAD>School Parents Launch Drive To Stop Child Preachers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede, 2nd graf to CORRECT ages of brother and sister;
picks up 3rd graf, `They stood ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOG1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old schoolyard preacher and his
sister were suspended again Thursday for violating school rules,
while angry parents circulated a petition to stop the children's
sermonizing on school grounds.
   The children, Matthew Strode and his 6-year-old sister Pepper,
returned Thursday morning to Eastfield Elementary School from their
third suspension in 18 days, arriving in a car driven by their
mother, Robin. When they refused to go into the school, they were
suspended yet again.
   They stood at an entrance, surrounded by a crowd of reporters,
TV cameras and other schoolchildren, and waited for a cue from
their 10-year-old brother, Duffey, who was outside the school gate.
   Duffey was suspended for 10 days last Friday for refusing to
stop proselytizing and go to class.
   ``For God so loved the world ...,'' Duffey called from the gate,
setting off a stream of preaching from his younger brother.
   ``Now is the day of salvation,'' Matthew cried as Pepper stood
beside him holding a Bible. ``Hell has enlarged herself and opened
her mouth without measure.''
   ``Fools make a mock at sin,'' the younger boy shouted at
Principal Jim Gorst when asked repeatedly to come inside the
school. Both children were then suspended.
   Though she stood beside her brother, Pepper does not preach
because she doesn't want to, the children's father, David, has said.
   Officials at the school, which has an enrollment of 370, call
the preaching a disruption. But the children's parents, who moved
to Marion 17 months ago from Pennsylvania, call the suspensions an
attack on their constitutional guarantees of freedom of speech and
freedom of religion.
   Gorst said parents appeared increasingly disturbed by the
preaching on school grounds, and were circulating a petition asking
the Strodes to stop it. Some had complained that their own children
were frightened by the fire-and-brimstone images conjured up by the
sermons.
   He added that the Strode children were being suspended not for
their preaching, but for remaining outside the school building when
school rules require them to be inside.
   ``If the news media was not here and if the offers for talk
shows were not present, I believe in my mind they'd be back in
school,'' he said. He said if the children would agree to come to
school Friday and discontinue preaching, the suspension would be
dropped.
   Hazel Strickland, a school parent who signed the petition, said
she did so because ``they're talking about demons (and) devils, and
(the other children) don't like it.''
   ``I'd just as soon have my young ones home safe,'' said Elaine
Harris, another parent.
   Mrs. Harris said she drove her three children to school Thursday
morning, but turned the car around and drove back when she caught
sight of reporters and two sheriff's cars at the school.
   ``I send my kids to school to get an education,'' Mrs. Harris
said. ``I take them to church on Sunday to get their education in
church. And I don't need some 11-year-old or whatever telling (my
son) he's going to die or we're going to die and all go to hell.''
   The children's father said the people who signed the petition
were ungodly.
   ``Of course that would be the reaction,'' David Strode said.
``If you're in an ungodly community, who would want preaching going
on?''
   As for the school officials, he said, ``They will have to answer
to the Lord for kicking three children out of school. ... One day,
they'll deal directly with the Lord, Jesus Christ.''
</TEXT>
