<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Party     05-19 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politburo To Meet Before Party Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tass said Thursday that the policy-making Central
Committee of the Communist Party will meet in what is likely to be
a key session before next month's important party conference.
   The official news agency said the ruling Politburo endorsed a
draft program for the conference, due to open June 28, and that it
would be submitted to the Central Committee and workers for
consideration.
   A meeting of the 300-odd Central Committee members could be held
next week in conjunction with an expected session of the Supreme
Soviet, which is likely to ratify the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning
intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   That would allow time for the largely formal nationwide
discussion of the program before the conference opens.
   Tass did not say what program for the party conference was
endorsed.
   But earlier this week a Central Committee official, Dmitri A.
Lisovolik, said the conference would take up proposals to limit the
term of the party general secretary, the post held by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   In speeches this year, Gorbachev also has said the conference
will consider reforms to strengthen the legal and judicial systems.
   He has said a full meeting of the Central Committee will be held
to discuss the question of relations among the Soviet Union's more
than 100 ethnic groups.
   Politburo membership can be changed at a Central Committee
plenum, and the conference that follows also gives Gorbachev a rare
opportunity to strengthen his support on the Central Committee.
   Gorbachev himself has called for creating a system to replace
aging party officials and has been especially critical of the
18-year rule of President Leonid I. Brezhnev as a period of
stagnation and corruption. Brezhnev died in 1982.
   Lisovolik, chief of the U.S. section of the Central Committee's
International Department, said proposals before the conference will
call for limiting the general secretary to two or three eight-year
terms.
   Reports of a serious policy dispute between Gorbachev and Yegor
K. Ligachev, the No. 2 man in the Kremlin, surfaced in Moscow last
month. Some reports said the dispute rose from the newspaper
Sovietskaya Rossiya's running an article in March questioning
whether Gorbachev's reforms had gone too far.
   Some commentators in the official Soviet press suggested that
the article was the start of an effort by conservatives to halt
Gorbachev's reforms at the party conference.
</TEXT>
