<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Threat, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0740,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Returns Indictment Over Alleged Threat To Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Williams, a construction ..., with 3 grafs to
UPDATE with comment from Mrs. Williams' attorney after meeting,
arraignment scheduled for Monday. Pickup 8th graf, `In an ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he is prejudiced ``against
anything that isn't white'' was indicted by a federal grand jury
Thursday on a charge of threatening to kill black presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson.
   Londell Williams, 30, of Washington, Mo., was named in all four
counts of the indictment. His wife, Tammy, 27, was named in three
of the counts, but she was not accused of being involved in the
threat on Jackson's life.
   The indictment said that on or about May 10 Williams ``knowingly
and willfully did threaten to kill and inflict bodily harm upon
Jesse Jackson.''
   The indictment charges both of the Williamses with possessing an
AR-15 rifle that had been altered to make it fully automatic. That
gun has been identified by the government as the weapon that was to
be used in a plot to kill Jackson.
   The pair also were charged with two counts of threatening to
harm a government informant in retaliation.
   The indictment said the Williamses used intimidation and threats
of physical harm on an informant ``with the intent to hinder, delay
and prevent the communication of information relating to the
possible commission of a federal offense.''
   Prosecutors and the couple's attorneys met for several hours
after the indictments issued Thursday but declined comment
afterward. Cynthia Short, Mrs. Williams' lawyer, would say only
that ``They (the Williamses) are scared.''
   Williams, a construction worker, faces a maximum penalty of
three years in prison and $250,000 in fines on the first count. On
each of the other three counts, the Williamses can be sentenced to
10 years in prison and fined $250,000.
   U.S. District Judge Edward L. Filippine set the Williams'
arraignment for 9:30 a.m. Monday.
   In an interview Wednesday at a federal detention center in
Belleville, Ill., across the Mississippi River from St. Louis,
Williams denied conspiring to kill Jackson and said that although
he sympathized with white supremacists, he did not belong to any
extremist group.
   ``I deny that there is a crime done,'' he said. ``I did not
conspire with anyone to kill any presidential candidate.
   ``I do have prejudices ... against anything that isn't white,''
Williams said. But he added regarding Jackson: ``If the man makes
it to president, more power to him.''
   The Williamses, who live in rural eastern Missouri with their
three daughters, have been held without bond in Belleville since
federal agents arrested them at their apartment Friday. The arrests
were announced Tuesday.
   Federal agents initially said Williams claimed he belonged to
two violent white-supremacist groups: the Covenant, the Sword and
the Arm of the Lord (CSA), and The Order.
   But Tom Den Ouden, who heads the Springfield, Mo., FBI office,
said he had found no evidence Williams or his wife belonged to The
Order or the CSA.
   Franklin County, Mo., Sheriff Paul J. Bruns said the case
stemmed from an incident earlier this month, when his department
received a call about a domestic argument in which a woman
brandished and fired into the air what appeared to be an automatic
weapon.
   An informer told investigators that Williams not only possessed
a rifle that had been converted to fire as a machine gun, but that
he was also part of a plot to kill Jackson on June 21 or July 4,
Bruns said.
   The sheriff said the informer led officers to a wooded area,
where they found the altered AR-15 assault rifle. Federal
authorities were brought into the case May 10.
   A Secret Service agent testified Tuesday that agents taped a
conversation in which Williams told the informer the Covenant
wanted the rifle back and was planning Jackson's assassination.
   According to a criminal complaint, Jackson was to be killed
because he ``was getting too close to being president of the United
States.''
   Williams said he had lived in a part of southern Missouri known
for attracting members of extremist groups. He said he knew of
former CSA leader James Ellison, who is serving a federal prison
sentence, and that he knew Richard Butler, the head of the Aryan
Nations, which spawned The Order.
   ``I have been raised the very same way a lot of them have been
raised,'' he said, ``but I'm not part of their activities and I'm
not a member of their groups.''
   Williams' mother, Mildred, of Norris, Ill., said she spoke with
her son by telephone Wednesday. She said her he told her he made up
the story about the assassination plot at a drinking party and the
informer believed it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
