<DOCNO> AP880519-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Soviet     05-19 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Soviet,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Hints Pakistan Will Continue Arming Afghan Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan's acting foreign minister,
Zain Noorani, returned Thursday from a goodwill visit to Moscow,
but indicated that this country will continue to help arm
anti-communist Afghan guerrillas.
   A leader of insurgents fighting Afghan and retreating Soviet
troops told The Associated Press his forces might concentrate on
taking a provincial capital in northern Afghanistan.
   Noorani, minister of state for foreign affairs, returned to
Karachi from a three-day visit to the Soviet Union which he was
reported as saying was ``more than satisfactory.''
   It was a notable restoration of harmony for two countries long
at opposite sides of the war in Afghanistan.
   Pakistan's official APP news agency quoted Noorani as saying
that although ``the purpose of the Pakistan mission to Moscow was
of goodwill,'' Pakistan will abide by the April Geneva accord and
the concept of ``symmetry.''
   He was referring to the agreement signed by Washington, Moscow,
Kabul and Islamabad that outlined the withdrawal of Soviet troops
from Afghanistan. The United States and Soviet Union agreed they
will keep supplying the guerrillas known as the mujahedeen and
Afghan communist forces, respectively, until one side or the other
stops.
   ``I have been quoted as saying that Pakistan will stop all
assistance to the mujahedeen. ... This is incorrect. ... We will
fulfill all obligations that we have taken upon (ourselves) in the
Geneva accord and after (the Soviet pullout) becoming operative on
May 15, 1988,'' he was quoted as saying.
   The Geneva accord covered four basic principles: the pace and
time frame of the nine-month Soviet withdrawal, the halt of foreign
interference in the Afghan conflict, the right of Afghans to
determine their own government and the safe return of some 5
million refugees from Pakistan and Iran.
   Pakistan is bound by the accord to stop serving as conduit for
mainly U.S. military supplies to the guerrillas, known as the
mujahedeen, although Pakistan officially denies it has ever done so.
   There have been confirmed reports that dozens of trucks have
crossed the loosely guarded border from Pakistan to Afghanistan
with arms and ammunition for the Moslem insurgents.
   ``It is for those who matter (the United States and the Soviet
Union) to stop the supply of arms to any individual faction of
Afghan people,'' Noorani was quoted as saying. ``This is a simple
case as the physicians can diagnose themselves.''
   Noorani's remarks indicated he reached an understanding with
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze that Soviet-Pakistani
relations should improve, although Pakistan has served as
headquarters for the guerrillas fighting Kabul's Marxist government
and the Soviet troops who have supported it since December 1979.
   The visit commemorated the 40th anniversary of Soviet-Pakistani
relations.
   Moslem Pakistan achieved statehood in 1947 when it was
partitioned from Hindu India under an agreement with the British
empire.
   As Noorani was speaking in Karachi, the chairman of the
seven-party muhjahedeen alliance said in Peshawar, Pakistan that
the insurgents would begin attacking Afghan army strongholds which
the muhahedeen felt they can take easily.
   ``We will be sure enough we can occupy and the enemy cannot
resist,'' Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, leader of the revolutionary
Hezb-I-Islami guerrilla party, told the AP.
</TEXT>
