<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Airspace,0118</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lufthansa Chief Calls for Cuts in Military Airspace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heinz Ruhnau, the chairman of the
airline Lufthansa, said Thursday that Europe's skies are
overcrowded with commercial aircraft and military airspace should
be reduced.
   He told a news conference that increases in airline traffic in
recent years have filled the skies over Europe's major cities and
stretched airport capacity to the breaking point.
   Ruhnau said the amount of airspace reserved for military
aircraft must be reduced if civil aviation authorities are to cope
with the growing demand for air traffic.
   Large portions of the sky over West Germany and other European
nations are reserved for military flights and maneuvers.
