<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic     05-19 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Ethnic,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Citizens Protest Ethnic Strife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 people from minority
ethnic groups marched Thursday to demand federal protection from
majority Albanians in a southern province, an official report said.
   The Tanjug news agency said the marchers represented about
50,000 people, mostly of Serbian and Montenegrin nationalities, who
signed a petition. They threatened ``an organized exodus'' from
Kosovo province if their efforts fail.
   According to official estimates, about 24,000 Serbs and
Montenegrins have emigrated from the province since 1981. Many
claim discrimination by ethnic Albanians who make up about 85
percent of the population in Yugoslavia's least developed region.
   In 1981, bloody riots broke out in the province, and some
Albanians called for increased autonomy for Kosovo.
   Tanjug said the petition representatives appealed in a meeting
with the president of the Parliament, Dusan Popovski, for an
``urgent undertaking of measures without which there is no peace,
survival and freedom of the Serbian and Montenegrin people in
Kosovo.''
   They said that otherwise Serbs and Montenegrins will ``organize
their own self-defense of their freedom, dignity and honor.''
   ``If we fail, we will have to resort to an organized exodus from
the province,'' Tanjug quoted the petition as saying. The agency
did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
