<2ND_LINE>AM-Malta-Libya,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Malta Gives Up Libyan Military Aid, Cleaves to West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami of the
Mediterranean island nation of Malta is forsaking Libyan military
protection and seeking closer ties with the United States, the
Italian news agency ANSA reported Thursday.
   It quoted Fenech Adami, a nationalist, as saying his government
is trying to restore good relations with foreign nations,
especially Western ones.
   In 1984, a Libyan-Maltese treaty, arranged with the Socialists
who then governed Malta, provided that Libya would come to Malta's
defense if Malta's neutrality was jeopardized. Malta lies 200 miles
north of Libya, the North African nation under the leadership of
Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
   Before Fenech Adami's party, allied to the Christian-Democrats,
came to power a year ago, Malta was governed for 16 years by
Socialists. Critics accused them of playing Libya and the United
States off each other.
   Fenech Adami's remarks came during a two-day visit to Rome this
week, the news agency reported.
   He was quoted as saying he will discuss promoting U.S.
investment on Malta during a visit with President Reagan in the
United States in July.
</TEXT>
