<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Quake,0126</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Shakes Guatemala City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook the Guatemalan
capital and surrounding areas Thursday, the Seismological Institute
said. No injuries or damage were reported.
   Guillermo Songton, an employee at the institute's monitoring
station in the southern part of Guatemala City, said the quake
measured 4.0 on the Richter scale, occurred at 4:29 p.m. (6:29 p.m.
EDT) and lasted eight seconds.
   Its epicenter was on the grounds of the University of San Carlos
of Guatemala, on the capital's southwestern edge.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph.
   A quake with a magnitude of 4 can cause moderate damage.
</TEXT>
