<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2318EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0801 05-19 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0801,0874</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Mourns Bus Crash Victims As Funerals Begin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 2, `Seven of ..., and graf 18, `A fifth ..., to
UPDATE with seven students buried; SUBS quote in 13th graf: ``Your
pain ..., to make it are, sted our, with you.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XRAD1,2 and LaserColor XRAD3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RADCLIFF, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anger and guilt but ``no satisfying
answers'' remain for the families and friends of 27 people killed
in a fiery bus crash, a priest said Thursday at the funeral for
three of the victims.
   Seven of the dead were buried Thursday, all but two at the North
Hardin Memorial Gardens graveyard that abuts the high school they
would have graduated from one day.
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson declared a day of mourning, with flags at
half-staff throughout the state.
   ``The saying is trite but painfully true: They had their whole
lives before them,'' said the Rev. Leo Craycroft during Mass at St.
Christopher Church in Radcliff for Mary Catheryn Daniels, 14;
Denise Ellen Voglund, 13, and Amy Christine Wheelock, 14.
   Twenty-four children and three adults were killed Saturday night
when a pickup truck traveling in the wrong direction on Interstate
71 struck a church bus, rupturing its fuel tank and setting it
ablaze.
   The crash occurred in Carroll County, 100 miles northeast of
this Army post town, as the bus owned by Radcliff First Assembly of
God church carried members of the church's youth group and their
guests home from a day at the Kings Island amusement park north of
Cincinnati. The driver of the truck allegedly was drunk.
   ``Why do bad things happen to good people? None of us can answer
that question,'' said the Rev. Gene Waggoner at a citywide evening
memorial service. ``And if we could, it wouldn't take away your
grief.
   ``I suggest that you do not blame anybody on that bus. I suggest
that you don't blame God; God did not cause this. There is sin in
this world ... and there are those who make wrong choices, and
innocent people pay the price.''
   Gov. Wallace Wilkinson and Maj. Gen. Thomas H. Tait, commander
of nearby Fort Knox, were among dignitaries in attendance at the
service in the football stadium of North Hardin High School.
   Bleachers in the stadium can hold 2,400 people, and chairs were
set up on the field to boost capacity to about 4,000. Rows of
people crowded around the perimeters of the field.
   Most of those in attendance broke down during the singing of
``What a Friend We Have in Jesus'' at the start of the service, and
many clasped hands and supported others during prayers.
   W. Don Tennison, pastor of the Radcliff First Assembly of God
Church, read letters from President and Nancy Reagan and Vice
President and Barbara Bush during the memorial.
   ``Your pain and loss is ours too,'' said the letter from the
Reagans. ``Your countrymen are with you in prayer.''
   After the ceremony, Wilkinson and the preachers who led the
service slowly made their way down a row of family members to
express their sympathies.
   The stadium lies at the edge of North Hardin Memorial Gardens
cemetery, where five of the victims of Saturday's crash were buried
earlier Thursday.
   The first victim to be buried was Julie Ann Earnest, 12,
following a graveside ceremony that coincided with the Mass. The
four girls attended Radcliff Middle School, and their graves are
all in the same section of North Hardin Memorial Gardens cemetery.
   A fifth middle-school pupil, eighth-grader Tina Michelle
Mustain, 14, was buried near Chandler, Texas, after a funeral in
Tyler, Texas. And eighth-grader Chad Witt, 14, was buried in
Liberty, Ky.
   Fourteen-year-old Joshua Conyers, credited with pushing his
younger brother, Aaron, through a window to safety as the bus
burned, also was buried in the cemetery adjoining North Hardin High
School, where he was a freshman.
   Conyers was from nearby Vine Grove, where his funeral was held.
His father, Larry Conyers, said survivors of the crash told him
Joshua could have escaped, but ``jerked away from the others, ran
back and crammed Aaron out a window.''
   Aaron Conyers, 13, remained in critical condition at Kosair
Children's Hospital in Louisville.
   ``There are no real satisfying answers,'' Craycroft said during
the Mass, which drew an overflow crowd to the small brick church on
a hilltop overlooking the middle school.
   ``We expect older people to die. ... Children in their prime do
not die,'' Craycroft said. ``We may feel guilty, we may feel angry,
and all of these are quite natural.''
   Speakers were set up outside St. Christopher to accommodate
mourners who could not be seated inside. The coffins were decked
with flowers and wreaths and lined end-to-end before a flower-laden
altar.
   The driver of the pickup, Larry W. Mahoney, was in the prison
unit of Humana Hospital-University of Louisville, where a
spokeswoman said Mahoney's family refused to allow release of
information about his condition. Mahoney has been charged with 27
counts of murder.
   Thirteen bus passengers besides Aaron Conyers remained
hospitalized Thursday. Six, including Aaron, were in critical
condition.
</TEXT>
