<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     05-19 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Turns Down Request To Push For Marcos' Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's leading Roman Catholic
churchman rejected an appeal Thursday by Ferdinand Marcos' wife to
ask the president to allow the ousted leader back into the
Philippines for his mother's funeral.
   Imelda Marcos said in a radio interview Friday that she and the
former president were sure to go home eventually because ``we are
on God's side.''
   Cardinal Jaime Sin, archbishop of Manila, said he received a
telegram from Mrs. Marcos ``pleading with me to voice an appeal to
the government to allow former President Marcos to return to the
country for the funeral of his mother.''
   The cardinal said he forwarded the request without comment to
President Corazon Aquino and other government officials who have
``better information.''
   Marcos' mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, died May 4 at age 95. No
date has been set for the funeral.
   Mrs. Aquino, citing national security reasons, has refused to
allow Marcos to return from exile in Hawaii. He fled there after a
popular uprising toppled his 20-year government on Feb. 25, 1986.
   Cardinal Sin was a strong opponent of the Marcos government. In
1986, he appealed to his followers to go into the streets to
protect soldiers who broke with Marcos.
   Hundreds of thousands heeded his call, triggering the uprising
known here as the ``people power revolution.''
   In her telegram, Mrs. Marcos said: ``I plead to you as the
spiritual leader of the Filipino people to voice an appeal of a
mother to allow a son, my husband, Ferdinand, to return to his
motherland and pay a final homage to his mother.''
   In a telephone interview Friday with radio station DZXL, Mrs.
Marcos said her husband was grieving over the death of his mother.
   ``The other day we thought we would have to bring him to the
hospital because of the hardship and embarrassment he is
experiencing,'' she said. ``In any part of the world, even a
convict, a criminal, would be allowed to go out on the wish of a
mother to visit her.''
   ``I am sure that I and the president will go home because we are
on God's side,'' she said.
   Marcos' supporters have staged several rallies in Manila since
Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' death to demand their leader's return. On
Wednesday, police used tear gas to break up about 5,000 Marcos
followers who were marching toward the American Embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
