<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     05-19 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Diplomats Discuss Southern Africa Peace Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top U.S. and Soviet diplomats
assigned to African affairs discussed on Wednesday progress in
negotiations toward peace in southern Africa in preparation for
superpower summit.
   Anatoly Adamishin, deputy foreign minister, and Chester Crocker,
assistant secretary of state for African affairs, met at the U.S.
Embassy to talk about efforts to end Angola's 13-year civil war and
to secure independence for South-West Africa (Namibia).
   ``This meeting was agreed on at their last meeting in London two
weeks ago,'' U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Susan Clyde told reporters
outside the mission gate.
   ``They're here to discuss the (southern African) regional issues
_ certainly the Angolan and Namibian points _ and to look at the
situation in Ethiopia and the Horn of Africa.''
   Reporters were not allowed into the embassy complex in this
Portuguese capital, and Ms. Clyde said neither Crocker nor
Adamishin would make any public statements on the meeting Wednesday.
   Both envoys were scheduled to give news conferences Thursday
before leaving to report to their governments before the Moscow
summit May 29 of President Reagan and Kremlin leader Mikhail
Gorbachev.
   Angola is a former Portuguese colony. Namibia is ruled by the
Pretoria government in defiance of a U.N. resolution.
   U.S.-brokered mediation seeking a comprehensive peace settlement
in southern Africa were stalled for years over demands by each side
that the other withdraw its forces from Angola first. Talks
progressed in recent weeks following a joint Angolan-Cuban proposal
in March for the phased withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola.
   Previously, Angola's Marxist government, the Popular Movement
for the Liberation of Angola, demanded that South Africa pull its
troops out of southern Angola and Namibia before Angola would
consider sending home the estimated 40,000-45,000 Cuban support
troops on its soil.
   South Africa, backed by the United States, initially demanded a
Cuban withdrawal first. However, it has since joined delegations
from Angola, Cuba and the United States in a May 2-3 negotiating
session in London. It also attended a second meeting with the
Angolans in Brazzaville, Congo, last week.
   The Angolans also want both South Africa and the United States
to halt all aid to the Angolan rebel movement UNITA _ the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
</TEXT>
