<HEAD>Singer James Brown Arrested After Police Chase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Carrol is cq as first name of male sergeant in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul music legend James Brown, charged last
month with trying to kill his wife, was arrested again Wednesday
after allegedly fleeing from officers responding to a call at his
home.
   Later in the day, authorities said Brown was charged with
possession of the drug PCP following tests on a substance found in
his car.
   Deputies were dispatched to Brown's Beech Island home Wednesday
afternoon after Brown's wife, Adrienne, went to a neighbor's house
and said her husband was abusing her, said Aiken County Sheriff
Carrol Heath.
   When officers arrived, Brown sped away in his car but was
overtaken about a mile and a half away, Heath said.
   Brown told officers he was late for an appointment and was
speeding to make up time, the sheriff said. A scuffle ensued, but
no injuries were reported.
   The 55-year-old singer, known to fans as the ``Godfather of
Soul,'' was charged with failure to stop for police, resisting
arrest, assault against an officer and illegal possession of a
weapon _ a revolver found in the car, Heath said.
   Heath also said 7 grams of a substance later identified as
phencyclidine, the hallucinogen PCP, was found in the car.
   Brown remained jailed Wednesday night at the Aiken County
Detention Center pending a bond hearing Thursday morning, said
Magistrate B.J. Millwood.
   On April 4 Brown was charged with assault with the intent to
murder, aggravated assault and battery after allegedly beating his
wife with a pipe. He also was charged with firing a gun into a car
while she was inside.
   The singer, who was released on bond the next day, has denied
those charges. Mrs. Brown subsequently filed for divorce.
   Mrs. Brown was arrested on April 9 in nearby Augusta, Ga., on
drug charges, which she claimed was a set-up by a friend of her
husband's.
   Brown, whose hits include ``Please, Please, Please'' and ``It's
A Man's World,'' won his second Grammy award last year for his
recording of ``Living in America.''
