<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-Soviet-Wick     05-19 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Wick,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says ``Disinformation'' Damages Soviet Interests, U.S.
Aide Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SMYTH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev appears to have
recognized that ``disinformation'' _ the planting of false stories
in the world press _ also hurts the Soviet Union, a senior U.S.
government official said Wednesday.
   Charles Z. Wick, director of the U.S. Information Agency, also
said the Soviet leader has promoted measures to establish a freer
flow of information between the United States and the Soviet Union.
   ``I believe that Mr. Gorbachev has recognized that
disinformation is also contrary to Soviet interests,'' Wick told a
meeting of the Council on Foreign Relations, a policy study
foundation.
   He said that during the U.S.-Soviet summit last December,
Gorbachev ``agreed that disinformation was counterproductive to his
efforts to reduce tensions, eliminate misunderstandings and create
greater trust between the U.S. and the Soviet Union.''
   Wick said that for several years, the Soviets ``planted stories
in the Third World media, and spread them throughout the world,
that U.S. military scientists had created the AIDS virus as a
biological warfare weapon.''
   But Wick said that during Gorbachev's visit to Washington last
December, Gorbachev ``agreed that disinformation was
counterproductive to his efforts to reduce tensions.''
   Wick said that later, ``following a confrontation between
Gorbachev and (U.S. Secretary of State George) Shultz, the Soviets
admitted they had erred when they claimed AIDS to be a creation of
U.S. germ warfare research. Yet they continued sporadically to
spread the AIDS disinformation story. ''
   After a Soviet-American meeting in Washington April 20-22 to
discuss media relations, Wick said ``promises were made that this
disinformation would now cease.''
   ``Already we have seen _ perhaps _ the first fruits of our
discussions on disinformation,'' Wick said. He said future Soviet
actions would determine how sincere the Soviet undertakings are.
   In a later interview Wednesday with editors and reporters of The
Associated Press, Wick cited other Soviet moves to improve
U.S.-Soviet contacts. He said these included a Soviet agreement to
allow the Voice of America, the USIA's radio network, to cover the
Moscow summit this month.
   He added that ``it also looks like'' Voice of America will be
allowed to open a bureau in Moscow. ``Amerika,'' USIA's
Russian-language magazine, may be allowed to increase its
circulation from 14,000 to 100,000 copies.
   Wick said Soviet citizens will also be able to purchase American
books by mail order at a permanent American book display in Moscow.
   In Moscow, the weekly Moscow News reported Wednesday that
officials have lifted restrictions on the sale of American and West
European newspapers and magazines, which will be sold at ordinary
newsstands in the future.
   Wick also said that Soviet officials promised this month to stop
interfering with U.S. domestic radio broadcasting ``through Cuban
transmissions.''
   Three U.S. stations operating on the frequency of 1,040
kilohertz complained last year that English-language Soviet
broadcasts from Cuba were interfering with their operations.
</TEXT>
