<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0967,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philippine Defense Secretary Says Relations With US Improving</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 8 grafs after 6th graf bgng, `Ramos has declined,' to
UPDATE with comments about Philippines nuclear weapons ban, more
money for the US bases in his country, Marcos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said
Wednesday U.S.-Philippines relations are on an upswing.
   ``I am confident our relations will continue to be strong and
will be reinforced in the future,'' Ramos said after meetings with
Secretary of State George Shultz and Michael Armacost,
undersecretary of state for political affairs.
   Earlier, he held extensive talks with Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci, his official host, and met with members of congressional
committees on Asian and military affairs.
   The meetings ``were very fruitful ... in terms of expediting
delivery of military equipment and joint projects'' under U.S. aid
programs, Ramos said.
   Progress also was made on plans for restoring the monument at
Corregidor, the site of a historic struggle against the Japanese
invasion of the Philippines in World War II, he said. U.S.
veterans' organization are to provide some of the financing for the
project.
   Ramos has declined to comment on talks in Manila on the future
of American military installations in the islands, saying the
matter is being handled at another level. But he said other
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations recognize
the security value of the bases to the region.
   However, he spoke Wednesday about his country's nuclear weapons
ban that could threaten the future of U.S. bases in the islands.
That ban is outranked by the ``higher interest'' of national
security, he said in a television interview on Cable News Network.
   Those who have sponsored a bill in the Philippines Senate that
would enforce the ban against U.S. ships ``do not really represent
all of the security opinions in the Philippines,'' he said.
   The Philippines constitution contains a clause banning nuclear
weapons but ``it is also equally true that in the same constitution
that this ban should be consistent with our national interests,''
Ramos said. ``While there is a nuclear-free interest, there is to
my mind a higher interest which is the national security interest,
so the door is not completely closed....''
   ``After all, this is just a bill that still has to be passed by
the House of Representatives and go through the complete
legislative process,'' he continued. ``It's not yet the law ...
it's not yet the closed door.''
   The United States has said enforcement of the ban would be
incompatible with American policy of refusal to confirm or deny the
presence of atomic weapons on particular vessels.
   Ramos said the Philippines request for higher payments for U.S.
use of military bases in the Philippines is not a matter of ``just
plain dollars and cents,'' but of the value of the installations to
the security of Southeast Asia and the South China Sea.
   ``If we are to be full partners there must be a better
balance,'' he said. ``The Philippines is very concerned about being
dragged into the global responsibilities of the United States, and
it is on the basis of this recognition of each other's roles that
the bases review is now being conducted.''
   The secretary said he agrees with President Corazon Aquino's
policy of preventing her deposed predecessor, Ferdinand Marcos, now
in Hawaii, from returning to the Philippines. ``I was part of the
Cabinet Crisis Committee that recommended this step and, in fact,
the cabinet as a whole unanimously recommended'' Marcos' exclusion,
he said.
   Ramos was scheduled Thursday to address the Council on Foreign
Relations and meet with media executives in New York City, and he
said was looking forward to a class reunion Friday at his alma
mater, the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y.
   Ramos also planned stops in Fort Bragg, N.C., Atlanta and Los
Angeles, San Diego and San Francisco in California before leaving
for Manila on May 26.
</TEXT>
