<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Bush-Education Adv22   05-19 1190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bush-Education, Adv 22,1219</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 22, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush Wants to Be `Education President' But Offers Few Specifics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everywhere he goes, Vice President George Bush
talks about wanting to be ``the education president,'' singling it
out as one area he would emphasize more than President Reagan.
   But the Republican nominee-in-waiting has offered few specifics
on how he would carry out that mission, apart from proposing a new
tax break for college savings accounts and promising to support the
Head Start program for disadvantaged children.
   At a recent campaign stop in Indiana, pressed to explain how a
Bush administration would handle education differently, the vice
president said he would bring outstanding school teachers to
Washington for recognition ceremonies. He also called for
restoration of ``the four R's: reading, 'riting, 'rithemetic and
respect.''
   But those are precisely the kinds of bully pulpit efforts that
Reagan and his secretary of education, William J. Bennett, have
specialized in. School recognition programs are already a regular
Rose Garden feature, blossoming in the Reagan years even while the
president sought to slash the education budget.
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, whom Bush identifies as
one his education advisers, said in an interview, ``I think he's
not yet spelled out his views in a number of areas and I'm looking
forward to his doing that.''
   The former governor, who launched a 10-point program in
Tennessee that included a controversial, ground-breaking
career-ladder plan for teachers, said he expects Bush will ``put
education right up there with peace and prosperity as a concern of
his administration. .... If he carries through with that for eight
years, he will have a massive effect on how Americans value and
view education.''
   Alexander said the next president should look ``for ways to help
communities make schools better, including helping to pay the
bill.''
   Bush told Republican activists at a fund-raiser in Fort Wayne,
Ind., last month, ``I don't want to have the federal government
come in and tell the superintendents in these schools, `Here's your
curriculum. Here are the A, B's and C's and you got to follow it.'
... But I do want to see the federal government used to put more
emphasis on excellence.''
   Pressed to spell out what he meant, Bush said: ``I want to build
on education, add to the concept of an education president. Because
as I look at our ability, and some would say inability, to compete,
the answer is education. ... It's not going to be a radical
philosophical change; it's going to be a question of emphasis.''
   ``It won't be turning my back on a record that I have identified
with,'' he added.
   Bush recently visited Garfield High School in the barrio of East
Los Angeles, where scores of Hispanic students have won honors in
calculus under the tutelage of prize-winning teacher Jaime
Escalante. A new movie, ``Stand and Deliver,'' celebrates
Escalante's success story.
   When one of Escalante's pupils asked the vice president if money
would be available to help them attend college, Bush replied, ``I
think the federal government has a responsibility _ there will be a
change of priorities to some degree'' under his administration.
   But Bush added, ``The problem is there is always going to be a
limitation in what the federal government can do. In this country,
if you can afford to pay for a kid's education, you should do it.''
   In Vandalia, Ohio, when a Butler High School student asked how
Bush would help public schools in financial trouble, he replied:
   ``The federal government should not create increased funding for
the public schools. That's not the function of the federal
government the way I see it,'' he said.
   Bush, a product of prep schools and Yale, supports tuition tax
credits for private-school parents, but has not made clear whether
he would seek, as Reagan did, vouchers that poor parents could
spend on public or private education.
   He told the students in Vandalia, ``I like the idea of trying to
get as much competition going between the schools as possible. ...
I wouldn't want to do anything to weaken the public school system,
although I think we should have the challenge and diversity that
we've got in the way of private schools and parochial schools.''
   Elsewhere, Bush has said the federal government pays 7 percent
of schools' bills and ``that's about right.''
   The National Education Association, which tracks school finance,
contends the federal share of public elementary and secondary
expenditures has dropped during the Reagan administration from 9.2
percent to 6.2 percent.
   Bush has said, ``I love the concept of Head Start,'' the $1.2
billion preschool program for disadvantaged children.
   Although Head Start was included in the 1982 Reagan ``safety
net,'' it serves only 445,000 children, or 16 percent of those
eligible, according to the Children's Defense Fund.
   The government's biggest school aid program, the $4.5 billion
Chapter 1 remedial program for the disadvantaged, reaches nearly 5
million children, but still only half those who need it.
   Reagan twice sought to cut the Department of Education budget by
$5 billion. The only increases he proposed were in election years:
1984 and 1988. In his first term, Reagan sought deep cuts in
Chapter 1 as well as aid for teaching the handicapped, bilingual
education and help for college students. Congress, nevertheless,
has boosted the education budget to more than $21 billion from less
than $15 billion.
   Bush also speaks frequently about his desire to ``strengthen
student aid for those that need it,'' including loans for college,
Pell Grants and the college work-study program.
   But he will have to reconcile those intentions with another
promise: his plan to seek a modified four-year freeze on the
federal budget, with the exception of Social Security, that would
allow spending to rise no more than 4 percent a year.
   Education accounts for only a tiny portion of the
trillion-dollar federal budget, but most school programs fall into
the category of discretionary spending where the pressure from a
freeze would be greatest.
   Bush says with disdain that, ``The liberals, Dukakis and
Jackson, their answer is, `Hey, if you really believe in education,
double the spending' ... I'm going to be saying, `Great. How are
you going to pay for it and why is it better to have it dictated
from Washington?'''
   Bush's wife, Barbara, has been a longtime activist in the fight
against adult illiteracy, and he frequently tells audiences that 13
percent of America's 17-year-olds are functionally illiterate. Bush
often extols public-private sector partnerships as a tool in the
fight against illiteracy.
   Bush says he is also getting education advice from David
Packard, the Hewlett-Packard Co. founder who headed a federal panel
that called two years ago for more federal support for university
researh.
   After a recent tour of coal research facilities at West Virginia
University in Morgantown, Bush said: ``The people working in
research institutions around this nation ... pushing back the
frontiers of human understanding will have more of an impact on the
21st century than all of us down in Washington, D.C.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday May 22</NOTE>
