<HEAD>Multifoods Says Bregman Partners Ending Acquisition Plans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs The company... with 2 new grafs detail on
standstill agreement. Picks up 3rd graf, It was...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bregman Partners of Canada has terminated its
consideration of the possible acquisition of certain International
Multifoods Corp. business units, International Multifoods said
Thursday.
   The company said it had received a letter from Bregman Partners
ending its consideration, and that the letter effectively
terminated a standstill agreement between International Multifoods
and the group.
   Bregman Partners had agreed not to purchase additional
International Multifoods shares during talks between the two.
   It was not immediately clear whether Bregman Partners' letter
was an indication the group was renewing its consideration of an
acquisition of the entire company. Company spokespeople could not
immediately be reached for further comment.
   International Multifoods stock fell 12{ cents to $26.12{ a share
on the New York Stock Exchange. The letter was disclosed after the
market closed.
   Bregman Partners, which consists mainly of the Bregman baking
family of Toronto and Belzberg banking family of Vancouver, said
last year it might seek control of International Multifoods, an
international food manufacturer and distributor.
   The company said it would oppose any takeover by Bregman
Partners, and in October filed suit alleging that the partnership
had illegally caused speculation in its stock and filed misleading
government disclosure statements.
   Bregman Partners disclosed in a Securities and Exchange
Commission filing in December that it held 10.7 percent of
International Multifoods' outstanding common stock. Earlier, it had
sought federal government clearance to raise its stake to as high
as 25 percent.
   The filing said the partnership had held discussions with
Multifoods' financial adviser about the ``possibility of entering
into negotiations'' to buy certain assets of the company. But ``no
negotiations were held and no agreement or understanding was
reached'' during the discussions, the filing said.
</TEXT>
