<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction of single-family homes dipped in
April, the government has reported, providing evidence that higher
mortgage interest rates may be dampening building activity.
   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that single-family
home building dropped 6.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 1.10 million units last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent in
April from year-earlier levels while total domestic production
registered a 2.7 percent decline, a trade association said.
   The American Petroleum Institute reported Wednesday in its
Monthly Statistical Report that U.S. imports of crude oil and
petroleum products averaged 7.04 million 42-gallon barrels daily in
April, up from 5.77 million barrels daily in April 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has refunded
$55.9 billion to taxpayers this year, about one-eighth of the
personal income taxes that were collected in advance in 1987.
   The IRS said Wednesday that 65.1 million couples and
individuals, or 80.4 percent of the returns that have been
processed so far this year, qualified for refunds. The refunds
averaged $860.
   The total number of refunds was up slightly, from 64.8 million
last year. The amount refunded declined, from $56.1 billion, as did
the average, from $866.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's chief economic adviser
predicts there will be a loss of more than 600,000 jobs if Congress
increases the minimum wage from the current $3.35 to $4.65 an hour
over three years.
   Beryl W. Sprinkel, chairman of the president's Council of
Economic Advisers, said in a letter released Wednesday to Rep.
Thomas E. Petri, R-Wis., that job losses ``would be concentrated
among younger, less skilled and minority workers.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. steelmakers are prepared to file a wave
of unfair trade suits against foreign competitors if the U.S.
voluntary import quota plan is not extended, according to the
leader of the domestic industry.
   ``The American steel industry ... will not stand idly by and
watch ... import abuses which threw our companies into a five-year
bath of red ink,'' Thomas C. Graham, chairman of the American Iron
and Steel Institute, said Wednesday.
   Voluntary restraint agreements negotiated by the Reagan
administration with 31 foreign nations are due to expire in
September 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Few youngsters are likely to answer ``actuary''
to the question of what they want to be when they grow up, but a
new book rates it as the best job of all.
   Typical children's choices like doctor and astronaut ran far
behind less glamorous professions such as computer programmers,
statisticians and parole officers in ``The Jobs Rated Almanac,''
published by American References Inc. of Chicago.
   Actuaries _ who interpret statistics to determine expected
personal losses _emerged No. 1 overall, as determined by the
almanac's criteria, which includes salary, stress, work
environment, and job security.
</TEXT>
