<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     05-19 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rate Concerns Depress Stocks, Single-Family Housing Construction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Concerns about rising interest rates are depressing the stock
market and the single-family home segment of the construction
market, analysts say.
   On Wall Street, stock prices slumped Wednesday for the second
consecutive session, sending one widely-watched market indicator to
a three-month low.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 35.32 to 1,951.09,
the lowest level since it closed at 1,914.46 on Feb. 9. Broader
market measures also tumbled.
   Bond prices fell broadly, pushing interest rates higher. The
yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond, regarded as an indicator of
interest rate speculation, rose to 9.29 percent from 9.21 percent
late Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said single-family home building dropped
6.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.10 million
units last month.
   Construction of multi-family units, which swing widely from
month to month, soared by 23.3 percent to a rate of 466,000 units.
   Overall, housing construction rose 0.5 percent in April to a
seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 1.56 million units, following
gains of 2.3 percent in March and 9.9 percent in February, the
report stated.
   But housing activity was still 4.5 percent below last year.
   Economists said the increase in apartment building probably was
an aberration and rising mortgage interest rates likely would
depress single-family construction.
   ``The single-family number is not a bad number, but I think it's
an indication that as rates rise through the year, it's going to
impact the housing market,'' said Martin A. Regalia, chief
economist of the National Council of Savings Institutions.
   Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages were just under 10
percent through March, but began edging up in April and averaged
10.4 percent last week.
   Housing permits, considered a good sign of future construction
activity, fell 4.1 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 1.42 million units. Single-family permits fell 6.8 percent,
while multi-family units rose 2.2 percent.
   In other economic news Wednesday:
   _President Reagan's chief economic adviser, Beryl Sprinkel, said
there will be a loss of more than 600,000 jobs if Congress
increases the minimum wage from the current $3.35 to $4.65 an hour
over three years. Sprinkel said in a letter to Rep. Thomas E.
Petri, R-Wis., that the job losses ``would be concentrated among
younger, less skilled and minority workers.''
   _U.S. imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent in April from
year-earlier levels while total domestic production declined 2.7
percent, the American Petroleum Institute reported. The trade group
said that unlike previous months, the latest domestic production
figure did not include a year-to-year increase in Alaskan output to
partially offset a decline in the lower 48 states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
