<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-19 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip On Weekly Domestic Data</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have slipped in the wake of
an industry report showing buildups of crude and heating oil
inventories, and weaker-than-expected demand for gasoline, analysts
say.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark U.S. crude, fell 33 cents to settle at $17.43 per
barrel Wednesday.
   Among June contracts for refined products, wholesale prices for
unleaded gasoline fell 0.51 cent to 52.23 cents per gallon, while
heating oil fell 0.71 cent to 47.07 cents per gallon.
   The declines followed Tuesday night's release of a report on the
status of domestic production and supplies for the week ended
Friday by the Washington-based American Petroleum Institute.
   Andrew Lebow, senior broker and analyst at E.D.&F. Man
International Futures Inc., said the report's indication that
stocks of heating oil were up by more than 3 million barrels, and
crude stocks were up by 1.6 million barrels were negative for the
market.
   Increased supplies amid stable or shrinking demand put downward
pressure on prices.
   Lebow also said an assessment of gasoline production and
imports, together with changes in inventories over the last four
weeks, indicated a 5.7 percent decline in gasoline consumption,
compared with the same period last year.
   ``That flies in the face of all the talk about booming demand,''
he said. ``We haven't seen that pre-Memorial Day surge in demand
for gasoline yet.''
</TEXT>
