<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan-Bass Bjt   05-19 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan-Bass, Bjt,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Stock Jumps Above Buyout Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street has propelled Macmillan Inc. common
stock above the $64-a-share price suggested in a $1.5 billion
buyout proposal from a group led by Texas investor Robert M. Bass,
indicating invsetors expect a higher bid is expected.
   Macmillan chairman Edward P. Evans, meanwhile, told the
company's shareholders at their annual meeting Wednesday that the
publishing and information services concern isn't for sale.
   Securities analysts speculated the Bass proposal could attract
others, possibly foreign companies, to become involved, touching
off a bidding war.
   Macmillan stock soared $18.25 a share to close at $68.87{ on the
New York Stock Exchange after trading as high as $71.62{ earlier in
the day.
   Some analysts have speculated the company could sell for as much
as $85 to $90 a share in a bidding contest.
   Bert Boksen, a publishing analyst for Raymond James & Associates
in St. Petersburg, Fla., estimated Macmillan could command a price
of $90 a share or more based on prices paid for other publishing
companies in recent months.
   Wayne Johnson, who follows Macmillan for H.G. Wellington & Co.
in New York, said he doubted the Bass group expected to be able to
buy Macmillan for $64 a share. ``I suspect it was a manuever to
encourage others to buy at a higher price,'' he said.
   The Bass group owns about 2.4 million Macmillan shares, or about
9.1 percent of the company's 26 million common shares outstanding.
   The analysts said foreign-based buyers, benefitting from the
decline in the dollar that has boosted their own buying power, have
shown an avid interest in U.S. publishing companies.
   French media giant Hachette SA recently agreed to buy Grolier
Inc., and Pearson PLC of Britain agreed to buy Addison-Wesley &
Sons Inc. Last year, Harper & Row was acquired by Australia's News
Corp.
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. underwent a costly
recapitalization last year to fend off a takeover bid by British
publisher Robert Maxwell.
   Boksen said the Bass group's proposal could force Macmillan to
find a friendly buyer or to propose a restructuring or a leveraged
buyout under which the company would be taken private.
   Bass, who heads Robert M. Bass Group Inc. in Fort Worth, Texas,
made the proposal in a letter to Evans on the eve of Macmillan's
annual meeting.
   As the meeting convened Wednesday morning, Evans said he had
received the inquiry, but Macmillan's board had not had a chance to
discuss it.
   He said management was confident about Macmillan's growth
potential, and added: ``This is why the company is not for sale.''
   The meeting was adjourned before shareholders could ask any
questions.
   Bass said the offer was conditioned upon approval by the
Macmillan board, sufficient financing being obtained and Macmillan
not issuing any additional equity securities.
   A proposal to authorize issuance of new preferred stock was on
the agenda for Macmillan's annual meeting, and the company said
shareholders approved it.
   Macmillan, based in New York, publishes textbooks aimed at
elementary through college grades as well as books of general
interest. It is a leader in children's books and the fast-growing
computer book field.
   Other businesses include instructional services, such as Berlitz
language training, and retail operations through its Gump's
department stores.
   Macmillan had an after-tax profit of $70.7 million on revenue of
$955.8 million in 1987.
   Publishing accounted for about 45.9 percent of revenue and 41.4
percent of operating income in 1987. Information services accounted
for 23.9 percent of revenue and 40.1 percent of income.
</TEXT>
