<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0219EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   05-19 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Denounces Bank Of NY Questioning Of Proxy Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. has denounced as ``totally
without merit'' hostile suitor Bank of New York's questioning of
preliminary results of a heated proxy battle that indicated Irving
retained control of its board of directors.
   Bank of New York claimed Wednesday that the preliminary count
Irving released earlier this week excluded at least 650,000 shares
that holders attempted to vote in favor of Bank of New York's
nominees.
   It also claimed the holders of a preferred stock issue it is
attempting to have invalidated provided a 318,000-share block
favoring Irving.
   The stock was issued three months ago to 15 private investors as
a defensive measure against the Bank of New York. Each share
guarantees voting rights beyond those of common shareholders.
   ``If we got the 650,000 shares counted for us ... and the
preferred stock not permitted to be counted ... I believe that
might be sufficient to swing the election in our favor,'' Bank of
New York spokesman Owen Brady said.
   Brady said the company had not formally challenged the proxy
count, but simply was announcing its belief that the contest still
was in doubt.
   Irving attorney Robert Falise called the complaints ``totally
without merit'' and said the company was confident the final tally
would jive with preliminary results.
   Irving said its shareholders at the May 6 annual meeting
re-elected the incumbent directors, by 52 percent to 48 percent,
over Bank of New York's slate of 16 nominees. Final results were
expected to be released at a reconvened shareholders' meeting on
May 24.
   Re-election of Irving's board would constitute a vote of
confidence in the company's defensive restructuring plan and
friendly merger with the state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA,
Italy's second-largest bank, and rejection of against Bank of New
York's hostile buyout offer.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Irving
closed up 12.5 cents to $61.50 Wednesday while Bank of New York
fell 75 cents to $30.37{.
   Bank of New York, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's common shares outstanding. The offer is valued at around
$64 a share or $1.1 billion.
   Bank of New York said it would be willing to raise the stock
portion of its bid to 1.675 Bank of New York shares, adding $3.20
per share to the deal pushing its value to around $1.2 billion.
   The offer would be amended only if Irving agrees to a negotiated
merger.
   Bank of New York said if Irving refused to negotiate, it would
buy the Irving shares tendered as of May 24 and operate the bank as
a subsidiary for five years, thereby avoiding the poison pill.
   Bank of New York said it owned or had been tendered about 50
percent of Irving's 18.5 million outstanding common shares.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $75 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent, valued at $707 million. In addition,
it said it would pay shareholders interest on the purchase price
from May 31 until the deal closes.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes asset sales, cost-cutting measures and a
$10-a-share special cash dividend. Irving said the offer has a
blended value of between $65.20 and $72.55 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Steel     05-19 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Steelmakers Demand Negotiation, Threaten Litigation Over
Import Quotas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Failure to renew U.S. steel import quotas may
trigger a wave of trade litigation by American companies against
foreign competitors, including Canada, the head of the main
domestic industry trade group says.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. steelmakers said Wednesday the recovery that
trade protection helped made possible in their industry may have
peaked for the time being.
   ``The American steel industry, so hard at work to make itself
internationally competitive, will not stand idly by and watch that
work undone by a repeat of the import abuses which threw our
companies into a five-year bath of red ink,'' said Thomas C.
Graham, whose election to a rare third term as American Iron and
Steel Institute chairman was announced Wednesday.
   Voluntary restraint agreements negotiated by the Reagan
adminisration with 31 foreign steelmaking nations expire in
September 1989. The five-year quota plan was instituted partly to
end a barrage of steelmaker lawsuits, many of them aimed at the
government-subsidized mills of Europe.
   ``If a VRA extension is deemed unecessary by those in
government, then we're prepared to flood the (International Trade
Commission) with trade case filings, if need be, in numbers which
will make what came before the VRAs seem trivial by comparison,''
Graham said in a speech at the AISI's annual conference.
   ``We do not want protection from efficient competition, nor do
we need it,'' he said. ``We need and expect only a climate of fair
trade and legal trading practices.''
   Earlier Wednesday in a panel discussion, Graham said Canada, the
United States' largest trading partner and the largest steel
exporter not covered by the voluntary quotas, is vulnerable to a
trade suit.
   The AISI, to which Canadian mills belong, wants Canada included
if the quotas are extended.
   Canada boosted its share of the U.S. steel market from what
Graham said is its fair share of 2.4 percent to 3.7 percent in
1987. The increase disadvantages Europe, Japan and other quota
nations, he said.
   John D. Allan, chairman of the Canadian steelmaker Stelco Inc.,
said in a speech Monday in Toronto that U.S. steel exports have
surged from 4.5 percent and 4.8 percent of the Canadian market in
1985 and 1986 respectively to 5.5 percent last year. Allan also
said Canadian steel is fairly traded.
   Separately, other industry leaders said steel's recovery may
have peaked if, as they fear, customers soon stop building
inventories.
   ``We're forecasting a decrease in the production rates in the
automobile, appliance and private housing sectors. So we don't see
any driving forces for a continuation of the demand we're seeing
today,'' said Armco Inc. Chairman Robert E. Boni.
   Boni said 1988 shipments probably would tail off to 75.5 million
tons, roughly even with the 76 million tons shipped in 1987 and
considerably shy of the 80 million tons talked about earlier this
year, the second year of the industry's long-awaited recovery.
   The shipping rate bears directly on profits and employment.
   ``The reduction of 5 million tons obviously ... is going to
reduce profits,'' Boni said without offering specific figures.
   But officials said they doubted such a slowdown sales would
force any plants to close.
   ``The most difficult thing for us to call in this equation is
customer inventory'' because no accurate surveys are available,
said LTV Steel Co. President David Hoag.
   ``We know the customers built a lot of inventory last year. We
feel certain they built some in the first half of this year and at
some point they will discontinue building those inventories,'' he
said. ``I think that will begin to occur sometime in the second
half.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CompanyBegs     05-19 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Company Begs,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oilfield Equipment Maker Wants Your Spare Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the going got tough, one oil patch company
turned to the newspaper classifieds for help.
   ``Please send MONEY. Manufacturing Corporation needs cash to
keep 50 people in jobs,'' said the Houston Chronicle ad placed by
Federal Flange & Fitting Co.
   ``I had hoped I would never have to (place such an ad),''
company president Tom Lyons said Wednesday. ``I'm not good at
begging, but I think it has come to be just that.''
   The ad, which appeared Tuesday, said contributors would not
receive stock or securities, but merely a thank you from the
company. The ad included a post office box where contributions
could be sent.
   By early Wednesday afternoon, about 150 people had called the
Houston company since the ad appeared, most asking for the
company's address, Lyons said.
   ``They just indicated they would be putting something in the
mail,'' Lyons said.
   Federal Flange, which produces pipe flanges used in oil fields,
suffered severely in the energy downturn. The company slashed its
workforce from 160 employees to about 50, including three of Lyon's
12 children and two of his nephews, he said.
   Annual revenue has plunged to about $3.5 million from about $15
million in the early 1980s.
   Lyons said the small ad also will appear in the Chronicle's
sports section Sunday. He said the newspaper had delayed printing
it by a few days to make sure there was nothing wrong in printing
it.
   Lyons said he has been thinking about placing such an ad for
months, but finally decided to do so after hearing about a Dallas
radio announcer who asked for money and got it.
   KVIL-FM announcer Ron Chapman asked listeners to send in $20
without telling them why, and the station received $243,120 in four
days. It later gave the money to charity.
   But Lyons said Federal Flange's need for money was no joke. He
needs it to pay overdue bills and help keep him from having to file
for bankruptcy.
   ``I find people in the United States are very, very generous,''
he said. ``I have a lot of confidence in the generosity of people.''
   Lyons, who has been battling Hodgkin's disease for two years,
said he also prays for his company's survival _ not money _ during
mass.
   ``I don't believe in praying for money,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
