<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BritishStocks     05-19 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Recover From Lows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices recovered by midday Thursday in
London after opening broadly lower in a response to earlier
declines in Tokyo and in New York on Wednesday.
   Traders said the market was steadying after its early jitters,
helped in part by neutral British economic news reported late in
the morning.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 14.8
points, or 0.8 percent, at 1,762.8 at about 12:15 p.m. local time.
The index had been down as much as 24.3 points earlier in the
session.
   Volume was 280.0 million shares, up from 255.3 million shares at
midday Wednesday.
   Earlier in the session, the market withstood a barrage of
economic reports which traders said appeared to paint a neutral
picture of the U.K. economy.
   A provisional 0.9 percent rise in the money supply was
considered equal to or better than market expectations. Industrial
production and earnings data also suggested the economy wasn't
overheating. Unemployment, which dropped to 8.8 percent in April
from 9 percent in March, was lower than expected.
   ``People aren't really worried about inflation'' as they were
earlier in the week following the U.S. March trade figures, said a
London trader. ``What we're waiting for is Wall Street.''
   Another weak start to the New York market could unnerve London
traders. Several said the Dow Jones industrial average's drop of
more than 35 points on Wednesday left Wall Street vulnerable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
