<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AmfacBuyout     05-19 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Amfac Buyout,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amfac Management Proposes Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amfac Inc. management, led by the president of
the San Francisco-based conglomorate, has proposed an all-cash
buyout for the purchase of the company at a value of $41 per share.
   ``The company stated that it has been advised that management
has been discussing financing for the buyout with a leading
financial institution and is confident that such financing can be
obtained,'' the company said in a statement issued on Wednesday at
a special board of directors' meeting.
   However, the statement added that ``there is as yet no firm
commitment.''
   The buyout would be led by Amfac President and Chief Executive
Officer Richard L. Griffith, 57.
   The proposed buyout is ``strongly supported by operating
management,'' said Griffith.
   He said it ``strengthens our ability to develop Amfac's Hawaii
asset base in a paced and profitable manner in concert with the
state's economic needs and long-term growth goals.''
   The plan is ``subject to obtaining the financing as well as a
number of other conditions,'' including approval of the board, the
company statement said.
   Meantime, the board decided not to proceed with the sale of the
Fred Harvey Resort operations and a 50 percent joint venture
interest in its Hawaii land and agricultural operations. The
company had received an offer of $166 million for Fred Harvey.
   Amfac is a diversified services company with main lines of
business in food processing, hotels and resorts, retail,
agriculture and property.
   Revenues in 1987 were $2.2 billion.
</TEXT>
