<DOCNO> AP880519-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BeefPrices     05-19 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Beef Prices,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beef Prices Increase In Latest Survey, NCA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average price of beef rose 12 cents a pound
over a month ago, the Denver-based National Cattlemen's Association
said Wednesday.
   The average price in its May 12 survey of prices in 19 cities
nationwide was $2.82 per pound, up from $2.70 in the survey on
April 14.
   Seasonal increases in demand _ especially for steak _ helped
trigger the higher costs for consumer beef, the association said.
   Sirloin, for example, was $3.62 per pound, up from $3.30 a month
ago, while round steak was up from $2.47 to $2.52. T-Bone steak
averages rose from $4.62 to $4.89.
   Ground beef prices also rose from $1.40 in April to $1.42 in
May, while chuck roast, the only category to come in lower in May,
dropped from $1.74 to $1.68. The NCA said demand for roasts
generally drops during summer months.
   The five-cut average, which also was above the average of $2.71
of May 1987, rose in 14 cities and was down in five.
   The five-cut average ranged from a low of $2.42 in Des Moines to
a high of $3.41 in both Baltimore and Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
