<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ChinaEurobonds     05-19 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China Eurobonds,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moody's Rates China Eurobonds Single-A-3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moody's Investors Service Inc. has assigned a
single-A-3 rating to 300 million West German marks of Eurobonds
issued by China and due in 1992, Moody's Japanese subsidiary said.
   Moody's Japan K.K. said in a statement Wednesday that it was the
first time a bond issued by China had been rated by a U.S.
credit-rating agency. The single-A-3 rating indicates that the
Eurobond issue is a safe investment.
   Moody's rates bonds in 27 categories from single-C-3, the
highest investment risk, to triple-A-1, the lowest risk.
   The Moody's statement said the rating was ``based on China's
current low level of debt, the expectation that future borrowing
will remain within a comfortable range relative to the nation's
debt-servicing capacity, and the progress made in stabilizing
Chinese politics since the death of Chairman Mao Zedong in 1976.''
   Moody's said China's foreign debt is low by international
standards, totaling an estimated $27 billion at the end of last
year. That represents 9.3 percent of China's gross national product
and 75 percent of its current foreign-exchange receipts, the
statement said.
   ``China has adopted a conservative policy toward reliance on
foreign debt and ... this policy is likely to continue,'' the
statement said.
   However, it said, ``the scope and the nature of the changes
underway are unprecedented, with major policy contradictions yet to
be resolved.''
   ``Discontent has emerged, primarily because of the dramatic
shifts in the control of resources and in the distribution of
benefits, but also because progress on political liberalization has
been slow,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
