<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Auto-US     05-19 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Auto-US,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan to End Voluntary Auto Export Limits to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan plans to end its voluntary limit of
automobile exports to the United States effective next April,
according to a news report disputed by the government.
   Kyodo News Service reported Thursday that the government plans
to end the limits. However, officials of the automobile department
of the Ministry of International Trade and Industry told The
Associated Press Thursday night they had not discussed the matter
yet.
   Kyodo quoted unidentified MITI sources as saying ministry
officials believe there is no possibility that automobile exports
to the United States will become an issue again because the high
value of the yen makes Japanese exports more expensive.
   Also, Japanese car makers now have production plants in the
United States. Major Japanese producers, led by the Toyota Motor
Corp., also are concentrating now on exporting deluxe cars to the
Untied States that compete with South Korean exports, it said.
   Japan began limiting its auto exports to the U.S. market in
fiscal 1981 under strong pressure from Washington and the slumping
American auto industry. The limit first was set at 1.68 million
vehicles, but was raised to 1.86 million in fiscal 1984.
   The United States stopped asking for the restraints in 1985, but
Japan voluntarily continued limiting car shipments to the U.S.
market to the 2.3 million vehicles exported there in fiscal 1985.
   Japan auto exports in fiscal 1987 were 2.21 million _ below the
limit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
