<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GeneralMills-Sales     05-19 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-General Mills-Sales,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Mills Selling Talbots, Eddie Bauer Subsidiaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. said it will sell its
Talbots women's clothing chain and its Eddie Bauer outdoor apparel
unit, the only remaining subsidiaries not related to food products,
for $585 million.
   The food giant said Wednesday that Jusco Co. of Tokyo will
purchase Talbots for $325 million, and Spiegel Inc. will pay $260
million for Eddie Bauer. Both are cash transactions.
   Proceeds from the sales will result in an after-tax profit of
more than $200 million, or a minimum $2.35 a share, said General
Mills Chairman and Chief Executive Officer H.B. Atwater Jr.
   Much of the remaining $400 million will be used to repurchase
stock in the coming months, Atwater said. General Mills has 84.3
million common shares outstanding.
   General Mills announced in January that it was considering
selling the two retail units, the only remaining subsidiaries not
related to food processing or food marketing.
   Talbots, based in Hingham, Mass., sells classic women's apparel
and accessories in 126 stores in 26 states. Its annual revenue,
including catalog sales, exceeds $340 million, which represented
about 6 percent of General Mills' total revenue.
   Jusco, one of Japan's largest retailers with annual sales of
about $7.6 billion, plans to continue to operate Talbots with its
existing employees, management and headquarters.
   Jusco has had a business relationship with General Mills since
1982, when the two companies formed a joint venture to develop and
operate Red Lobster restaurants in Japan.
   Eddie Bauer, a specialty retailer that sells sportswear, gifts
and outdoor equipment through catalogs and 58 retail stores in 14
states and in Canada, has annual sales of about $255 million.
   John J. Shea, president and chief executive officer of the
Chicago-based Spiegel, said Eddie Bauer will continue to be based
in Seattle.
   He called the acquisition ``a very significant step in Spiegel's
growth plans.''
   Spiegel markets women's and men's apparel, home furnishings and
other general merchandise through catalogs and had revenue of more
than $1 billion in 1987.
   ``Eddie Bauer's customer base for both its retail and catalog
operations is composed principally of men in upper income
households, whereas Spiegel caters primarily to upper income
women,'' Shea said.
   Both transactions are expected to be completed within six weeks,
General Mills said.
</TEXT>
