<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Sharply Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures bounded sharply higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as a rally fueled by dry
growing conditions continued.
   Within minutes of the opening bell, some new-crop soybean
contracts surpassed $8 a bushel and wheat futures traded above
$3.50 a bushel.
   The latest forecasts for weekend weather in the Midwest were
divided, with some meteorologists calling for widespread rain and
others predicting only scattered showers.
   The National Weather Service predicted normal precipitation in
the northern United States and dry conditions in the South for the
first half of next week.
   Analysts said speculative activity in the grain markets has
increased markedly in the past two weeks as prices have hit new
contract highs almost daily.
   ``We're getting phone calls from people who have never been
involved with this stuff before looking to get in,'' said Walter
Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   In early trading, wheat was 13{ cents to 16} cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $3.37 a bushel; corn was 7
cents to 8{ cents higher with May at $2.16{ a bushel; oats were 3\
cents to 5\ cents higher with May at $1.66{ a bushel; soybeans were
18 cents to 22 cents higher with May at $7.78{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were sharply lower and pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .32 cent to .75 cent lower with June at 73.50
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to 1.10 cents lower with
May at 80.65 cents a pound; hogs were .17 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with June at 53.40 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.50 cent lower to .13 cent higher with May at 53.50 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday while pork
futures were mixed.
 
</TEXT>
