<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AndersenDismissal     05-19 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Andersen Dismissal,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arthur Andersen Consulting Chief Dismissed, Journal Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Arthur Andersen & Co.'s domestic
consulting operation has been dismissed for allegedly planning to
leave Andersen and take the operation with him, according to a
newspaper report.
   The Wall Street Journal, in today's editions, said Gresham
Brebach, the head of domestic consulting who is also a partner in
Andersen, confirmed he had been relieved of his duties but denied
that he was trying to take away Andersen's consulting business.
   Andersen had no immediate comment on the Journal article, said
Michele Bondy, a spokeswoman for the accounting firm.
   Andersen, based in Chicago, is one of the ``Big Eight''
accounting firms, which are the nation's largest and best known.
Its domestic consulting business is the largest in the United
States, according to the Journal.
   Brebach acknowledged that many of Andersen's consulting partners
have a major disagreement with top management ``over the strategic
direction and philosophical approach'' of the firm, the newspaper
said.
   Revenues from consulting operations are generally growing at a
faster pace than fees from auditing and tax accounting, according
to the Journal.
   Brebach told the paper his dismissal probably resulted from a
meeting he called of 11 other Andersen consulting partners in New
York two weeks ago to discuss opposition to a proposed amendment in
the firm's bylaws. The amendment would have required a departing
partner to wait a full year before soliciting Andersen clients or
trying to hire other Andersen partners.
</TEXT>
