<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ProxyFights Adv23   05-19 1103</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Proxy Fights, Adv 23,1135</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Proxy Fights _ The Latest In Takeover Strategies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate takeover artists are waging their own
political campaigns this election year. They call them proxy
contests.
   Rather than merely throwing money at shareholders to buy their
way into companies, raiders are exerting new pressure on their
targets by trying to infiltrate the boardroom.
   Convinced they can do more with a company's assets than
incumbent management, outsiders are asking shareholders to cast
their lots with them by voting in a new regime. Often without track
records of their own, raiders promise shareholders handsome returns
in exchange for their support of a rival slate of board candidates.
   The process is not for the faint of heart or purse. Experts
estimate it can cost up to $10 million to wage a full-blown proxy
battle, replete with newspaper ads, mass mailings and phone
solicitations.
   While that's a steep price tag for a fight that usually favors
management, it's sometimes worth the expense. By testing the hinges
on the palace gates, some proxy warriors have stirred entrenched
managers to make big changes and raise the value of their stock to
the delight of common shareholders.
   Corporate gunslingers have had few dead shots with the proxy
weapon, but their aim is getting better. In recent weeks,
managements at Gillette Co. and Irving Bank Corp. came perilously
close to losing control of their boards in heated proxy contests.
   Even more revealing, a study of 60 proxy fights between 1978 and
1985 conducted by the University of Rochester found that, in many
cases, top managers eventually resigned even after beating back
challenges from outside.
   A challenger's typical tactics include painting a ``broad-brush
picture of managerial inefficiency, using a variety of
easy-to-convey criticisms such as poor operating profits or an
allegedly inadequate dividend payout,'' said Harry DeAngelo, a
professor at the University of Rochester who co-authored the study.
   Until recently, proxy contests were not waged against corporate
heavyweights. Experts say the new wave is a result of corporate
defensive maneuvers like poison pills and state laws that make
unwanted takeovers cumbersome.
   Poison pills and new legislation ``have become significant
deterrents to the purchasing of a major stake in a company,''
DeAngelo said.
   Aggressors believe their allies, if elected, can work to rescind
poison pills that may be in place and can help push for a deal.
   The proxy battles that ensue are ``a form of pressure on
companies ... an amplification of takeover strategy,'' said
attorney Todd Lang, chairman of the American Bar Association's
committee on proxy fights and tender offers.
   He noted that until recently, raiders used proxy battles ``as a
way to obtain control of a whole company without paying for it ...
but now we're finding a lot of these contests are connected with
tender offers.''
   California investor Burt Sugarman sought seats for himself and
two allies on the board of Media General Inc. in conjunction with
his $1.8 billion tender offer for the communications company.
Sugarman's bid was complicated by two classes of stock, one of
which put control of the company in the hands of the Bryan family,
owners of 70 percent of Media General's more powerful Class B
shares.
   Management's main advantage in these fights is financial.
Because they control the pursestrings, corporate chieftains can
spend a lot of money to make their own case.
   ``They have all the corporte resources at their disposal _ and
that's shareholder money _ to do as many mailings as they want,
which is tremendously expensive,'' said James Heard, executive
director of United Shareholders Association, a shareholder rights
organization headed by T. Boone Pickens Jr.
   Management also has a better idea who the major shareholders are
and can court them quickly.
   Some experts estimate as much as 50 percent of a corporation's
stock is held in street name, or the name of a broker or another
nominee instead of the customer who will vote the shares.
   Proxy solicitors hired by outsiders spend countless hours trying
to trace shareholders through a confusing web of surface
organizations.
   Institutional shareholders, who control a major portion of
corporate America, often are more inclined to side with management
because of possible reprisals. ``They know if they don't, they will
be punished,'' DeAngelo said.
   In Gillette's case, for example, institutional investors were
believed to hold as much as 65 percent of the 115 million
oustanding shares.
   One source involved in a recent, high-profile proxy battle noted
that ``management has a lot more political strings to pull than the
people from outside who have to persuade stockholders.''
   Difficult to document but nonetheless pervasive are management
threats and behind-the-scenes arm-twisting. One source said
management puts pressure on institutions with which it has business
relationships, sometimes threatening to sever those ties if
dissatisfied with their vote.
   ``That's a tremendous advantage and it's very unfair,'' the
source said.
   Winning or losing is not so easy to judge in these affairs,
however. Joel Reed, chief financial officer of Desert Partners
L.P., notes that it all depends on how success is measured.
   Desert Partners, which has had an outstanding tender offer for
USG Corp., had sought six seats on the company's board. Although
the results of the vote won't be available for some time, Reed
noted that Desert Partners made its point even if USG's directors
are re-elected.
   ``Anytime a board is facing an election contest, management
becomes increasingly concerned about how shareholders view the job
they are doing,'' he said. ``In the case of USG, I question whether
management would have ever proposed the recapitalization plan that
they did ... were it not for the battle for our slate of
candidates.''
   Reed was referring to USG's plan to spend about $2.2 billion to
pay shareholders a one-time dividend that includes cash, stock and
notes for each common share.
   Despite the expense and emotional wear-and-tear of a proxy
battle, some say raiders merely are hoping to cash out at a higher
price. Reed bristled at that suggestion, noting that ``our
objective is to acquire the company.''
   ``You do see success in terms of what I think is a increased
accountability to stockholders on the part of incumbent management
and the board,'' Reed said.
   Despite the advantage management might have, Reed said the proxy
process is a good one.
   ``I would hate to see any barriers to free elections of
directors. I think the free-election process has tremendous
motivation for incumbent management and boards to be responsive to
the wishes of their constituents.''
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
