<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Proxy-Management Adv23   05-19 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Proxy-Management, Adv 23,0346</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Management Suffers Even If It Wins In Proxy Contests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Proxy Fights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winning a proxy contest is no job guarantee for
current managers.
   According to an analysis of 60 proxy contests, management
resignations typically follow a proxy battle even when outsiders
fail to win seats on a company's board of directors, according to
two researchers at the University of Rochester.
   Professors Harry and Linda DeAngelo, who studied the contests
between 1978 and 1985, noted that about two-thirds of the time, top
managers resigned within three years of a proxy fight, with the
majority of the changes coming within one year.
   That includes managers who lost their jobs when disssident
shareholders won control of their companies, which happened about
30 percent of the time.
   Perhaps even more significant, the two found that only about 20
percent of the companies they studied remained publicly held
corporations run by the same management teams three years after the
proxy contests.
   Harry DeAngelo pointed to two examples:
   _Samuel B. Casey, president and chief executive officer of
Pullman Inc., resigned in November 1978 even though dissident
shareholders were defeated in a proxy fight. Two years later, the
company was acquired by Wheelabrator-Frye Inc.
   _In the case of Management Assistance, a group of dissident
shareholders backed by Asher Edelman won four out of 10 board seats
in an April 1984 proxy fight. Four months later, the company's
president and chief executive officer Raymond Kurshan resigned.
Within a year, the company was liquidated.
   The DeAngelos say their findings raise serious questions about
claims that proxy contests are an inefficient way to discipline
managers of publicly held corporations.
   In many cases of management resignations, the new manager is
designed to accommodate the dissidents' interest, Harry DeAngelo
said.
   ``These findings suggest that, independent of its immediate
outcome, a proxy challenge does pose a serious threat to managerial
tenure,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
