<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Proxy-Solicitors Adv23   05-19 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Proxy-Solicitors, Adv 23,0518</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Proxy Solicitors Thrive in New Environment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Proxy Fights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The more proxy contests, and the grizzlier, the
more business booms for proxy solicitors.
   Solicitors are responsible for the gritty legwork in a proxy
battle. They track down shareholders and talk to them, draft
letters and write newspaper ads, send out mailings, tally votes,
and serve as general hand-holders to whichever side they happen to
represent.
   ``They've got it down to a science,'' one observer remarked.
   The Carter Organization, one of the largest solicitors with 1987
fee income of more than $22 million, has had a hand in several
major proxy fights recently.
   Donald Carter, the group's president, said the cost of a proxy
battle can range anywhere from $1 million to $10 million.
   Because a large precentage of any company's stock is held by
institutional investors or in street names _ names other than the
actual shareholder _ simply identifying just who owns the
outstanding shares is a job for a first-rate sleuth.
   At Georgeson & Co., the nation's oldest proxy solicitor,
managing director John Wilcox said he relies on a database that has
been built up over time linking individuals and their securities
holdings.
   Once shareholders are identified, solicitors have to convince
them to vote in a particular direction. Carter estimates his people
talk by phone with 2 million shareholders a year in an attempt to
influence voting.
   Some firms have even been known to hire actors to use Southern
accents in an attempt to sway shareholders in Southern states,
observers say.
   Carter said new technology allowing shareholders to vote by
phone has ``added a new dimension'' to solicitation. ``When we get
finished speaking with a shareholder, we give them a toll-free
number and ask them to call immediately if they agree with us,'' he
said.
   ``Within five minutes, we know if they're telling the truth that
they're going to vote with us.''
   If the shareholder doesn't call in with a vote, Carter's people
are back on the phone.
   Newspaper ads are also crucial to the proxy process, but they
are not directed toward the individual shareholder. Rather, they
are aimed at the investment community _ both large institutional
investors as well as brokers who may be asked for advice from
individual clients.
   Joel Reed, chief financial officer of Desert Partners L.P., said
solicitors are ``totally key to the entire process. They help
identify and contact shareholders, they give you their prognosis of
how the vote is stacking up and they make sure proxies are properly
executed so they don't get thrown out on a technicality.''
   Desert Partners sought seats on the board of USG Corp. in a
recent proxy contest. The partnership also launched a tender offer
for USG shares.
   As for the latest wave of proxy battles that has come to center
on large corporations, ``business is the busiest ever'' for
solicitors, Wilcox said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
