<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-19 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the London Stock Exchange fell Thursday
as the market was pressured by a slump on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down 17
points, or 1 percent, at 1,760.6. Volume was a moderate 438.1
million shares, compared with Wednesday's 536.1 million shares.
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as much as 25
points in the last hour of London trading, disappointing many
London players. Several dealers said rumors of large stock sales in
New York by Japanese investors also did not bode well for the
London market.
   A large computer-generated trading program involving disposal of
several stocks late in the London afternoon also contributed to the
pressure, some traders said.
   ``I would say it's more a case of lethargy than outright
pessimism,'' said one equity salesman, adding that ``unless we get
some more bids and corporate activity, we won't have anything to
keep the market alive.''
   A battery of U.K. economic indicators released earlier Thursday
were digested by the market without causing much of a stir, dealers
said.
   A provisional rise in the money supply of 0.9 percent in April
was equal to or better than market expectations. March industrial
production rose 1.2 percent and the annual rate of increase in
average earnings remained unchanged at 8.5 percent in March,
suggesting the British economy was not immediately overheating.
Unemployment, which dropped to 8.8 percent in April from 9 percent
in March, was lower than expected.
</TEXT>
