<HEAD>Dollar Trades in Narrow Range, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded in a narrow range Thursday
in quiet European trading amid uncertainty about currency's
direction. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said dollar trading was dull because of
a lack of conviction among market players on where the U.S.
currency is headed in the short-term.
   Dealers were also uncertain whether this week's U.S. trade
figures, which revealed the trade deficit fell to $9.75 billion in
March from $13.8 billion in February, were an aberration or the
beginning of a trend.
   In London, the British pound finished mixed. It was quoted at
$1.8665 late Thursday, more expensive for buyers than $1.8605 late
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Wednesday's prices,
included: 1.6990 West German marks, down from 1.7055; 1.4155 Swiss
francs, down from 1.4215; 5.7542 French francs, down from 5.7700;
1.9042 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9090; 1,262.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,265.50; and 1.2442 Canadian dollars, up from 1.24125.
   Earlier, the dollar fell 0.73 yen to a closing 124.80 yen in
Tokyo, in what traders said was a correction following sharp gains
on the back of the trade report. In London, the dollar was quoted
at 124.87 yen.
   Gold prices rose in active European trading.
   In London, the metal was quoted at a late bid price of $456.90 a
troy ounce, up from $453.70 late Wednesday.
   Dealers said a rush to buy soybeans by commodity dealers in
Chicago helped boost gold prices. Higher prices for the beans
following dry weather in the U.S. plains threaten to cause an
increase in food prices and inflation and thus make gold _ a
favorite hedge against inflation _ more desirable.
   In Zurich, the bid price for gold was $458, up from $454 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.02 to close at a bid $457.56.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid $6.72 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $6.58.
</TEXT>
