<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WorldEconomy Bjt   05-19 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Economy, Bjt,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Europe Set Aside Differences On Farm Trade Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference of leading industrial nations ended
Thursday after the United States failed to persuade European
governments to accept its proposal for ending public aid to farmers
by the year 2000.
   However, trade and finance ministers from the 24 members of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development said they
would work together to reform global farm trading rules.
   The European countries held out against U.S. efforts to set a
timetable for phasing out subsidies designed to prop up farm prices
and boost exports.
   These efforts already are under way, with little apparent
progress, in the 96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
a Geneva-based body that sets and monitors world trade rules.
   U.S. officials said they would have preferred a more specific
commitment to press ahead with farm policy reforms, but that
differences with the Europeans were not insurmountable.
   ``We're basically on the same wave length,'' said Clayton
Yeutter, the U.S. special trade representative.
   ``What we achieved in this meeting is a recognition of the fact
that ... we've got to begin to develop the specifics of the
negotiating outlines,'' he added.
   Officials from other countries took a more modest view of the
meeting's outcome.
   Kjell-Olof Feldt, Swedish finance minister and chairman of the
meeting, told reporters the Americans wanted a commitment to start
reforming farm trade rules in 1989, while ``others believed it
should be a gradual process.''
   ``I wouldn't dare to say this has been resolved,'' he said.
   Willy De Clercq, the top trade official of the European Economic
Community, told reporters the EEC, or Common Market, would never
accept the U.S. idea of eliminating all farm subsidies.
   ``For us it is a question of reduction (of subsidies), not
phasing out,'' he said.
   The United States and the EEC both spend about $25 billion a
year on farm subsidies. They agree that this aid has become too
burdensome, but they disagree over how to correct the problem.
   Bill Hayden, the Austrialian foreign minister, told reporters he
was pleased the Paris meeting had avoided an open clash over what
he called apparently irreconcilable differences between U.S. and
European officials.
   De Clercq made a similar assessment.
   ``The main thing was to avoid a needless ... clash which would
have been a counterproductive signal,'' De Clercq said.
   The Paris communique said the GATT negotiations in Geneva should
achieve solid progress in all areas _ including rules for trading
in services such as banking _ by December, when a review conference
will be held.
   ``As they enter their more difficult phase, it is vital to
ensure the momentum of these ambitious negotiations,'' the joint
declaration said.
   The trade and finance ministers, in a broad review of the state
of the world economy, said economic growth was much stronger than
had been expected in the immediate aftermath of last October's
stock market crash.
   They said world trade was growing robustly, inflation was
holding at a low level, global trade imbalances were improving and
international cooperation on economic issues was growing.
   The ministers added, however, that problems remain, including
protectionism, or actions by governments to protect domestic
industries from foreign competition.
   The statement said the top priority for the United States should
be to further reduce its federal budget deficit.
   Japan was praised for its efforts to increase imports and
stimulate domestic consumer demand.
   Europe was urged to increase the flexibility of its labor and
financial markets and to reform its agricultural policies.
   The ministers also agreed the current approach to easing the
debt burdens of poorer nations should be continued. They said each
debtor's situation should be considered individually rather than
applying an across-the-board formula for financial relief.
</TEXT>
