<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MediaGeneral     05-19 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Directors Urged To Reject Proposal to Divide Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. executives will urge the
board of directors to reject a proposal that would split the
company, giving California industrialist Burt Sugarman more than
one-fourth interest in the firm's broadcast operations, according
to a published report Thursday.
   Lawyer Nicholas Chimicles of Haverford, Pa. proposed the
restructuring in a May 5 letter. Chimicles represents Harvey M.
Jasper of New York and Sarah Shields of Florida, who claim in a
federal court lawsuit that Media General officers and directors
breached their fiduciary duty to stockholders by rejecting
Sugarman's $61.50-per-share offer to buy all of the company's stock.
   Sugarman has since increased the offer to $70 per share, or
about $2 billion. He also is waging a proxy fight to have himself
and two associates elected to Media General's board of directors at
Friday's annual meeting.
   The takeover proposal will not be voted on at the meeting.
   James S. Evans, president and chief executive officer of Media
General, told the Richmond News-Leader ``management intends to
recommend against pursuing'' Chimicles' proposal.
   ``We are not recommending any form of recapitalization at this
time,'' he added.
   Chimicles said in his letter his proposal would be better than a
clear victory by either side in court. He said a Sugarman defeat
would result in a decline in Media General stock.
   A Sugarman victory would benefit shareholders, Chimicles said,
``but perhaps not the the degree available'' under his plan.
   The lawyer said he retained a Philadelphia investment banking
company, Howard, Lawson & Co., to formulate a plan that would boost
stockholder value in Media General, divide the company into two
units, give Sugarman ``a fair return on his investment'' and enable
members of the D. Tennant Bryan family to retain control of the
company's newsprint and newspaper businesses, which include the
News-Leader and the Richmond Times-Dispatch.
   Sugarman and his associates own 10.1 percent of Media General
Class A stock, an investment of more than $111 million.
   Bryan family members own 70 percent of the company's Class B
stock which, in effect, controls the company, and about 12 percent
of the publicly traded Class A stock.
   Chimicles said Media General's cable franchises in Fairfax
County and Fredericksburg, three commercial television stations in
the Southeast and a broadcast services operation are valued at
about $580.5 million.
   Under the plan, Sugarman would be given 27 percent of the new
company, based on his Media General investment. Each Media General
stockholder would receive one share in the new company for each
Media General share held. Under that structure, the broadcast
company would be capitalized with more than 34.9 million shares of
common stock, valued at about $16.50 each.
   Chimicles said the new company would be operated under a
one-share, one-vote principle.
   The company less its broadcast properties would be operated as
Media General is now, with Class B stock closely held and
controlling the firm, and Class A stock publicly traded but with
less voting power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TandyLaptops     05-19 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tandy Laptops,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tandy Phasing Out Model 200 Laptop Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tandy Corp. is phasing out its Radio Shack Model
200 laptop computer, a mainstay for journalists, and expects to run
out of inventories by around the end of the year, the company said
Thursday.
   The Model 200, which has a flip-up, flat-panel screen, has been
reduced to a clearance price of $499, down from $799. That makes it
the same price as the Model 102, which has a smaller, built-in
screen and will remain in production.
   The Model 200 enjoyed its greatest market penetration in the
newspaper business, where reporters used it to write stories while
away from the office, said Ed Juge, director of market planning for
Fort Worth, Texas-based Tandy.
   Juge said the Model 200 was squeezed from the bottom by the
Model 102 and from the top by the Model 1400, a $1,499 computer
introduced last August that has more memory and runs
industry-standard MS-DOS software.
</TEXT>
