<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChinaGuns     05-19 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China Guns,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Company to Manufacture Guns in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California gun manufacturer will make
semiautomatic carbines similar to the Israeli Uzi in China under a
contract described as the first such agreement with a communist
country, the company announced Thursday.
   Weaver Arms Corp. of San Diego will sell the first shipments of
its 9mm Nighthawk carbines in the United States, and plans to sell
the guns to American police agencies, private citizens and Third
World military, said Robert Weaver, company president.
   The initial production agreement, which the company said was
approved by the State Department, prohibits sale of the guns to
China, but the company hopes eventually to open that market, Weaver
said.
   The State Department's public affairs office did not immediately
respond to a request for confirmation that it was the first time an
American gun company had been allowed to make weapons in China.
   One arms industry analyst downplayed the value of such a weapon
to the military or police, saying there are plenty of other
semiautomatic weapons available to them.
   Semiautomatics fire once each time the trigger is pulled. It is
legal for civilians to own semiautomatic weapons in this country,
but fully automatic guns are illegal.
   The principal value of the deal would be to give Weaver a cheap
product for sale to American collectors and others who value guns
that look like the short-barreled Uzis they see on television, said
the analyst, Gregory Fetter of Forecast International, the Newtown,
Conn., publisher of World Weapons Week.
   ``Everybody wants to walk around being macho these days,''
Fetter said. ``The gun-loving public wants something that makes
them look like a special forces trooper yet is legal.''
   Weaver signed an agreement with the Chinese government at a
ceremony May 14 in Beijing, and expects to begin production in 90
days, with the first shipment of 10,000 guns planned by January
1989.
   ``We're very excited,'' Weaver said. ``It's an agreement that's
never been accomplished before between a Western arms company and a
communist country.''
   Weaver refused to divulge the value of the contract or the
location of the factory in China, saying the Chinese insisted on
secrecy for the time being.
   The guns are expected to sell for $525 retail. The Uzi goes for
$698 in this country, and the other similar gun, the German HK94,
retails for $800, Weaver said.
   The publicly held company also has designed a 9mm pistol and an
ultralight submachine gun, but neither is yet in production, Weaver
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
