<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0353</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices eroded today in moderate trading,
extending a two-day slide that brokers have blamed on rising fear
of inflation and higher interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which hit the
lowest point in more than three months on Wednesday, was down as
much as 25 points this morning although it rebounded to 1,950.27 as
of 3 p.m. EDT, down 0.82. Broader market indices weakened.
   Despite a rash of good economic news, the stock market has
instead focused on rising yields in the bond market, a barometer of
inflation and interest rates.
   With 30-year Treasury bonds yielding about 9.3 percent, the
highest since the October stock crash, many investors are finding
bonds more attractive.
   ``The market today is continuing the selloff that's been in
progress for the last couple of days, primarily in reaction to the
fact that the bond market is providing some very meaningful
competition in attracting money,'' said Jonathan Groveman, head of
equity trading at Ladenburg, Thalmann & Co.
   ``The stock market is trying to go down to a level where it can
attract some buyers relative to the bond market,'' he said.
   Losing issues outnumbered gains by about 3-to-2 on the NYSE,
with 905 down, 553 up and 485 unchanged. Big Board volume totaled
141.86 million shares with an hour of trading left.
   Union Carbide, a component of the Dow average, was among the
most-active NYSE issues, down { to 18\. The company announced plans
Wednesday to cut its dividend and issue more stock.
   Amfac jumped 6} to 45[ after the diversified company's
management announced a plan to buy the company for $41 a share.
   Among the blue chips, IBM rose 1{ to 110], Texaco fell | to 49\,
General Electric rose | to 40, Merck rose 1\ to 149| and Boeing
fell ~ to 48|.
   The NYSE composite index of all listed issues fell 0.03 to
142.48. On the American Stock Exchange, the market-value index fell
1.40 to 291.39.
