<HEAD>Wheat Futures Up Sharply As Grains, Soybeans Advance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures closed sharply higher Thursday on
the Chicago Board of Trade and contracts for future delivery of
other grains and soybeans also extended their weather-related
advance.
   With the winter wheat crop in need of a good soaking to finish
off its critical heading stage before harvest, wheat traders are
worried that a continuing run of dry weather could do enough damage
to significantly decrease yields, analysts said.
   Weekend weather forecasts were mixed and the National Weather
Service called for normal to below-normal rainfall across the
country for the first half of next week.
   Corn and soybean prices also ran up sharply early in the day but
retreated on profit taking after contracts for May delivery expired
at noon. But wheat prices remained firm through the close.
   ``I think the wheat market is beginning to take on a life of its
own,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co. ``It hasn't really been in an uptrend
like corn and soybeans and there's some concern about the condition
of the crop in Kansas and Nebraska.
   At the close, wheat was 8{ cents to 11} cents higher with July
at $3.42{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with July
at $2.17{ a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 3{ cents higher with July
at $1.72\ a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents lower to 2} cents higher
with July at $7.67 a bushel.
