<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ElectricRates     05-19 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Electric Rates,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Non-Residential Electricity Rates Fell In Year Ended April
30</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While U.S. commercial and industrial electric
users enjoyed fractionally cheaper rates in the year ended April
30, their foreign counterparts were mostly paying more, a
consulting firm said Thursday.
   In its annual study, National Utility Service Inc. said the
nation's 24 largest investor-owned utilities charged their
non-residential customers an average 6.28 cents per kilowatt-hour
over the 12-month period, compared with 6.29 cents a year earlier.
   That slight decrease compared with an overall inflation rate of
3.9 percent over the same period, the firm said.
   ``Price reductions by some utilities could be attributed to the
recent decline in oil prices,'' said Marvin Lauterbach, executive
vice president of the Park Ridge, N.J.-based firm.
   But Lauterbach warned that the apparent stability masked an
upward price movement by half of the utilities surveyed.
   ``Some of these increases are a direct result of having
industrial and commercial users offset the costs incurred in the
building of nuclear power plants,'' he said. ``Most of these
nuclear power plants still lack a license to operate.''
   Looking to other countries, the firm found that electricity
costs also fell in Ireland, by 4.87 percent, and Belgium, by 1.98
percent. That compared with inflation rates of 2.5 percent and 0.96
percent, respectively.
   In France, the average cost remained constant, while inflation
rose by 2.4 percent, the organization said.
   Countries where businesses paid more for electricity, with
percentages of increases and national inflation rates were:
   _Canada, 8.7 percent, 4.1 percent.
   _Australia, 5.9 percent, 6.8 percent.
   _United Kingdom, 5.5 percent, 3.5 percent.
   _Sweden, 4.6 percent, 5.4 percent.
   _Italy, 3.17 percent, 4.9 percent.
   _Netherlands, 1.1 percent, 0.5 percent.
   _West Germany, 0.2 percent, 0.8 percent.
   National Utility Service is an international utility
cost-consulting firm with offices in 12 nations.
</TEXT>
