<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $3.70 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 425 money market mutual
funds rose $3.70 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $274.12 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a $3.35 billion drop to $270.41 billion in the
funds' assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based
mutual fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 212 general purpose funds rose $1.05 billion to $83.9
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds rose $652 million to
$115.78 billion, and assets of 116 institutional funds rose $2.0
billion to $74.44 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.27 percent from 6.14 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.17 percent from 6.12 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
39 days, down from 40 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
5.70 percent as of Wednesday from 5.68 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.95
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 6.93 percent
the previous week. Yields were 7.28 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
7.23 percent; 7.70 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.65 percent;
and 8.18 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.12 percent.
</TEXT>
