<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NorthropProbe     05-19 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northrop Probe,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Committee Looks at Northrop Payments in Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional subcommittee is trying to
determine if $6.5 million Northrop Corp. invested in a hotel
project in Korea was actually intended to influence sales of the
company's ill-fated F-20 jet fighter, a committee aide said
Thursday.
   A Northrop spokesman denied any violation of the Foreign Corrupt
Practices act, and portrayed the company a victim of fraud by its
Korean partner in the deal.
   Northrop has filed a fraud suit against the Korean company,
which was its partner in a 50-50 joint venture to build a hotel in
Seoul, said Tony Cantafio, a spokesman at the company's Los Angeles
headquarters.
   Northrop never began commercial production of the F-20 because
it failed to win sufficient orders.
   The probe by the U.S. House Energy and Commerce Committee's
subcommittee on investigations focuses on Northrop's payment of
$6.5 million in 1984 to Asia Culture Travel Co.
   Cantafio said the payment was part of a so-called offset program
in which the company was to invest in Korea's economy in return for
receiving the fighter contract. Such arrangements are common among
aerospace companies dealing with developing countries and are
allowed by U.S. law.
   The committee, chaired by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., is probing
whether the payment was intended to buy influence rather than build
a hotel, said a subcommittee staff member who refused to be
identified. It would be a violation of the Corrupt Practices Act if
the company meant the money as payment to individuals.
   One aspect of the arrangement that aroused suspicion, the
Dingell aide said, was that the money intended for the development
company was deposited in a Hong Kong bank account.
   ``We were defrauded by a group of people in Korea,'' Cantafio
said. ``We tried and tried again to get that hotel under way and
when it became evident that the hotel wasn't going to be built we
filed for arbitration, and then we filed this suit.''
   The suit, filed in Korea in December 1987, accuses the Asia
Culture Travel Co. and 12 individuals of defrauding the company.
   The committee also is probing Northrop's payment of $1.5 million
to terminate an agreement with a Korean company that was supposed
to help it market the jet in Korea. The committee staff has
questioned the size of January 1984 payment to the Dong Yang
Express Group because the agreement didn't bring any sales, the
Dingell aide said.
   Cantafio declined to comment on the Dong Yang agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880519-0316 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 1724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ChryslerMeeting     05-19 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler Meeting,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Looking to Improve Profits while Holding Market Share</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. is looking for ways to improve
profits on its auto business without sacrificing sthe market share
it gained by holding down prices and offering aggressive buyer
incentives, Chairman Lee Iacocca told shareholders Thursday.
   ``We are in a real dog fight in this market,'' Iacoccasaid. ``We
intend to price as aggressively as we have to. Our goal is market
share ... We want all the ground we can take.''
   Chrysler increased its share of the U.S. vehicle market to 14.5
percent at the end of April from 13.3 percent a year ago while
industry leader General Motors Corp. continued to lose market share.
   The No. 3 U.S. automaker pushed up its share by keeping its
prices the lowest among the Big Three company and offering ``the
biggest rebates and incentives the world has ever known,'' Iacocca
said.
   The pricing strategies and continuing expenses from Chrysler's
August acquisition of American Motors Corp. have pushed down
profits. A United Auto Workers contract ratified last week will put
further pressure on earnings.
   In addition, Chrysler has increased spending on new product
research and development by 25 percent, or $150 million, in 1988 _
a necessary expense for updating its cars and trucks with new
engines and transmissions in the 1990s.
   Chrysler's immediate capital spending on new products and
facilities will be about $2.8 billion in 1988, nearly even with $3
billion in 1987, Iacocca said.
   Iacocca predicted Chrysler would earn more in the second quarter
than the $183.7 million it earned in the first quarter, but would
not do as well as analysts are projecting because of costs
including continuing incentives.
   ``I can't tell you how long it will be before we can do
something to improve our profit margins _ that is, without giving
up any of the market share we've taken,'' he said.
   Bennett Bidwell, president of product and marketing for Chrysler
Motors Corp., Chrysler's core automaking business, said Thursday
Chrysler is looking at increasing prices in 1989 to improve profits.
   ``At some point in time you reach a point of diminishing
returns'' selling cars and trucks by offering rebates on top of low
prices, Bidwell said.
   For example, the Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant are Chrysler's
best-selling cars. But Chrysler is selling them as part of its
America series with a $6,995 base price and more standard equipment
than in previous years and including the cars in its rebate
campaign.
   ``That doesn't leave much on the table,'' Bidwell said. Chrysler
will replace the K-car after 1989 with the Dodge Spirit and
Plymouth Acclaim, a bigger, more modern version of the same car
that goes on sale in January.
   Despite intense conflict between Chrysler and its 66,000 UAW
workers in the months before and during negotiations on the new
two-year contract, only a handful of UAW representatives other than
President Owen Bieber _ a member of Chrysler's board _ attended the
meeting.
   Mike Allen, an official with UAW Local 624 at Chrysler's New
Process Gear plant in Syracuse, was assured by Iacocca Chrysler
does not plan to sell any of its Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary
plants beyond the four already announced _ three in the Detroit
area and one in Van Wert, Ohio.
   Chrysler wound up in early contract negotiations with the UAW
because it entertained a $2 billion offer for Acustar, which
includes the Syracuse plant. Chrysler turned down the offer after
workers threatened to cripple the company with plant-by-plant
strikes.
   Iacocca said Chrysler had underestimated ``how strongly our
employees felt about remaining part of this Chrysler family.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
