<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet Bjt   05-19 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, Bjt,0663</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks barely broke a two-day losing streak
Thursday in a partial recovery that traders attributed to bargain
shopping and slightly eased tension over inflation, but the outlook
on Wall Street remained bleak.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 56.54 points
on Tuesday and Wednesday and dropped another 25 points in early
trading, rebounded and finished up 7.63 points to 1,958.72. Broader
market indices were mixed.
   To a large degree, the Dow average's behavior echoed movements
in the bond market, which in turn echoed movements in the Commodity
Research Bureau index, a key measure of inflation that tracks
commodity futures prices in Chicago.
   The CRB index rose sharply in the morning, heightening inflation
fears, raising yields in the bond market and depressing stock
prices as bonds became a more attractive alternative to stocks.
   The CRB index later retreated when soybean futures weakened,
easing bond yields and helping the stock market rise.
   ``The funny thing is how the market is so tuned to inflation, it
turned on the commodity price index, which was turned on and off on
soybeans,'' said Lawrence Wachtel, a senior vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``This shows how graphically the stock market has become a
commodity business,'' Wachtel said. ``We're subject to the vagaries
of traders in the pits of Chicago.''
   Some traders said eased yields in the bond market was viewed as
a reason by some investors to buy selected well-known stocks that
had fallen over the previous two sessions, making them potential
bargains.
   But they said any more indications of higher inflation likely
would weaken stocks again. One possibly destabilizing figure was
the Labor Department's consumer price index for April, to be
released Friday morning.
   ``The market is fragile enough to react very negatively to
almost any figure,'' said Joseph Barthel, strategist for the
investment firm Butcher & Singer Inc. ``The market is seeing the
bogeyman when it comes to inflation.''
   Others said they saw little reason to be optimistic about the
market, which has been ignoring signs of economic health that defy
the dire predictions issued after the crash seven months ago.
   ``What we're seeing now are apathetic investors who are using
economic news to get out of stock market,'' said Peter DaPuzzo,
manager of retail equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``The
whole thing now is negative psychology.''
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4-to-3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
843 down, 640 up and 496 unchanged. NYSE volume totaled 165.16
million shares, down from 209.42 million shares in the previous
session.
   Among the most-active blue chip issues, Union Carbide fell 2| to
18\ after announcing plans to cut its dividend and issue more
stock, but other components of the Dow average compensated for
Union Carbide's drop. Woolworth rose 1[ to 51, IBM rose 1{ to 110],
American Express rose | to 23|, and General Electric rose 1 to 40].
   Amfac jumped 6} to 45[ after the company's management offered
$41 a share to buy it. Chrysler fell } to 21} after chairman Lee
Iacocca told shareholders at their annual meeting that the
automaker's second-quarter results probably wouldn't meet analyst
expectations.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 190.26 million shares.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of
5,000 NYSE, American and OTC issues, rose by $6.48 billion.
   The NYSE index rose 0.50 to 143.01.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 1.21 to 292.97,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.22 to 252.57.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1 to
291.79. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
closed at 366.25, down 0.74.
</TEXT>
