<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankBid     05-19 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Asks Fed To Reconsider Bank of NY Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. said Thursday it asked the
Federal Reserve Board to reconsider the conditional approval of
Bank of New York Co.'s hostile takeover bid, in light of a proxy
vote that retained Irving's board of directors.
   Irving is backing a merger with the state-run Banca Commerciale
Italiana SpA, Italy's second largest bank.
   In a letter to the Fed, Irving said the Bank of New York should
be required to file a new application for approval due to changes
it proposed for the takeover bid.
   For one thing, Irving noted, the Bank of New York offered to
raise the stock portion of its bid to 1.675 Bank of New York shares
from 1.575 shares, adding $3.20 per share to the deal and pushing
its value to around $1.2 billion.
   The offer, which includes $15 in cash, would be amended only if
Irving agreed to a negotiated merger.
   In addition, Irving said, Bank of New York's subsequent threat
to buy the Irving shares tendered to it if negotiations failed and
operate the bank as a subsidiary were not in keeping with the
approval by regulators in February.
   Bank of New York said Tuesday it would buy the shares provided
at least two-thirds of Irving's 18.5 million outstanding stock were
tendered. But it also said it would run Irving separately to avoid
activating the company's ``poison pill'' takeover defense.
   Irving contends the Fed did not approve ``a proposal by BNY to
acquire a majority of IBC's shares in the absence of a feasible
plan for a prompt second-step merger of the two institutions.''
   In a response, the Fed asked the Bank of New York to reply to
the issues Irving raised.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said, ``We consider the
questions posed by the Fed to be exactly what we expected.''
   Banca Commerciale is offering $75 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent of the stock outstanding, for a total
of about $707 million. The bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that would include asset sales, cost-cutting measures and a
$10-a-share special cash dividend.
</TEXT>
