<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 2311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brazil-Industry     05-19 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Industry,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Announces New Industrial Liberalization Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Sarney on Thursday
announced a plan to remove restrictions on imports and exports, and
``open Brazil to international markets.''
   The plan ends a decades-old policy of import-substitution, under
which the government provided hefty fiscal incentives for companies
that produced industrial goods previously found only on
international markets.
   ``Our new industrial policy signals the democratization of
Brazilian industry,'' Sarney told journalists and government
ministers. ``The country's new-found freedom hadn't arrived in the
industrial or economic sectors, they hadn't felt the benefits of
our new-found democracy.''
   Sarney said the new measures would cut through thick Brazilian
bureaucracy and clarify the government's position in the future.
   The measures would:
   _Free up imports, with some exceptions. Imports have been
restricted to build the trade surplus and national industry, but
now any company can buy most goods on international markets as long
it pays hefty import dues.
   _Revoke all fiscal incentives for industry, except in the area
of technology. Companies working in this area can receive tax cuts
of up to 8 percent.
   _Ease export of industrial goods, with less paperwork and less
government control.
   _Create a five-minister commission to govern industrial policy.
   Details of how the policy was to be implemented were to be
worked out at a later date.
   ``The new policy will modernize Brazil and open the economy to
international markets,'' Sarney said.
   Initial business response to the new measures that reversed a
40-year policy of government-led growth was favorable.
   ``Industry now has clear rules and freedom to grow with less
government intervention,'' business leader Andre Beer told TV
Globo, the nation's largest private network.
   Brazil returned to civilian government in March 1985, after 21
years of military rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
