<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Higher In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Nikkei morning close, later
dollar trading, comments. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was slightly stronger against the
Japanese yen in morning trading Friday, while stock prices edged
higher.
   The dollar opened trading at 124.85 yen, up from Thursday's
close of 124.80 yen, and by midmorning was changing hands at the
124.88-yen level.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 29.57 points to finish the morning session
at 27,402.81. The widely-followed market index had fallen a sharp
394.34 points on Thursday.
   ``Because a long weekend is nearing, traders don't seem to be
enthusiastic about setting up a new position,'' said Hiroaki
Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank.
   Markets in Europe will be closed Monday in observance of
Whitsunday.
   ``The strong dollar lifted share prices, but not as much as the
market expected,'' added Keiichi Nishida of Kidder Peabody's Tokyo
office.
   ``But overall trading was slow because of a concern over
inflation and also ahead of a long weekend,'' he said.
