<FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Navistar     05-19 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Navistar,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navistar Posts 49 Percent Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong demand for medium- and heavy-duty trucks
boosted Navistar International Corp.'s second quarter profit by 49
percent from a year earlier, the truck manufacturer said Wednesday.
   Navistar posted net income of $70 million, or 24 cents a share,
for the three months ended April 30. That compared with a profit of
$47 million, or 15 cents a share, for the same period a year
earlier.
   Sales increased 13 percent to $1.05 billion from $930 million in
the second quarter of 1987, the Chicago-based manufacturer stated.
   Navistar said workers at its Springfield, Ohio, assembly plant
have been working overtime due to strong demand.
   The company said it would increase its heavy truck production
schedules by about 9 percent and its medium-duty truck production
rates by 3 percent on Monday, and was exploring other options to
further expand production.
   Increased industrial production and inter-city freight tonnage
were important factors in Navistar's second-quarter performance,
James C. Cotting, chairman and chief executive, stated.
   But higher prices for aluminum and steel cut into the company's
profit margin, as did production phase-in costs at Navistar's new
foundry in Indianapolis and new paint plant in Springfield, Ohio,
Cotting said.
   Results included a $15 million gain from partial recovery of an
Australian investment that had previously been written off. In
addition, the results included a reduction in the carrying value of
the company's investment in Tenneco preferred stock to $105 million
from $120 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
